{"title_page": "Demiurge", "text_new": "{{short description|An artisan-like figure responsible for fashioning and maintaining the physical universe}}\n{{about|philosophical concept of a Universal Fashioner|other uses|Demiurge (disambiguation)}}\n{{God| expanded=representations}}\n{{platonism}}\nIn the [[Platonism|Platonic]], [[Neopythagorean]], [[Middle Platonism|Middle Platonic]], and [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonic]] schools of philosophy, the '''demiurge''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|\u025b|m|i|.|\u025cr|d\u0292}}) is an [[artisan]]-like figure responsible for fashioning and maintaining the physical universe. The [[Gnosticism|Gnostics]] adopted the term \"demiurge\". Although a fashioner, the demiurge is not necessarily the same as the creator figure in the [[monotheism|monotheistic]] sense, because the demiurge itself and the material from which the demiurge fashions the universe are both considered to be consequences of something else. Depending on the system, they may be considered to be either uncreated and eternal or the product of some other entity.\n\nThe word \"demiurge\" is an English word derived from ''demiurgus'', a [[List of Latinised names|Latinised]] form of the [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|grc|\u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c2}} or ''d\u0113miurg\u00f3s''. It was originally a common noun meaning \"craftsman\" or \"artisan,\" but gradually came to mean \"producer,\" and eventually \"creator.\" The philosophical usage and the proper noun derive from [[Timaeus (dialogue)|Plato's ''Timaeus'']], written {{circa}}&nbsp;360 BC, where the demiurge is presented as the creator of the universe. The demiurge is also described as a creator in the Platonic ({{circa}}&nbsp;310\u201390 BC) and Middle Platonic ({{circa}}&nbsp;90 BC-AD 300) philosophical traditions. In the various branches of the Neoplatonic school (third century onwards), the demiurge is the fashioner of the real, perceptible world after the model of the [[Theory of Forms|<!-- capitalized-->Ideas]], but (in most Neoplatonic systems) is still not itself \"[[Form of the Good|the One]].\" In the arch-[[Dualistic cosmology|dualist]] ideology of the various Gnostic systems, the material universe is evil, while the non-material world is good. According to some strains of Gnosticism, the demiurge is [[Evil|malevolent]], as it is linked to the material world. In others, including the teaching of [[Valentinianism|Valentinus]], the demiurge is simply ignorant or misguided.\n\n==Platonism and neoplatonism==\n[[Plato]], as the speaker Timaeus, refers to the Demiurge frequently in the [[Socratic dialogue]] ''[[Timaeus (dialogue)|Timaeus]]'' (28a [[wikt:ff.#Abbreviation|ff.]]), {{circa}}&nbsp;360 BC. The main character refers to the Demiurge as the entity who \"fashioned and shaped\" the material world. Timaeus describes the Demiurge as unreservedly [[:wikt:benevolence|benevolent]], and so it desires a world as good as possible. Plato's work ''Timaeus'' is a philosophical reconciliation of [[Hesiod]]'s cosmology in his ''[[Theogony]]'', [[syncretism|syncretically]] reconciling Hesiod to [[Homer]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Python: A Study of Delphic Myth and Its Origin|year=1974|first=Joseph|last=Fontenrose|page=226|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h56ansk4SyQC&pg=PA226 | isbn=978-0-8196-0285-5 | publisher=Biblo & Tannen Publishers}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Chorology: On Beginning in Plato's Timaeus|year=1999|first=John|last=Sallis|page=86|isbn=0-253-21308-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gS_9aQ5mYKgC&pg=PA86 | publisher=Indiana University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The mythology of ancient Greece and Italy|first=Thomas|last=Keightley|year=1838|page=[https://archive.org/details/mythologyancien04keiggoog/page/n90 44]|publisher=Oxford University|url=https://archive.org/details/mythologyancien04keiggoog|quote=theogony timaeus.}}</ref>\n\n===Middle Platonism===\nIn [[Numenius of Apamea|Numenius]]'s [[Neo-Pythagorean]] and Middle Platonist [[cosmogony]], the Demiurge is second God as the ''[[nous]]'' or thought of intelligibles and sensibles.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Pythagoras and the Pythagoreans|last=Kahn|first=Charles|publisher=Hacket Publishing|year=|isbn=978-0-872205758|location=Indianapolis|pages=124}}</ref>\n\n===Neoplatonism===\n[[Plotinus]] and the later Platonists worked to clarify the Demiurge. To Plotinus, the second [[Emanationism|emanation]] represents an uncreated second cause (see [[Pythagoras]]' [[Dyad (symbol)|Dyad]]). Plotinus sought to reconcile Aristotle's ''[[energeia]]'' with Plato's Demiurge,<ref name=\"Karamanolis2006\">{{cite book|last=Karamanolis|first=George|year= 2006|title=Plato and Aristotle in Agreement?: Platonists on Aristotle from Antiochus to Porphyry|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-926456-2|page=240}}</ref> which, as Demiurge and mind (''nous''), is a critical component in the [[ontological]] construct of human consciousness used to explain and clarify [[substance theory]] within [[Platonic realism]] (also called [[idealism]]). In order to reconcile Aristotelian with Platonian philosophy,<ref name=\"Karamanolis2006\" /> Plotinus metaphorically identified the demiurge (or ''nous'') within the [[Pantheon (gods)|pantheon of the Greek Gods]] as [[Zeus]].<ref>The ordering principle is twofold; there is a principle known as the Demiurge, and there is the Soul of the All; the appellation \"Zeus\" is sometimes applied to the Demiurge and sometimes to the principle conducting the universe.{{cn|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Henology====\nThe first and highest aspect of God is described by Plato as the One (\u03a4\u1f78 \u1f1d\u03bd, \"To Hen\"), the source, or the [[Monad (philosophy)|Monad]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dionysius the Areopagite and the Neoplatonist Tradition: Despoiling the Hellenes|last=Wear|first=Sarah|last2=Dillon|first2=John|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2013|isbn=9780754603856|location=Burlington, VT|pages=15}}</ref> This is the God above the Demiurge, and manifests through the actions of the Demiurge. The Monad [[Emanationism|emanated]] the demiurge or ''[[Nous]]'' (consciousness) from its \"indeterminate\" vitality due to the monad being so abundant that it overflowed back onto itself, causing self-reflection.<ref>{{cite book|title=Neoplatonism and Gnosticism|year=1992|editor1-first=Richard T.|editor1-last=Wallis|editor2-first=Jay|editor2-last=Bregman|others=[[International Society for Neoplatonic Studies]]|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WSbrLPup7wYC&pg=PA55&lpg=PA55&dq=Anti-Gnostic+Polemic+Francisco+Garcia+Bazan+translated+from+Spanish+by+Winifred+T.+Slater+Nous+as+a+%22Second+God%22+According+to+Plotinus+In+Enneads#PPA55,M1 |isbn=978-0-7914-1337-1 |publisher=SUNY Press}}</ref> This self-reflection of the indeterminate vitality was referred to by Plotinus as the \"Demiurge\" or creator. The second principle is organization in its reflection of the [[Sentience|nonsentient]] force or ''[[Potentiality and actuality|dynamis]]'', also called the one or the Monad. The dyad is ''energeia'' emanated by the one that is then the work, process or activity called ''nous'', Demiurge, mind, consciousness that organizes the indeterminate vitality into the experience called the material world, universe, cosmos. [[Plotinus]] also elucidates the equation of matter with nothing or non-being in ''[[The Enneads]]''<ref>\"Matter is therefore a non-existent\"; Plotinus, ''Ennead'' 2, Tractate 4 Section 16.</ref> which more correctly is to express the concept of [[idealism]] or that there is not anything or anywhere outside of the \"mind\" or ''nous'' (c.f. [[pantheism]]).\n\nPlotinus' form of [[Platonic idealism]] is to treat the Demiurge, ''nous'' as the contemplative faculty (''ergon'') within man which orders the force (''dynamis'') into conscious reality.<ref>[[Schopenhauer]] wrote of this Neoplatonist philosopher: \"With Plotinus there even appears, probably for the first time in [[Western philosophy]], idealism that had long been current in the East even at that time, for it taught (Enneads, iii, lib. vii, c.10) that the soul has made the world by stepping from eternity into time, with the explanation: 'For there is for this universe no other place than the soul or mind' (''neque est alter hujus universi locus quam anima''), indeed the ideality of time is expressed in the words: 'We should not accept time outside the soul or mind' (''oportet autem nequaquam extra animam tempus accipere'').\" (Parerga and Paralipomena, Volume I, \"Fragments for the History of Philosophy,\" \u00a7&nbsp;7) Similarly, Professor Ludwig Noir\u00e9 wrote: \"For the first time in Western philosophy we find idealism proper in Plotinus (Enneads, iii, 7, 10), where he says, 'The only space or place of the world is the soul,' and 'Time must not be assumed to exist outside the soul.'\" [5] It is worth noting, however, that like Plato but unlike Schopenhauer and other modern philosophers, Plotinus does not worry about whether or how we can get beyond our ideas to know external objects.</ref> In this, he claimed to reveal Plato's true meaning: a doctrine he learned from Platonic tradition that did not appear outside the academy or in Plato's text. This tradition of creator God as ''nous'' (the manifestation of consciousness), can be validated in the works of pre-Plotinus philosophers such as [[Numenius of Apamea|Numenius]], as well as a connection between Hebrew and Platonic cosmology (see also [[Philo]]).<ref>[[Numenius of Apamea]] was reported to have asked, \"What else is Plato than Moses speaking Greek?\" Fr. 8 Des Places.</ref>\n\nThe Demiurge of Neoplatonism is the ''Nous'' (mind of God), and is one of the three ordering principles:\n* ''[[Arche]]'' (Gr. \"beginning\") \u2013 the source of all things,\n* ''[[Logos]]'' (Gr. \"reason/cause\") \u2013 the underlying order that is hidden beneath appearances,\n* ''[[:wikt:harmonia|Harmonia]]'' (Gr. \"harmony\") \u2013 numerical [[ratios]] in [[mathematics]].\n\nBefore Numenius of Apamea and Plotinus' ''[[Enneads]]'', no Platonic works ontologically clarified the Demiurge from the [[allegory]] in Plato's ''Timaeus''. The idea of Demiurge was, however, addressed before Plotinus in the works of Christian writer [[Justin Martyr]] who built his understanding of the Demiurge on the works of Numenius.{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\n====Iamblichus====\n{{See also|Panentheism}}\nLater, the Neoplatonist [[Iamblichus of Chalcis|Iamblichus]] changed the role of the \"One,\" effectively altering the role of the Demiurge as second cause or dyad, which was one of the reasons that Iamblichus and his teacher [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]] came into conflict.\n\nThe figure of the Demiurge emerges in the theoretic of Iamblichus, which conjoins the transcendent, incommunicable \u201cOne,\u201d or Source. Here, at the summit of this system, the Source and Demiurge (material realm) coexist via the process of ''[[henosis]]''.<ref>See [http://www.theandros.com/iamblichus.html Theurgy, Iamblichus and henosis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109100359/http://www.theandros.com/iamblichus.html |date=2010-01-09 }}.</ref>\nIamblichus describes the One as a monad whose first principle or emanation is intellect (''nous''), while among \"the many\" that follow it there is a second, super-existent \"One\" that is the producer of intellect or soul (''psyche'').\n\nThe \"One\" is further separated into spheres of intelligence; the first and superior sphere is objects of thought, while the latter sphere is the domain of thought. Thus, a [[wikt:triad#Noun|triad]] is formed of the [[perception|intelligible]] ''nous'', the [[noesis|intellective]] ''nous'', and the ''[[Psyche (psychology)|psyche]]'' in order to reconcile further the various Hellenistic philosophical schools of [[Aristotle]]'s [[Actus et potentia|''actus'' and ''potentia'']] (actuality and potentiality) of the [[unmoved mover]] and Plato's Demiurge.\n\nThen within this intellectual triad Iamblichus assigns the third rank to the Demiurge, identifying it with the perfect or Divine ''nous'' with the intellectual triad being promoted to a ''hebdomad'' (pure intellect).\n\nIn the theoretic of Plotinus, ''nous'' produces nature through intellectual mediation, thus the intellectualizing gods are followed by a triad of psychic gods.\n\n==Gnosticism==\n{{Split section |Yaldabaoth|discuss={{TALKPAGENAME}}#Split proposed |date=November 2018}}\n{{gnosticism}}\n[[Gnosticism]] presents a distinction between the highest, unknowable God or [[Aeon (Gnosticism)|Supreme Being]] and the demiurgic \"creator\" of the material. Several systems of Gnostic thought present the Demiurge as antagonistic to the will of the Supreme Being: his act of creation occurs in an unconscious semblance of the divine model, and thus is fundamentally flawed, or else is formed with the malevolent intention of entrapping aspects of the divine ''in'' materiality. Thus, in such systems, the Demiurge acts as a solution to (or, at least possibly, the problem or cause that gives rise to){{citation needed|date=March 2014}} the [[problem of evil]].\n\n===Mythos===\nOne Gnostic [[mythos]] describes the declination of aspects of the divine into human form. [[Sophia (Gnosticism)|Sophia]] (Greek: \u03a3\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03b1, lit. \"wisdom\"), the Demiurge's mother and partial aspect of the divine ''[[Pleroma]]'' or \"Fullness,\" desired to create something apart from the [[Absolute (philosophy)|divine totality]], without the receipt of divine assent. In this act of separate creation, she gave birth to the monstrous Demiurge and, being ashamed of her deed, wrapped him in a cloud and created a throne for him within it. The Demiurge, isolated, did not behold his mother, nor anyone else, and concluded that only he existed, ignorant of the superior levels of reality.\n\nThe Demiurge, having received a portion of power from his mother, sets about a work of creation in unconscious imitation of the superior [[Pleroma|Pleromatic]] realm: He frames the [[seven heavens]], as well as all material and animal things, according to forms furnished by his mother; working, however, blindly and ignorant even of the existence of the mother who is the source of all his energy. He is blind to all that is spiritual, but he is king over the other two provinces. The word ''d\u0113miurgos'' properly describes his relation to the material; he is the ''father'' of that which is animal-like himself.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103105.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 5, 1.]</ref>\n\nThus Sophia's power becomes enclosed within the material forms of humanity, themselves entrapped within the material universe. In essence, the goal of Gnostic movements was typically the awakening of this spark, which permitted a return by the subject to the superior, non-material realities, which were its primal source.\n\n===Angels===\n[[Psalm 82]] begins ({{bibleref2|Psa|82:1|NET|verse 1}}), \"God stands in the assembly of [[El (deity)|El]] {{bracket|[[Septuagint|LXX]]: the assembly of gods}}, amid the gods he renders judgment,\" indicating a plurality of gods. However, it does not indicate that these gods were co-actors in creation. [[Philo]] had inferred from the expression \"Let us make man\" of the [[Book of Genesis]] that God had used other beings as assistants in the creation of man, and he explains in this way why man is capable of vice as well as virtue, ascribing the origin of the latter to God, of the former to His helpers in the work of creation.<ref>{{quote|It is on this account that Moses says, at the creation of man alone that God said, \"Let us make man,\" which expression shows an assumption of other beings to himself as assistants, so that God, the governor of all things, might have all the blameless intentions and actions of man when he does right attributed to him; and that his other assistants might bear the imputation of his contrary actions.|{{cite web |title=Philo: On the Creation, XXIV |url=http://www.earlyjewishwritings.com/text/philo/book1.html |website=www.earlyjewishwritings.com}}}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest Gnostic sects ascribe the work of creation to angels, some of them using the same passage in Genesis.<ref>[[Justin Martyr]], ''[[Dialogue with Trypho]]''. c. 67.</ref> So [[Irenaeus]] tells<ref>Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 23, 1.</ref> of the system of [[Simon Magus]],<ref>Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 23, 5.</ref> of the system of [[Menander (gnostic)|Menander]],<ref>Irenaeus, i. 24, 1.</ref> of the system of Saturninus, in which the number of these angels is reckoned as seven, and<ref>Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 25.</ref> of the system of [[Carpocrates]]. In the report of the system of [[Basilides]],<ref>Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 24, 4.</ref> we are told that our world was made by the angels who occupy the lowest heaven; but special mention is made of their chief, who is said to have been the [[God in Judaism|God of the Jews]], to have led that people out of the land of [[Egypt]], and to have given them their law. The prophecies are ascribed not to the chief but to the other world-making angels.\n\nThe Latin translation, confirmed by [[Hippolytus of Rome]],<ref>Hippolytus, ''[[Refutation of All Heresies]]''. vii. 33.</ref> makes [[Irenaeus]] state that according to [[Cerinthus]] (who shows [[Ebionites|Ebionite]] influence), creation was made by a power quite separate from the Supreme God and ignorant of Him. [[Theodoret]],<ref>Theodoret, ''Haer. Fab''. ii. 3.</ref> who here copies Irenaeus, turns this into the plural number \"powers,\" and so [[Epiphanius of Salamis]]<ref>Epiphanius, ''[[Panarion]]'', 28.</ref> represents Cerinthus as agreeing with Carpocrates in the doctrine that angels made the world.\n\n===Yaldabaoth===\n[[File:Lion-faced deity.jpg|thumb|right|150px|A lion-faced deity found on a Gnostic gem in [[Bernard de Montfaucon]]'s ''L'antiquit\u00e9 expliqu\u00e9e et repr\u00e9sent\u00e9e en figures'' may be a depiction of the Demiurge.]]\n\nIn the [[Ophites|Ophite]] and [[Sethians|Sethian]] systems, which have many affinities with the teachings of Valentinus, the making of the world is ascribed to a company of seven [[archon (Gnosticism)|archons]], whose names are given, but still more prominent is their chief, \"Yaldabaoth\" (also known as \"Yaltabaoth\" or \"Ialdabaoth\").\n\nIn the ''[[Apocryphon of John]]'' {{circa}}&nbsp; AD 120\u2013180, the demiurge arrogantly declares that he has made the world by himself:\n<blockquote>\nNow the [[archon]] [\"ruler\"], who is weak, has three names. The first name is Yaltabaoth, the second is Saklas [\"fool\"], and the third is [[Samael]]. And he is impious in his arrogance, which is in him. For he said, 'I am God, and there is no other God beside me,' for he is ignorant of his strength, the place from which he had come.<ref>\"Apocryphon of John,\" translation by Frederik Wisse in ''The Nag Hammadi Library''. Accessed online at [http://www.gnosis.org/naghamm/apocjn.html gnosis.org]</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe is Demiurge and maker of man, but as a ray of light from above enters the body of a man and gives him a soul, Yaldabaoth is filled with envy; he tries to limit man's knowledge by forbidding him the fruit of knowledge in paradise. At the consummation of all things, all light will return to the [[Pleroma]]. But Yaldabaoth, the Demiurge, with the material world, will be cast into the lower depths.<ref name=\"Catholic\">{{Catholic|wstitle=Demiurge|inline=yes}}</ref>\n\nYaldabaoth is frequently called \"the Lion-faced,\" ''leontoeides'', and is said to have the body of a serpent. The demiurge is also<ref>Hipp. ''Ref''. vi. 32, p.&nbsp;191.</ref> described as having a fiery nature, applying the words of Moses to him: \"the Lord our God is a burning and consuming fire.\" Hippolytus claims that Simon used a similar description.<ref>Hipp. ''Ref''. vi. 9.</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Pistis Sophia]]'', Yaldabaoth has already sunk from his high estate and resides in Chaos, where, with his forty-nine demons, he tortures wicked souls in boiling rivers of the pitch, and with other punishments (pp.&nbsp;257, 382). He is an archon with the face of a lion, half flame, and half-darkness.\n\nUnder the name of ''Nebro'' (rebel), Yaldabaoth is called an angel in the [[apocryphal]] ''[[Gospel of Judas]]''. He is first mentioned in \"The Cosmos, Chaos, and the Underworld\" as one of the twelve angels to come \"into being [to] rule over chaos and the [underworld].\" He comes from heaven, and it is said his \"face flashed with fire and [his] appearance was defiled with blood.\" Nebro creates six angels in addition to the angel [[Saklas]] to be his assistants. These six, in turn, create another twelve angels \"with each one receiving a portion in the heavens.\"\n\n====Names====\n[[File:Leontocephaline-Ostia.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|right|Drawing of the lion-headed figure found at the [[Mithraeum]] of C.&nbsp;Valerius Heracles and sons, dedicated 190&nbsp;CE at [[Ostia Antica]], Italy (CIMRM 312).]]\n\nThe most probable derivation of the name \"Yaldabaoth\" was given by [[Johann Karl Ludwig Gieseler]]. Giesler believed the name was derived from the Aramaic ''yald\u0101 bahuth'', {{lang|arc|\u05d9\u05dc\u05d3\u05d0\u05d1\u05d4\u05d5\u05ea}}, meaning \"Son of Chaos.\" However, [[Gilles Quispel]] notes:\n{{quote|[[Gershom Scholem]], the third genius in this field, more specifically the genius of precision, had taught us that some of us were wrong when they believed that Jaldabaoth means \"son of chaos\" because the [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] word ''bahutha'' in the sense of chaos only existed in the imagination of the author of a well-known dictionary. This is a pity because this name would suit the demiurge risen from chaos to a nicety. And perhaps the author of the ''[[On the Origin of the World|Untitled Document]]'' did not know Aramaic and also supposed as we did once, that ''baoth'' had something to do with ''[[Tohu wa-bohu|tohuwabohu]]'', one of the few Hebrew words that everybody knows. ... It would seem then that the Orphic view of the demiurge was integrated into Jewish Gnosticism even before the redaction of the myth contained in the original ''[[Apocryphon of John]]''. ... [[Phanes]] is represented with the mask of a ''lion's'' head on his breast, while from his sides, the heads of a ram and a buck are budding forth: his body is encircled by a snake. This type was accepted by the [[Mithraism|Mithras mysteries]], to indicate [[Aion (deity)|Aion]], the new year, and Mithras, whose numerical value is 365. Sometimes he is also identified with Jao Adonai, the creator of the Hebrews. His hieratic attitude indicates Egyptian origin. The same is true of [[Mithraism#lion-headed figure|the monstrous figure with the head of a lion]], which symbolises Time, [[Chronos]], in Mithraism; Alexandrian origin of this type is probable.<ref>{{cite book |last=Quispel |first=Gilles |authorlink=Gilles Quispel |page=64 |title=Gnostica, Judaica, Catholica: Collected Essays of Gilles Quispel |editor1-first= Johannes |editor1-last=Van Oort |isbn=978-90-04-13945-9 |year=2008 |publisher=Koninklijke Brill NV |location=Leiden}}</ref>}}\n\n\"[[Samael]]\" literally means \"Blind God\" or \"God of the Blind\" in Hebrew ({{hebrew|\u05e1\u05de\u05d0\u05dc}}). This being is considered not only blind, or ignorant of its own origins but may, in addition, be evil; its name is also found in [[Judaism]] as the [[Death (personification)#Death (angels) in religion|Angel of Death]] and in Christian [[demon]]ology. This link to the Judeo-Christian tradition leads to a further comparison with [[Satan]]. Another alternative title for the demiurge is \"Saklas,\" Aramaic for \"fool.\"\n\nThe angelic name \"[[Ariel (angel)|Ariel]]\" (meaning \"the lion of God\" in Hebrew)<ref>{{cite book |title=Jewish Gnosticism, Merkabah Mysticism, and Talmudic Tradition |first=Gershom |last=Scholem |publisher=Jewish Theological Seminary of America |year=1965 |page=72}}</ref> has also been used to refer to the Demiurge and is called his \"perfect\" name;<ref>{{cite book |author=Robert McLachlan Wilson |title=Nag Hammadi and gnosis: Papers read at the First International Congress of Coptology |year=1976 |publisher=BRILL |pages=21\u201323 |quote=''Therefore his esoteric name is Jaldabaoth, whereas the perfect call him Ariel, because he has the appearance of a lion.''}}</ref> in some Gnostic lore, Ariel has been called an ancient or original name for Ialdabaoth.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gustav Davidson|title=A dictionary of angels: including the fallen angels |year=1994 |publisher=Scrollhouse |page=54}}</ref> The name has also been inscribed on amulets as \"Ariel Ialdabaoth\",<ref>{{cite book|author=David M Gwynn|title=Religious Diversity in Late Antiquity |year=2010 |publisher=BRILL |page=448}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Campbell Bonner |title=An Amulet of the Ophite Gnostics |year=1949 |publisher=The American School of Classical Studies at Athens, Hesperia Supplements, Vol. 8|pages=43\u201346}}</ref> and the figure of the archon inscribed with \"Aariel\".<ref>{{cite book |author1=Gilles Quispel |author2=R. van den Broek |author-link2=Roel van den Broek |author3=Maarten Jozef Vermaseren |title=Studies in gnosticism and hellenistic religions |year=1981 |publisher=BRILL |pages=40\u201341}}</ref>\n\n===Marcion===\nAccording to [[Marcion of Sinope|Marcion]], the title God was given to the Demiurge, who was to be sharply distinguished from the higher Good God. The former was ''d\u00edkaios,'' severely just, the latter ''agath\u00f3s,'' or loving-kind; the former was the \"god of this world\" ({{bibleverse|2|Corinthians|4:4}}), the God of the [[Old Testament]], the latter the true God of the [[New Testament]]. Christ, though in reality, the Son of the Good God, pretended to be the Messiah of the Demiurge, the better to spread the truth concerning His heavenly Father. The true believer in Christ entered into God's kingdom; the unbeliever remained forever the slave of the Demiurge.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/>\n\n===Valentinus===\nIt is in the [[Valentinianism|system of Valentinus]] that the name ''D\u0113miurgos'' is used, which occurs nowhere in Irenaeus except in connection with the Valentinian system; we may reasonably conclude that it was Valentinus who adopted from Platonism the use of this word. When it is employed by other Gnostics either, it is not used in a technical sense, or its use has been borrowed from Valentinus. But it is only the name that can be said to be specially Valentinian; the personage intended by it corresponds more or less closely with the Yaldabaoth of the Ophites, the [[Abraxas|great Archon]] of Basilides, the Elohim of [[Justin (gnostic)|Justinus]], etc.\n\nThe Valentinian theory elaborates that from Achamoth (''he k\u00e1t\u014d soph\u00eda'' or lower wisdom) three kinds of substance take their origin, the spiritual (''pneumatiko\u00ed''), the animal (''psychiko\u00ed'') and the material (''hyliko\u00ed''). The Demiurge belongs to the second kind, as he was the offspring of a union of Achamoth with the matter.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/><ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103105.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 5.]</ref> And as Achamoth herself was only the daughter of ''Soph\u00eda'' the last of the thirty Aeons, the Demiurge was distant by many emanations from the Propat\u00f4r, or Supreme God.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/>\n\nIn creating this world out of Chaos, the Demiurge was unconsciously influenced for good; and the universe, to the surprise even of its Maker, became almost perfect. The Demiurge regretted even its slight imperfection, and as he thought himself the Supreme God, he attempted to remedy this by sending a Messiah. To this Messiah, however, was actually united with Jesus the Saviour, Who redeemed men. These are either ''hyliko\u00ed'' or ''pneumatiko\u00ed''.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/>\n\nThe first, or material men, will return to the grossness of matter and finally be consumed by fire; the second, or animal men, together with the Demiurge, will enter a middle state, neither Pleroma nor ''hyle''; the purely spiritual men will be completely freed from the influence of the Demiurge and together with the Saviour and Achamoth, his spouse, will enter the Pleroma divested of body (''hyle'') and soul (''psych\u00e9'').<ref name=\"Catholic\"/><ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103106.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 6.]</ref> In this most common form of Gnosticism the Demiurge had an inferior though not intrinsically evil function in the universe as the head of the animal, or psychic world.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/>\n\n===The devil===\nOpinions on [[the devil]], and his relationship to the Demiurge, varied. The Ophites held that he and his demons constantly oppose and thwart the human race, as it was on their account the devil was cast down into this world.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103130.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 30, 8.]</ref> According to one variant of the Valentinian system, the Demiurge is also the maker, out of the appropriate substance, of an order of ''spiritual'' beings, the devil, the prince of this world, and his angels. But the devil, as being a ''spirit'' of wickedness, is able to recognize the higher spiritual world, of which his maker the Demiurge, who is the only animal, has no real knowledge. The devil resides in this lower world, of which he is the prince, the Demiurge in the heavens; his mother Sophia in the middle region, above the heavens and below the Pleroma.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103105.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 5, 4.]</ref>\n\nThe Valentinian [[Heracleon]]<ref>[http://www.gnosis.org/library/fragh.htm Heracleon, Frag. 20.]</ref> interpreted the devil as the ''principle'' of evil, that of ''hyle'' (matter). As he writes in his commentary on {{bibleverse||John|4:21}},\n<blockquote>The mountain represents the Devil, or his world since the Devil was one part of the whole of matter, but the world is the total mountain of evil, a deserted dwelling place of beasts, to which all who lived before the law and all Gentiles render worship. But Jerusalem represents the creation of the Creator whom the Jews worship. ... You then who are spiritual should worship neither the creation nor the Craftsman, but the Father of Truth. </blockquote>\n\nThis vilification of the creator was held to be inimical to Christianity by the early fathers of the church. In refuting the beliefs of the gnostics, [[Irenaeus]] stated that \"Plato is proved to be more religious than these men, for he allowed that the same God was both just and good, having power over all things, and himself executing judgment.\"<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103325.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', iii. 25.]</ref>\n\n===Cathars===\n[[Catharism]] inherited their idea of Satan as the creator of the evil world from Gnosticism. Quispel writes,\n\n{{quote|There is a direct link between ancient Gnosticism and Catharism. The Cathars held that the creator of the world, Satanael, had usurped the name of God, but that he had subsequently been unmasked and told that he was not really God.<ref>Quispel, Gilles and Van Oort, Johannes (2008), p. 143.</ref>}}\n\n==Neoplatonism and Gnosticism==\n{{Main|Neoplatonism and Gnosticism}}\n{{Wikisource|1=Enneads/Against the Gnostics; or, Against Those That Affirm the Creator of the Cosmos and the Cosmos Itself to be Evil|2=Against the Gnostics; or, Against Those That Affirm the Creator of the Cosmos and the Cosmos Itself to be Evil}}\nGnosticism attributed falsehood or evil to the concept of the Demiurge or creator. However, in some Gnostic traditions, the creator is from a fallen, ignorant, or lesser\u2014rather than evil\u2014perspective, such as that of [[Valentinius]].\n\n===Plotinus===\nThe Neoplatonic philosopher [[Plotinus]] addressed within his works Gnosticism's conception of the Demiurge, which he saw as un-[[Ancient Greece|Hellenic]] and blasphemous to the Demiurge or creator of Plato. Plotinus, along with his teacher [[Ammonius Saccas]], was the founder of [[Neoplatonism]].<ref>John D. Turner. [https://web.archive.org/web/20140816004048/http://www.unl.edu/classics/faculty/turner/triadaft.htm Neoplatonism].</ref> In the ninth [[tractate]] of the second of his ''Enneads'', Plotinus criticizes his opponents for their appropriation of ideas from Plato:\n\n{{quote|From Plato come their punishments, their rivers of the underworld and the changing from body to body; as for the plurality they assert in the Intellectual Realm\u2014the Authentic Existent, the Intellectual-Principle, ''the Second Creator and the Soul''\u2014all this is taken over from the Timaeus.|Ennead 2.9.vi; emphasis added from [[A. H. Armstrong]]'s introduction to Ennead 2.9}}\n\nOf note here is the remark concerning the second [[hypostasis (philosophy and religion)|hypostasis]] or Creator and third hypostasis or [[Anima mundi|World Soul]]. Plotinus criticizes his opponents for \"all the novelties through which they seek to establish a philosophy of their own\" which, he declares, \"have been picked up outside of the truth\";<ref name=\"sacred-texts\">\"For, in sum, a part of their doctrine comes from Plato; all the novelties through which they seek to establish a philosophy of their own have been picked up outside of the truth.\" Plotinus, \"Against the Gnostics,\" [http://www.sacred-texts.com/cla/plotenn/enn161.htm ''Ennead'' II, 9, 6.]</ref> they attempt to conceal rather than admit their indebtedness to ancient philosophy, which they have corrupted by their extraneous and misguided embellishments. Thus their understanding of the Demiurge is similarly flawed in comparison to Plato\u2019s original intentions.\n\nWhereas Plato's Demiurge is good wishing good on his creation, Gnosticism contends that the Demiurge is not only the originator of evil but is evil as well. Hence the title of Plotinus' refutation: \"Against Those That Affirm the Creator of the Kosmos and the Kosmos Itself to be Evil\" (generally quoted as \"Against the Gnostics\"). Plotinus argues of the disconnect or great barrier that is created between the ''nous'' or the mind's [[noumenon]] (see [[Heraclitus]]) and the material world ([[phenomenon]]) by believing the material world is evil.\n\nThe majority of scholars tend<ref>{{cite book|title=Plotinus: Enneads II|edition=Loeb Classical Library|author=Plotinus, Arthur Hilary Armstrong (trans.)|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1966|quote=From this point to the end of ch. 12 Plotinus is attacking a Gnostic myth known to us best at present in the form it took in the system of Valentinus. The Mother, Sophia-Achamoth, produced as a result of the complicated sequence of events which followed the fall of the higher Sophia, and her offspring the Demiurge, the inferior and ignorant maker of the material universe, are Valentinian figures; cp. Irenaeus, ''[[On the Detection and Overthrow of the So-Called Gnosis|Adversus haereses]]'' 1.4 and 5. Valentinius had been in Rome, and there is nothing improbable in the presence of Valentinians there in the time of Plotinus. But the evidence in the ''Life'' ch. 16 suggests that the Gnostics in Plotinus's circle belonged rather to the older group called Sethians or [[Archontics]], related to the [[Ophites]] or [[Barbelo]]gnostics: they probably called themselves simply 'Gnostics.' Gnostic sects borrowed freely from each other, and it is likely that Valentinius took some of his ideas about Sophia from older Gnostic sources, and that his ideas, in turn, influenced other Gnostics.}}</ref> to understand Plotinus' opponents as being a Gnostic sect\u2014certainly (specifically [[Sethianism|Sethian]]), several such groups were present in [[Alexandria]] and elsewhere about the [[Mediterranean]] during Plotinus' lifetime. Plotinus specifically points to the Gnostic doctrine of Sophia and her emission of the Demiurge.\n\nThough the former understanding certainly enjoys the most significant popularity, the identification of Plotinus' opponents as Gnostic is not without some contention. Christos Evangeliou has contended<ref>Evangeliou, \"Plotinus's Anti-Gnostic Polemic and Porphyry's Against the Christians,\" in Wallis & Bregman, [https://books.google.com/books?id=WSbrLPup7wYC&pg=PA111&lpg=PA111&dq=Plotinus%27s+Anti-Gnostic+Polemic+and+Porphyry%27s+Against+the+Christians%22+Christos+Evangeliou&source=bl&ots=rSBVKFe8VD&sig=3MNVVSq8bDZs4koa-yMP6PaNT-Q&hl=en&ei=jR4hTIK_AsP48AbV_shl&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Plotinus%27s%20Anti-Gnostic%20Polemic%20and%20Porphyry%27s%20Against%20the%20Christians%22%20Christos%20Evangeliou&f=false p. 111.]</ref> that Plotinus' opponents might be better described as simply \"Christian Gnostics\", arguing that several of Plotinus' criticisms are as applicable to orthodox Christian doctrine as well. Also, considering the evidence from the time, Evangeliou thought the definition of the term \"Gnostics\" was unclear. Of note here is that while Plotinus' student [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]] names [[Christianity]] specifically in Porphyry's works, and Plotinus is to have been a known associate of the Christian [[Origen]], none of Plotinus' works mention Christ or Christianity\u2014. In contrast, Plotinus specifically addresses his target in the ''Enneads'' as the Gnostics.\n\n[[A. H. Armstrong]] identified the so-called \"Gnostics\" that Plotinus was attacking as Jewish and Pagan, in his introduction to the tract in his translation of the ''Enneads''. Armstrong alluding to Gnosticism being a Hellenic philosophical heresy of sorts, which later engaged Christianity and Neoplatonism.<ref>From \"Introduction to Against the Gnostics,\" Plotinus' ''Enneads'' as translated by A. H. Armstrong, pp. 220\u2013222: \"The treatise as it stands in the Enneads is a most powerful protest on behalf of Hellenic philosophy against the un-Hellenic heresy (as it was from the Platonist as well as the orthodox Christian point of view) of Gnosticism. There were Gnostics among Plotinus's friends, whom he had not succeeded in converting (Enneads ch. 10 of this treatise), and he and his pupils devoted considerable time and energy to anti-Gnostic controversy (Life of Plotinus ch. 16). He considered Gnosticism a dangerous influence, likely to pervert the minds even of members of his circle. It is impossible to attempt to give an account of Gnosticism here. By far, the best discussion of what the particular group of Gnostics Plotinus knew believed is M. Puech's admirable contribution to Entretiens Hardt V (Les Sources de Plotin). But it is important for the understanding of this treatise to be clear about the reasons why Plotinus disliked them so intensely and thought their influence so harmful.\"</ref><ref>Armstrong, pp. 220\u201322: \"Short statement of the doctrine of the three hypostasis, the One, Intellect, and Soul; there cannot be more or fewer than these three. Criticism of the attempts to multiply the hypostasis, and especially of the idea of two intellects, one which thinks and that other which thinks that it thinks. (ch. 1). The true doctrine of Soul (ch. 2). The law of constant procession and the eternity of the universe (ch.3). Attack on the Gnostic doctrine of the making of the universe by a fallen soul, and their despising of the universe and the heavenly bodies (ch. 4\u20135). The senseless jargon of the Gnostics, their plagiarism from and perversion of Plato, and their insolent arrogance (ch. 6). The true doctrine about Universal Soul and the goodness of the universe, which it forms and rules (ch. 7\u20138). Refutation of objections from the inequalities and injustices of human life (ch. 9). Ridiculous arrogance of the Gnostics who refuse to acknowledge the hierarchy of created gods and spirits and say that they alone are sons of God and superior to the heavens (ch. 9). The absurdities of the Gnostic doctrine of the fall of \"Wisdom\" (Sophia) and of the generation and activities of the Demiurge, maker of the visible universe (ch. 10\u201312). False and exaggerated Gnostic teaching about the cosmic spheres and their influence (ch. 13). The blasphemous falsity of the Gnostic claim to control the higher powers by magic and the absurdity of their claim to cure diseases by casting out demons (ch. 14). The false other-worldliness of the Gnostics leads to immorality (ch. 15). The true Platonic other-worldliness, which love and venerates the material universe in all its goodness and beauty as a perfect possible image of the intelligible, contracted at length with the false, Gnostic, other-worldliness which hates and despises the material universe and its beauties (ch. 16\u201318).\"</ref>\n\n[[John D. Turner]], professor of religious studies at the University of Nebraska, and famed translator and editor of the [[Nag Hammadi library]], stated<ref>Turner, \"Gnosticism and Platonism,\" in Wallis & Bregman.</ref> that the text Plotinus and his students read was Sethian Gnosticism, which predates Christianity. It appears that Plotinus attempted to clarify how the philosophers of the academy had not arrived at the same conclusions (such as [[dystheism]] or [[misotheism]] for the creator God as an answer to the [[problem of evil]]) as the targets of his criticism.\n\n[[Emil Cioran]] also wrote his ''Le mauvais d\u00e9miurge'' (\"The Evil Demiurge\"), published in 1969, influenced by Gnosticism and [[Schopenhauer]]ian interpretation of Platonic ontology, as well as that of Plotinus.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Religion}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Albinus (philosopher)]]\n* [[Azazil]]\n* [[Emil Cioran]]\n* [[Devil in Christianity]]\n* [[Gnosticism]]\n* [[Mara (demon)]]\n* [[Mayasura]]\n* [[Narasimha]]\n* [[Problem of the creator of God]]\n* [[Ptah]]\n* [[Tenth Intellect|Tenth Intellect (Isma'ilism)]]\n* [[Urizen]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* ''This article incorporates text from the entry '''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Lf8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA804 Demiurgus]''' in ''A Dictionary of Christian Biography, Literature, Sects and Doctrines'' by [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]] and [[Henry Wace (Anglican priest)|Henry Wace]] (1877), a publication now in the public domain.''\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071016173047/http://timelessmyths.com/mirrors/gnostic.php Dark Mirrors of Heaven: Gnostic Cosmogony]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Demiurge}}\n\n{{Ancient Greek philosophical concepts}}\n{{Theology}}\n{{Plato navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Conceptions of God]]\n[[Category:Concepts in ancient Greek metaphysics]]\n[[Category:Creator deities]]\n[[Category:Demons in Gnosticism]]\n[[Category:Gnostic deities]]\n[[Category:Names of God in Gnosticism]]\n[[Category:Platonic deities]]\n[[Category:Evil deities]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|An artisan-like figure responsible for fashioning and maintaining the physical universe}}\n{{about|philosophical concept of a Universal Fashioner|other uses|Demiurge (disambiguation)}}\n{{God| expanded=representations}}\n{{platonism}}\nIn the [[Platonism|Platonic]], [[Neopythagorean]], [[Middle Platonism|Middle Platonic]], and [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonic]] schools of philosophy, the '''demiurge''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|\u025b|m|i|.|\u025cr|d\u0292}}) is an [[artisan]]-like figure responsible for fashioning and maintaining the physical universe. The [[Gnosticism|Gnostics]] adopted the term \"demiurge\". Although a fashioner, the demiurge is not necessarily the same as the creator figure in the [[monotheism|monotheistic]] sense, because the demiurge itself and the material from which the demiurge fashions the universe are both considered to be consequences of something else. Depending on the system, they may be considered to be either uncreated and eternal or the product of some other entity.\n\nThe word \"demiurge\" is an English word derived from ''demiurgus'', a [[List of Latinised names|Latinised]] form of the [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|grc|\u03b4\u03b7\u03bc\u03b9\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03b3\u03cc\u03c2}} or ''d\u0113miurg\u00f3s''. It was originally a common noun meaning \"craftsman\" or \"artisan,\" but gradually came to mean \"producer,\" and eventually \"creator.\" The philosophical usage and the proper noun derive from [[Timaeus (dialogue)|Plato's ''Timaeus'']], written {{circa}}&nbsp;360 BC, where the demiurge is presented as the creator of the universe. The demiurge is also described as a creator in the Platonic ({{circa}}&nbsp;310\u201390 BC) and Middle Platonic ({{circa}}&nbsp;90 BC-AD 300) philosophical traditions. In the various branches of the Neoplatonic school (third century onwards), the demiurge is the fashioner of the real, perceptible world after the model of the [[Theory of Forms|<!-- capitalized-->Ideas]], but (in most Neoplatonic systems) is still not itself \"[[Form of the Good|the One]].\" In the arch-[[Dualistic cosmology|dualist]] ideology of the various Gnostic systems, the material universe is evil, while the non-material world is good. According to some strains of Gnosticism, the demiurge is [[Evil|malevolent]], as it is linked to the material world. In others, including the teaching of [[Valentinianism|Valentinus]], the demiurge is simply ignorant or misguided.\n\n==Platonism and neoplatonism==\n[[Plato]], as the speaker Timaeus, refers to the Demiurge frequently in the [[Socratic dialogue]] ''[[Timaeus (dialogue)|Timaeus]]'' (28a [[wikt:ff.#Abbreviation|ff.]]), {{circa}}&nbsp;360 BC. The main character refers to the Demiurge as the entity who \"fashioned and shaped\" the material world. Timaeus describes the Demiurge as unreservedly [[:wikt:benevolence|benevolent]], and so it desires a world as good as possible. Plato's work ''Timaeus'' is a philosophical reconciliation of [[Hesiod]]'s cosmology in his ''[[Theogony]]'', [[syncretism|syncretically]] reconciling Hesiod to [[Homer]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Python: A Study of Delphic Myth and Its Origin|year=1974|first=Joseph|last=Fontenrose|page=226|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h56ansk4SyQC&pg=PA226 | isbn=978-0-8196-0285-5 | publisher=Biblo & Tannen Publishers}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Chorology: On Beginning in Plato's Timaeus|year=1999|first=John|last=Sallis|page=86|isbn=0-253-21308-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gS_9aQ5mYKgC&pg=PA86 | publisher=Indiana University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The mythology of ancient Greece and Italy|first=Thomas|last=Keightley|year=1838|page=[https://archive.org/details/mythologyancien04keiggoog/page/n90 44]|publisher=Oxford University|url=https://archive.org/details/mythologyancien04keiggoog|quote=theogony timaeus.}}</ref>\n\n===Middle Platonism===\nIn [[Numenius of Apamea|Numenius]]'s [[Neo-Pythagorean]] and Middle Platonist [[cosmogony]], the Demiurge is second God as the ''[[nous]]'' or thought of intelligibles and sensibles.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Pythagoras and the Pythagoreans|last=Kahn|first=Charles|publisher=Hacket Publishing|year=|isbn=978-0-872205758|location=Indianapolis|pages=124}}</ref>\n\n===Neoplatonism===\n[[Plotinus]] and the later Platonists worked to clarify the Demiurge. To Plotinus, the second [[Emanationism|emanation]] represents an uncreated second cause (see [[Pythagoras]]' [[Dyad (symbol)|Dyad]]). Plotinus sought to reconcile Aristotle's ''[[energeia]]'' with Plato's Demiurge,<ref name=\"Karamanolis2006\">{{cite book|last=Karamanolis|first=George|year= 2006|title=Plato and Aristotle in Agreement?: Platonists on Aristotle from Antiochus to Porphyry|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0-19-926456-2|page=240}}</ref> which, as Demiurge and mind (''nous''), is a critical component in the [[ontological]] construct of human consciousness used to explain and clarify [[substance theory]] within [[Platonic realism]] (also called [[idealism]]). In order to reconcile Aristotelian with Platonian philosophy,<ref name=\"Karamanolis2006\" /> Plotinus metaphorically identified the demiurge (or ''nous'') within the [[Pantheon (gods)|pantheon of the Greek Gods]] as [[Zeus]].<ref>The ordering principle is twofold; there is a principle known as the Demiurge, and there is the Soul of the All; the appellation \"Zeus\" is sometimes applied to the Demiurge and sometimes to the principle conducting the universe.{{cn|date=October 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Henology====\nThe first and highest aspect of God is described by Plato as the One (\u03a4\u1f78 \u1f1d\u03bd, \"To Hen\"), the source, or the [[Monad (philosophy)|Monad]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Dionysius the Areopagite and the Neoplatonist Tradition: Despoiling the Hellenes|last=Wear|first=Sarah|last2=Dillon|first2=John|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2013|isbn=9780754603856|location=Burlington, VT|pages=15}}</ref> This is the God above the Demiurge, and manifests through the actions of the Demiurge. The Monad [[Emanationism|emanated]] the demiurge or ''[[Nous]]'' (consciousness) from its \"indeterminate\" vitality due to the monad being so abundant that it overflowed back onto itself, causing self-reflection.<ref>{{cite book|title=Neoplatonism and Gnosticism|year=1992|editor1-first=Richard T.|editor1-last=Wallis|editor2-first=Jay|editor2-last=Bregman|others=[[International Society for Neoplatonic Studies]]|url=https://books.google.com/?id=WSbrLPup7wYC&pg=PA55&lpg=PA55&dq=Anti-Gnostic+Polemic+Francisco+Garcia+Bazan+translated+from+Spanish+by+Winifred+T.+Slater+Nous+as+a+%22Second+God%22+According+to+Plotinus+In+Enneads#PPA55,M1 |isbn=978-0-7914-1337-1 |publisher=SUNY Press}}</ref> This self-reflection of the indeterminate vitality was referred to by Plotinus as the \"Demiurge\" or creator. The second principle is organization in its reflection of the [[Sentience|nonsentient]] force or ''[[Potentiality and actuality|dynamis]]'', also called the one or the Monad. The dyad is ''energeia'' emanated by the one that is then the work, process or activity called ''nous'', Demiurge, mind, consciousness that organizes the indeterminate vitality into the experience called the material world, universe, cosmos. [[Plotinus]] also elucidates the equation of matter with nothing or non-being in ''[[The Enneads]]''<ref>\"Matter is therefore a non-existent\"; Plotinus, ''Ennead'' 2, Tractate 4 Section 16.</ref> which more correctly is to express the concept of [[idealism]] or that there is not anything or anywhere outside of the \"mind\" or ''nous'' (c.f. [[pantheism]]).\n\nPlotinus' form of [[Platonic idealism]] is to treat the Demiurge, ''nous'' as the contemplative faculty (''ergon'') within man which orders the force (''dynamis'') into conscious reality.<ref>[[Schopenhauer]] wrote of this Neoplatonist philosopher: \"With Plotinus there even appears, probably for the first time in [[Western philosophy]], idealism that had long been current in the East even at that time, for it taught (Enneads, iii, lib. vii, c.10) that the soul has made the world by stepping from eternity into time, with the explanation: 'For there is for this universe no other place than the soul or mind' (''neque est alter hujus universi locus quam anima''), indeed the ideality of time is expressed in the words: 'We should not accept time outside the soul or mind' (''oportet autem nequaquam extra animam tempus accipere'').\" (Parerga and Paralipomena, Volume I, \"Fragments for the History of Philosophy,\" \u00a7&nbsp;7) Similarly, Professor Ludwig Noir\u00e9 wrote: \"For the first time in Western philosophy we find idealism proper in Plotinus (Enneads, iii, 7, 10), where he says, 'The only space or place of the world is the soul,' and 'Time must not be assumed to exist outside the soul.'\" [5] It is worth noting, however, that like Plato but unlike Schopenhauer and other modern philosophers, Plotinus does not worry about whether or how we can get beyond our ideas to know external objects.</ref> In this, he claimed to reveal Plato's true meaning: a doctrine he learned from Platonic tradition that did not appear outside the academy or in Plato's text. This tradition of creator God as ''nous'' (the manifestation of consciousness), can be validated in the works of pre-Plotinus philosophers such as [[Numenius of Apamea|Numenius]], as well as a connection between Hebrew and Platonic cosmology (see also [[Philo]]).<ref>[[Numenius of Apamea]] was reported to have asked, \"What else is Plato than Moses speaking Greek?\" Fr. 8 Des Places.</ref>\n\nThe Demiurge of Neoplatonism is the ''Nous'' (mind of God), and is one of the three ordering principles:\n* ''[[Arche]]'' (Gr. \"beginning\") \u2013 the source of all things,\n* ''[[Logos]]'' (Gr. \"reason/cause\") \u2013 the underlying order that is hidden beneath appearances,\n* ''[[:wikt:harmonia|Harmonia]]'' (Gr. \"harmony\") \u2013 numerical [[ratios]] in [[mathematics]].\n\nBefore Numenius of Apamea and Plotinus' ''[[Enneads]]'', no Platonic works ontologically clarified the Demiurge from the [[allegory]] in Plato's ''Timaeus''. The idea of Demiurge was, however, addressed before Plotinus in the works of Christian writer [[Justin Martyr]] who built his understanding of the Demiurge on the works of Numenius.{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}\n\n====Iamblichus====\n{{See also|Panentheism}}\nLater, the Neoplatonist [[Iamblichus of Chalcis|Iamblichus]] changed the role of the \"One,\" effectively altering the role of the Demiurge as second cause or dyad, which was one of the reasons that Iamblichus and his teacher [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]] came into conflict.\n\nThe figure of the Demiurge emerges in the theoretic of Iamblichus, which conjoins the transcendent, incommunicable \u201cOne,\u201d or Source. Here, at the summit of this system, the Source and Demiurge (material realm) coexist via the process of ''[[henosis]]''.<ref>See [http://www.theandros.com/iamblichus.html Theurgy, Iamblichus and henosis] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100109100359/http://www.theandros.com/iamblichus.html |date=2010-01-09 }}.</ref>\nIamblichus describes the One as a monad whose first principle or emanation is intellect (''nous''), while among \"the many\" that follow it there is a second, super-existent \"One\" that is the producer of intellect or soul (''psyche'').\n\nThe \"One\" is further separated into spheres of intelligence; the first and superior sphere is objects of thought, while the latter sphere is the domain of thought. Thus, a [[wikt:triad#Noun|triad]] is formed of the [[perception|intelligible]] ''nous'', the [[noesis|intellective]] ''nous'', and the ''[[Psyche (psychology)|psyche]]'' in order to reconcile further the various Hellenistic philosophical schools of [[Aristotle]]'s [[Actus et potentia|''actus'' and ''potentia'']] (actuality and potentiality) of the [[unmoved mover]] and Plato's Demiurge.\n\nThen within this intellectual triad Iamblichus assigns the third rank to the Demiurge, identifying it with the perfect or Divine ''nous'' with the intellectual triad being promoted to a ''hebdomad'' (pure intellect).\n\nIn the theoretic of Plotinus, ''nous'' produces nature through intellectual mediation, thus the intellectualizing gods are followed by a triad of psychic gods.\n\n==Gnosticism==\n{{Split section |Yaldabaoth|discuss={{TALKPAGENAME}}#Split proposed |date=November 2018}}\n{{gnosticism}}\n[[Gnosticism]] presents a distinction between the highest, unknowable God or [[Aeon (Gnosticism)|Supreme Being]] and the demiurgic \"creator\" of the material. Several systems of Gnostic thought present the Demiurge as antagonistic to the will of the Supreme Being: his act of creation occurs in an unconscious semblance of the divine model, and thus is fundamentally flawed, or else is formed with the malevolent intention of entrapping aspects of the divine ''in'' materiality. Thus, in such systems, the Demiurge acts as a solution to (or, at least possibly, the problem or cause that gives rise to){{citation needed|date=March 2014}} the [[problem of evil]].\n\n===Mythos===\nOne Gnostic [[mythos]] describes the declination of aspects of the divine into human form. [[Sophia (Gnosticism)|Sophia]] (Greek: \u03a3\u03bf\u03c6\u03af\u03b1, lit. \"wisdom\"), the Demiurge's mother and partial aspect of the divine ''[[Pleroma]]'' or \"Fullness,\" desired to create something apart from the [[Absolute (philosophy)|divine totality]], without the receipt of divine assent. In this act of separate creation, she gave birth to the monstrous Demiurge and, being ashamed of her deed, wrapped him in a cloud and created a throne for him within it. The Demiurge, isolated, did not behold his mother, nor anyone else, and concluded that only he existed, ignorant of the superior levels of reality.\n\nThe Demiurge, having received a portion of power from his mother, sets about a work of creation in unconscious imitation of the superior [[Pleroma|Pleromatic]] realm: He frames the [[seven heavens]], as well as all material and animal things, according to forms furnished by his mother; working, however, blindly and ignorant even of the existence of the mother who is the source of all his energy. He is blind to all that is spiritual, but he is king over the other two provinces. The word ''d\u0113miurgos'' properly describes his relation to the material; he is the ''father'' of that which is animal-like himself.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103105.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 5, 1.]</ref>\n\nThus Sophia's power becomes enclosed within the material forms of humanity, themselves entrapped within the material universe. In essence, the goal of Gnostic movements was typically the awakening of this spark, which permitted a return by the subject to the superior, non-material realities, which were its primal source.\n\n===Angels===\n[[Psalm 82]] begins ({{bibleref2|Psa|82:1|NET|verse 1}}), \"God stands in the assembly of [[El (deity)|El]] {{bracket|[[Septuagint|LXX]]: the assembly of gods}}, amid the gods he renders judgment,\" indicating a plurality of gods. However, it does not indicate that these gods were co-actors in creation. [[Philo]] had inferred from the expression \"Let us make man\" of the [[Book of Genesis]] that God had used other beings as assistants in the creation of man, and he explains in this way why man is capable of vice as well as virtue, ascribing the origin of the latter to God, of the former to His helpers in the work of creation.<ref>{{quote|It is on this account that Moses says, at the creation of man alone that God said, \"Let us make man,\" which expression shows an assumption of other beings to himself as assistants, so that God, the governor of all things, might have all the blameless intentions and actions of man when he does right attributed to him; and that his other assistants might bear the imputation of his contrary actions.|{{cite web |title=Philo: On the Creation, XXIV |url=http://www.earlyjewishwritings.com/text/philo/book1.html |website=www.earlyjewishwritings.com}}}}</ref>\n\nThe earliest Gnostic sects ascribe the work of creation to angels, some of them using the same passage in Genesis.<ref>[[Justin Martyr]], ''[[Dialogue with Trypho]]''. c. 67.</ref> So [[Irenaeus]] tells<ref>Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 23, 1.</ref> of the system of [[Simon Magus]],<ref>Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 23, 5.</ref> of the system of [[Menander (gnostic)|Menander]],<ref>Irenaeus, i. 24, 1.</ref> of the system of Saturninus, in which the number of these angels is reckoned as seven, and<ref>Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 25.</ref> of the system of [[Carpocrates]]. In the report of the system of [[Basilides]],<ref>Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 24, 4.</ref> we are told that our world was made by the angels who occupy the lowest heaven; but special mention is made of their chief, who is said to have been the [[God in Judaism|God of the Jews]], to have led that people out of the land of [[Egypt]], and to have given them their law. The prophecies are ascribed not to the chief but to the other world-making angels.\n\nThe Latin translation, confirmed by [[Hippolytus of Rome]],<ref>Hippolytus, ''[[Refutation of All Heresies]]''. vii. 33.</ref> makes [[Irenaeus]] state that according to [[Cerinthus]] (who shows [[Ebionites|Ebionite]] influence), creation was made by a power quite separate from the Supreme God and ignorant of Him. [[Theodoret]],<ref>Theodoret, ''Haer. Fab''. ii. 3.</ref> who here copies Irenaeus, turns this into the plural number \"powers,\" and so [[Epiphanius of Salamis]]<ref>Epiphanius, ''[[Panarion]]'', 28.</ref> represents Cerinthus as agreeing with Carpocrates in the doctrine that angels made the world.\n\n===Yaldabaoth===\n[[File:Lion-faced deity.jpg|thumb|right|150px|A lion-faced deity found on a Gnostic gem in [[Bernard de Montfaucon]]'s ''L'antiquit\u00e9 expliqu\u00e9e et repr\u00e9sent\u00e9e en figures'' may be a depiction of the Demiurge.]]\n\nIn the [[Ophites|Ophite]] and [[Sethians|Sethian]] systems, which have many affinities with the teachings of Valentinus, the making of the world is ascribed to a company of seven [[archon (Gnosticism)|archons]], whose names are given, but still more prominent is their chief, \"Yaldabaoth\" (also known as \"Yaltabaoth\" or \"Ialdabaoth\").\n\nIn the ''[[Apocryphon of John]]'' {{circa}}&nbsp; AD 120\u2013180, the demiurge arrogantly declares that he has made the world by himself:\n<blockquote>\nNow the [[archon]] [\"ruler\"], who is weak, has three names. The first name is Yaltabaoth, the second is Saklas [\"fool\"], and the third is [[Samael]]. And he is impious in his arrogance, which is in him. For he said, 'I am God, and there is no other God beside me,' for he is ignorant of his strength, the place from which he had come.<ref>\"Apocryphon of John,\" translation by Frederik Wisse in ''The Nag Hammadi Library''. Accessed online at [http://www.gnosis.org/naghamm/apocjn.html gnosis.org]</ref></blockquote>\n\nHe is Demiurge and maker of man, but as a ray of light from above enters the body of a man and gives him a soul, Yaldabaoth is filled with envy; he tries to limit man's knowledge by forbidding him the fruit of knowledge in paradise. At the consummation of all things, all light will return to the [[Pleroma]]. But Yaldabaoth, the Demiurge, with the material world, will be cast into the lower depths.<ref name=\"Catholic\">{{Catholic|wstitle=Demiurge|inline=yes}}</ref>\n\nYaldabaoth is frequently called \"the Lion-faced,\" ''leontoeides'', and is said to have the body of a serpent. The demiurge is also<ref>Hipp. ''Ref''. vi. 32, p.&nbsp;191.</ref> described as having a fiery nature, applying the words of Moses to him: \"the Lord our God is a burning and consuming fire.\" Hippolytus claims that Simon used a similar description.<ref>Hipp. ''Ref''. vi. 9.</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Pistis Sophia]]'', Yaldabaoth has already sunk from his high estate and resides in Chaos, where, with his forty-nine demons, he tortures wicked souls in boiling rivers of the pitch, and with other punishments (pp.&nbsp;257, 382). He is an archon with the face of a lion, half flame, and half-darkness.\n\nUnder the name of ''Nebro'' (rebel), Yaldabaoth is called an angel in the [[apocryphal]] ''[[Gospel of Judas]]''. He is first mentioned in \"The Cosmos, Chaos, and the Underworld\" as one of the twelve angels to come \"into being [to] rule over chaos and the [underworld].\" He comes from heaven, and it is said his \"face flashed with fire and [his] appearance was defiled with blood.\" Nebro creates six angels in addition to the angel [[Saklas]] to be his assistants. These six, in turn, create another twelve angels \"with each one receiving a portion in the heavens.\"\n\n====Names====\n[[File:Leontocephaline-Ostia.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|right|Drawing of the lion-headed figure found at the [[Mithraeum]] of C.&nbsp;Valerius Heracles and sons, dedicated 190&nbsp;CE at [[Ostia Antica]], Italy (CIMRM 312).]]\n\nThe most probable derivation of the name \"Yaldabaoth\" was given by [[Johann Karl Ludwig Gieseler]]. Giesler believed the name was derived from the Aramaic ''yald\u0101 bahuth'', {{lang|arc|\u05d9\u05dc\u05d3\u05d0\u05d1\u05d4\u05d5\u05ea}}, meaning \"Son of Chaos.\" However, [[Gilles Quispel]] notes:\n{{quote|[[Gershom Scholem]], the third genius in this field, more specifically the genius of precision, had taught us that some of us were wrong when they believed that Jaldabaoth means \"son of chaos\" because the [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] word ''bahutha'' in the sense of chaos only existed in the imagination of the author of a well-known dictionary. This is a pity because this name would suit the demiurge risen from chaos to a nicety. And perhaps the author of the ''[[On the Origin of the World|Untitled Document]]'' did not know Aramaic and also supposed as we did once, that ''baoth'' had something to do with ''[[Tohu wa-bohu|tohuwabohu]]'', one of the few Hebrew words that everybody knows. ... It would seem then that the Orphic view of the demiurge was integrated into Jewish Gnosticism even before the redaction of the myth contained in the original ''[[Apocryphon of John]]''. ... [[Phanes]] is represented with the mask of a ''lion's'' head on his breast, while from his sides, the heads of a ram and a buck are budding forth: his body is encircled by a snake. This type was accepted by the [[Mithraism|Mithras mysteries]], to indicate [[Aion (deity)|Aion]], the new year, and Mithras, whose numerical value is 365. Sometimes he is also identified with Jao Adonai, the creator of the Hebrews. His hieratic attitude indicates Egyptian origin. The same is true of [[Mithraism#lion-headed figure|the monstrous figure with the head of a lion]], which symbolises Time, [[Chronos]], in Mithraism; Alexandrian origin of this type is probable.<ref>{{cite book |last=Quispel |first=Gilles |authorlink=Gilles Quispel |page=64 |title=Gnostica, Judaica, Catholica: Collected Essays of Gilles Quispel |editor1-first= Johannes |editor1-last=Van Oort |isbn=978-90-04-13945-9 |year=2008 |publisher=Koninklijke Brill NV |location=Leiden}}</ref>}}\n\n\"[[Samael]]\" literally means \"Blind God\" or \"God of the Blind\" in Hebrew ({{hebrew|\u05e1\u05de\u05d0\u05dc}}). This being is considered not only blind, or ignorant of its own origins but may, in addition, be evil; its name is also found in [[Judaism]] as the [[Death (personification)#Death (angels) in religion|Angel of Death]] and in Christian [[demon]]ology. This link to the Judeo-Christian tradition leads to a further comparison with [[Satan]]. Another alternative title for the demiurge is \"Saklas,\" Aramaic for \"fool.\"\n\nThe angelic name \"[[Ariel (angel)|Ariel]]\" (meaning \"the lion of God\" in Hebrew)<ref>{{cite book |title=Jewish Gnosticism, Merkabah Mysticism, and Talmudic Tradition |first=Gershom |last=Scholem |publisher=Jewish Theological Seminary of America |year=1965 |page=72}}</ref> has also been used to refer to the Demiurge and is called his \"perfect\" name;<ref>{{cite book |author=Robert McLachlan Wilson |title=Nag Hammadi and gnosis: Papers read at the First International Congress of Coptology |year=1976 |publisher=BRILL |pages=21\u201323 |quote=''Therefore his esoteric name is Jaldabaoth, whereas the perfect call him Ariel, because he has the appearance of a lion.''}}</ref> in some Gnostic lore, Ariel has been called an ancient or original name for Ialdabaoth.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gustav Davidson|title=A dictionary of angels: including the fallen angels |year=1994 |publisher=Scrollhouse |page=54}}</ref> The name has also been inscribed on amulets as \"Ariel Ialdabaoth\",<ref>{{cite book|author=David M Gwynn|title=Religious Diversity in Late Antiquity |year=2010 |publisher=BRILL |page=448}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Campbell Bonner |title=An Amulet of the Ophite Gnostics |year=1949 |publisher=The American School of Classical Studies at Athens, Hesperia Supplements, Vol. 8|pages=43\u201346}}</ref> and the figure of the archon inscribed with \"Aariel\".<ref>{{cite book |author1=Gilles Quispel |author2=R. van den Broek |author-link2=Roel van den Broek |author3=Maarten Jozef Vermaseren |title=Studies in gnosticism and hellenistic religions |year=1981 |publisher=BRILL |pages=40\u201341}}</ref>\n\n===Marcion===\nAccording to [[Marcion of Sinope|Marcion]], the title God was given to the Demiurge, who was to be sharply distinguished from the higher Good God. The former was ''d\u00edkaios,'' severely just, the latter ''agath\u00f3s,'' or loving-kind; the former was the \"god of this world\" ({{bibleverse|2|Corinthians|4:4}}), the God of the [[Old Testament]], the latter the true God of the [[New Testament]]. Christ, though in reality, the Son of the Good God, pretended to be the Messiah of the Demiurge, the better to spread the truth concerning His heavenly Father. The true believer in Christ entered into God's kingdom; the unbeliever remained forever the slave of the Demiurge.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/>\n\n===Valentinus===\nIt is in the [[Valentinianism|system of Valentinus]] that the name ''D\u0113miurgos'' is used, which occurs nowhere in Irenaeus except in connection with the Valentinian system; we may reasonably conclude that it was Valentinus who adopted from Platonism the use of this word. When it is employed by other Gnostics either, it is not used in a technical sense, or its use has been borrowed from Valentinus. But it is only the name that can be said to be specially Valentinian; the personage intended by it corresponds more or less closely with the Yaldabaoth of the Ophites, the [[Abraxas|great Archon]] of Basilides, the Elohim of [[Justin (gnostic)|Justinus]], etc.\n\nThe Valentinian theory elaborates that from Achamoth (''he k\u00e1t\u014d soph\u00eda'' or lower wisdom) three kinds of substance take their origin, the spiritual (''pneumatiko\u00ed''), the animal (''psychiko\u00ed'') and the material (''hyliko\u00ed''). The Demiurge belongs to the second kind, as he was the offspring of a union of Achamoth with the matter.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/><ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103105.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 5.]</ref> And as Achamoth herself was only the daughter of ''Soph\u00eda'' the last of the thirty Aeons, the Demiurge was distant by many emanations from the Propat\u00f4r, or Supreme God.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/>\n\nIn creating this world out of Chaos, the Demiurge was unconsciously influenced for good; and the universe, to the surprise even of its Maker, became almost perfect. The Demiurge regretted even its slight imperfection, and as he thought himself the Supreme God, he attempted to remedy this by sending a Messiah. To this Messiah, however, was actually united with Jesus the Saviour, Who redeemed men. These are either ''hyliko\u00ed'' or ''pneumatiko\u00ed''.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/>\n\nThe first, or material men, will return to the grossness of matter and finally be consumed by fire; the second, or animal men, together with the Demiurge, will enter a middle state, neither Pleroma nor ''hyle''; the purely spiritual men will be completely freed from the influence of the Demiurge and together with the Saviour and Achamoth, his spouse, will enter the Pleroma divested of body (''hyle'') and soul (''psych\u00e9'').<ref name=\"Catholic\"/><ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103106.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 6.]</ref> In this most common form of Gnosticism the Demiurge had an inferior though not intrinsically evil function in the universe as the head of the animal, or psychic world.<ref name=\"Catholic\"/>\n\n===The devil===\nOpinions on [[the devil]], and his relationship to the Demiurge, varied. The Ophites held that he and his demons constantly oppose and thwart the human race, as it was on their account the devil was cast down into this world.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103130.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 30, 8.]</ref> According to one variant of the Valentinian system, the Demiurge is also the maker, out of the appropriate substance, of an order of ''spiritual'' beings, the devil, the prince of this world, and his angels. But the devil, as being a ''spirit'' of wickedness, is able to recognize the higher spiritual world, of which his maker the Demiurge, who is the only animal, has no real knowledge. The devil resides in this lower world, of which he is the prince, the Demiurge in the heavens; his mother Sophia in the middle region, above the heavens and below the Pleroma.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103105.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', i. 5, 4.]</ref>\n\nThe Valentinian [[Heracleon]]<ref>[http://www.gnosis.org/library/fragh.htm Heracleon, Frag. 20.]</ref> interpreted the devil as the ''principle'' of evil, that of ''hyle'' (matter). As he writes in his commentary on {{bibleverse||John|4:21}},\n<blockquote>The mountain represents the Devil, or his world since the Devil was one part of the whole of matter, but the world is the total mountain of evil, a deserted dwelling place of beasts, to which all who lived before the law and all Gentiles render worship. But Jerusalem represents the creation of the Creator whom the Jews worship. ... You then who are spiritual should worship neither the creation nor the Craftsman, but the Father of Truth. </blockquote>\n\nThis vilification of the creator was held to be inimical to Christianity by the early fathers of the church. In refuting the beliefs of the gnostics, [[Irenaeus]] stated that \"Plato is proved to be more religious than these men, for he allowed that the same God was both just and good, having power over all things, and himself executing judgment.\"<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/fathers/0103325.htm Irenaeus, ''Adversus Haereses'', iii. 25.]</ref>\n\n===Cathars===\n[[Catharism]] inherited their idea of Satan as the creator of the evil world from Gnosticism. Quispel writes,\n\n{{quote|There is a direct link between ancient Gnosticism and Catharism. The Cathars held that the creator of the world, Satanael, had usurped the name of God, but that he had subsequently been unmasked and told that he was not really God.<ref>Quispel, Gilles and Van Oort, Johannes (2008), p. 143.</ref>}}\n\n==Neoplatonism and Gnosticism==\n{{Main|Neoplatonism, and Gnosticism}}\n{{Wikisource|1=Enneads/Against the Gnostics; or, Against Those That Affirm the Creator of the Cosmos and the Cosmos Itself to be Evil|2=Against the Gnostics; or, Against Those That Affirm the Creator of the Cosmos and the Cosmos Itself to be Evil}}\nGnosticism attributed falsehood or evil to the concept of the Demiurge or creator. However, in some Gnostic traditions, the creator is from a fallen, ignorant, or lesser\u2014rather than evil\u2014perspective, such as that of [[Valentinius]].\n\n===Plotinus===\nThe Neoplatonic philosopher [[Plotinus]] addressed within his works Gnosticism's conception of the Demiurge, which he saw as un-[[Ancient Greece|Hellenic]] and blasphemous to the Demiurge or creator of Plato. Plotinus, along with his teacher [[Ammonius Saccas]], was the founder of [[Neoplatonism]].<ref>John D. Turner. [https://web.archive.org/web/20140816004048/http://www.unl.edu/classics/faculty/turner/triadaft.htm Neoplatonism].</ref> In the ninth [[tractate]] of the second of his ''Enneads'', Plotinus criticizes his opponents for their appropriation of ideas from Plato:\n\n{{quote|From Plato come their punishments, their rivers of the underworld and the changing from body to body; as for the plurality they assert in the Intellectual Realm\u2014the Authentic Existent, the Intellectual-Principle, ''the Second Creator and the Soul''\u2014all this is taken over from the Timaeus.|Ennead 2.9.vi; emphasis added from [[A. H. Armstrong]]'s introduction to Ennead 2.9}}\n\nOf note here is the remark concerning the second [[hypostasis (philosophy and religion)|hypostasis]] or Creator and third hypostasis or [[Anima mundi|World Soul]]. Plotinus criticizes his opponents for \"all the novelties through which they seek to establish a philosophy of their own\" which, he declares, \"have been picked up outside of the truth\";<ref name=\"sacred-texts\">\"For, in sum, a part of their doctrine comes from Plato; all the novelties through which they seek to establish a philosophy of their own have been picked up outside of the truth.\" Plotinus, \"Against the Gnostics,\" [http://www.sacred-texts.com/cla/plotenn/enn161.htm ''Ennead'' II, 9, 6.]</ref> they attempt to conceal rather than admit their indebtedness to ancient philosophy, which they have corrupted by their extraneous and misguided embellishments. Thus their understanding of the Demiurge is similarly flawed in comparison to Plato\u2019s original intentions.\n\nWhereas Plato's Demiurge is good wishing good on his creation, Gnosticism contends that the Demiurge is not only the originator of evil but is evil as well. Hence the title of Plotinus' refutation: \"Against Those That Affirm the Creator of the Kosmos and the Kosmos Itself to be Evil\" (generally quoted as \"Against the Gnostics\"). Plotinus argues of the disconnect or great barrier that is created between the ''nous'' or the mind's [[noumenon]] (see [[Heraclitus]]) and the material world ([[phenomenon]]) by believing the material world is evil.\n\nThe majority of scholars tend<ref>{{cite book|title=Plotinus: Enneads II|edition=Loeb Classical Library|author=Plotinus, Arthur Hilary Armstrong (trans.)|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1966|quote=From this point to the end of ch. 12 Plotinus is attacking a Gnostic myth known to us best at present in the form it took in the system of Valentinus. The Mother, Sophia-Achamoth, produced as a result of the complicated sequence of events which followed the fall of the higher Sophia, and her offspring the Demiurge, the inferior and ignorant maker of the material universe, are Valentinian figures; cp. Irenaeus, ''[[On the Detection and Overthrow of the So-Called Gnosis|Adversus haereses]]'' 1.4 and 5. Valentinius had been in Rome, and there is nothing improbable in the presence of Valentinians there in the time of Plotinus. But the evidence in the ''Life'' ch. 16 suggests that the Gnostics in Plotinus's circle belonged rather to the older group called Sethians or [[Archontics]], related to the [[Ophites]] or [[Barbelo]]gnostics: they probably called themselves simply 'Gnostics.' Gnostic sects borrowed freely from each other, and it is likely that Valentinius took some of his ideas about Sophia from older Gnostic sources, and that his ideas, in turn, influenced other Gnostics.}}</ref> to understand Plotinus' opponents as being a Gnostic sect\u2014certainly (specifically [[Sethianism|Sethian]]), several such groups were present in [[Alexandria]] and elsewhere about the [[Mediterranean]] during Plotinus' lifetime. Plotinus specifically points to the Gnostic doctrine of Sophia and her emission of the Demiurge.\n\nThough the former understanding certainly enjoys the most significant popularity, the identification of Plotinus' opponents as Gnostic is not without some contention. Christos Evangeliou has contended<ref>Evangeliou, \"Plotinus's Anti-Gnostic Polemic and Porphyry's Against the Christians,\" in Wallis & Bregman, [https://books.google.com/books?id=WSbrLPup7wYC&pg=PA111&lpg=PA111&dq=Plotinus%27s+Anti-Gnostic+Polemic+and+Porphyry%27s+Against+the+Christians%22+Christos+Evangeliou&source=bl&ots=rSBVKFe8VD&sig=3MNVVSq8bDZs4koa-yMP6PaNT-Q&hl=en&ei=jR4hTIK_AsP48AbV_shl&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CAYQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Plotinus%27s%20Anti-Gnostic%20Polemic%20and%20Porphyry%27s%20Against%20the%20Christians%22%20Christos%20Evangeliou&f=false p. 111.]</ref> that Plotinus' opponents might be better described as simply \"Christian Gnostics\", arguing that several of Plotinus' criticisms are as applicable to orthodox Christian doctrine as well. Also, considering the evidence from the time, Evangeliou thought the definition of the term \"Gnostics\" was unclear. Of note here is that while Plotinus' student [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]] names [[Christianity]] specifically in Porphyry's works, and Plotinus is to have been a known associate of the Christian [[Origen]], none of Plotinus' works mention Christ or Christianity\u2014. In contrast, Plotinus specifically addresses his target in the ''Enneads'' as the Gnostics.\n\n[[A. H. Armstrong]] identified the so-called \"Gnostics\" that Plotinus was attacking as Jewish and Pagan, in his introduction to the tract in his translation of the ''Enneads''. Armstrong alluding to Gnosticism being a Hellenic philosophical heresy of sorts, which later engaged Christianity and Neoplatonism.<ref>From \"Introduction to Against the Gnostics,\" Plotinus' ''Enneads'' as translated by A. H. Armstrong, pp. 220\u2013222: \"The treatise as it stands in the Enneads is a most powerful protest on behalf of Hellenic philosophy against the un-Hellenic heresy (as it was from the Platonist as well as the orthodox Christian point of view) of Gnosticism. There were Gnostics among Plotinus's friends, whom he had not succeeded in converting (Enneads ch. 10 of this treatise), and he and his pupils devoted considerable time and energy to anti-Gnostic controversy (Life of Plotinus ch. 16). He considered Gnosticism a dangerous influence, likely to pervert the minds even of members of his circle. It is impossible to attempt to give an account of Gnosticism here. By far, the best discussion of what the particular group of Gnostics Plotinus knew believed is M. Puech's admirable contribution to Entretiens Hardt V (Les Sources de Plotin). But it is important for the understanding of this treatise to be clear about the reasons why Plotinus disliked them so intensely and thought their influence so harmful.\"</ref><ref>Armstrong, pp. 220\u201322: \"Short statement of the doctrine of the three hypostasis, the One, Intellect, and Soul; there cannot be more or fewer than these three. Criticism of the attempts to multiply the hypostasis, and especially of the idea of two intellects, one which thinks and that other which thinks that it thinks. (ch. 1). The true doctrine of Soul (ch. 2). The law of constant procession and the eternity of the universe (ch.3). Attack on the Gnostic doctrine of the making of the universe by a fallen soul, and their despising of the universe and the heavenly bodies (ch. 4\u20135). The senseless jargon of the Gnostics, their plagiarism from and perversion of Plato, and their insolent arrogance (ch. 6). The true doctrine about Universal Soul and the goodness of the universe, which it forms and rules (ch. 7\u20138). Refutation of objections from the inequalities and injustices of human life (ch. 9). Ridiculous arrogance of the Gnostics who refuse to acknowledge the hierarchy of created gods and spirits and say that they alone are sons of God and superior to the heavens (ch. 9). The absurdities of the Gnostic doctrine of the fall of \"Wisdom\" (Sophia) and of the generation and activities of the Demiurge, maker of the visible universe (ch. 10\u201312). False and exaggerated Gnostic teaching about the cosmic spheres and their influence (ch. 13). The blasphemous falsity of the Gnostic claim to control the higher powers by magic and the absurdity of their claim to cure diseases by casting out demons (ch. 14). The false other-worldliness of the Gnostics leads to immorality (ch. 15). The true Platonic other-worldliness, which love and venerates the material universe in all its goodness and beauty as a perfect possible image of the intelligible, contracted at length with the false, Gnostic, other-worldliness which hates and despises the material universe and its beauties (ch. 16\u201318).\"</ref>\n\n[[John D. Turner]], professor of religious studies at the University of Nebraska, and famed translator and editor of the [[Nag Hammadi library]], stated<ref>Turner, \"Gnosticism and Platonism,\" in Wallis & Bregman.</ref> that the text Plotinus and his students read was Sethian Gnosticism, which predates Christianity. It appears that Plotinus attempted to clarify how the philosophers of the academy had not arrived at the same conclusions (such as [[dystheism]] or [[misotheism]] for the creator God as an answer to the [[problem of evil]]) as the targets of his criticism.\n\n[[Emil Cioran]] also wrote his ''Le mauvais d\u00e9miurge'' (\"The Evil Demiurge\"), published in 1969, influenced by Gnosticism and [[Schopenhauer]]ian interpretation of Platonic ontology, as well as that of Plotinus.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Religion}}\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Albinus (philosopher)]]\n* [[Azazil]]\n* [[Emil Cioran]]\n* [[Devil in Christianity]]\n* [[Gnosticism]]\n* [[Mara (demon)]]\n* [[Mayasura]]\n* [[Narasimha]]\n* [[Problem of the creator of God]]\n* [[Ptah]]\n* [[Tenth Intellect|Tenth Intellect (Isma'ilism)]]\n* [[Urizen]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* ''This article incorporates text from the entry '''[https://books.google.com/books?id=Lf8ZAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA804 Demiurgus]''' in ''A Dictionary of Christian Biography, Literature, Sects and Doctrines'' by [[William Smith (lexicographer)|William Smith]] and [[Henry Wace (Anglican priest)|Henry Wace]] (1877), a publication now in the public domain.''\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071016173047/http://timelessmyths.com/mirrors/gnostic.php Dark Mirrors of Heaven: Gnostic Cosmogony]\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Demiurge}}\n\n{{Ancient Greek philosophical concepts}}\n{{Theology}}\n{{Plato navbox}}\n\n[[Category:Conceptions of God]]\n[[Category:Concepts in ancient Greek metaphysics]]\n[[Category:Creator deities]]\n[[Category:Demons in Gnosticism]]\n[[Category:Gnostic deities]]\n[[Category:Names of God in Gnosticism]]\n[[Category:Platonic deities]]\n[[Category:Evil deities]]\n", "name_user": "Prana1111", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNeoplatonism and Gnosticism:if commas are added to links without pipes, they won't work", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demiurge"}
{"title_page": "Frederick Yeh", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Frederick C. Yeh\n|image = Frederick_C._Yeh_releases_rescued_sea_turtle_back_in_the_ocean_with_children,_Apr_2013.jpg\n|caption = Yeh releases a rescued sea turtle back in the ocean with disadvantaged children\n|alma_mater = {{plain list|\n*[[Johns Hopkins University]] \n*[[Duke University]] }}\n|occupation = [[social entrepreneur]] <br> [[conservation biologist]]\n|known_for = The unlikely sea turtle savior<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/travel/story/20150521-in-china-saving-sea-turtles-from-soup|title=The unlikely sea turtle saviour|first=Amanda|last=Ruggeri|date=|website=bbc.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> \n}}\n\n'''Frederick C. Yeh''' is an [[United States|American]] [[social entrepreneur]] and [[conservation biologist]] who founded [[Sea Turtles 911]], a [[non-profit]] [[sea turtle]] rescue and [[conservation organization]] that operates in the United States and China.<ref name=bbc /><ref name=cnn>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/travel/article/china-hainan-sea-turtles|title=Could rare sea turtles return to the Hawaii of China?|author=|date=28 August 2017|website=cnn.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=fyeh2>{{Cite web |url=http://en.visithainan.gov.cn/en/mt_newsview-1776.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131016152546/http://en.visithainan.gov.cn/en/mt_newsview-1776.htm |archive-date=2013-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=fyeh3>{{Cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/sci/2013-09/03/c_132688041.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114185041/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/sci/2013-09/03/c_132688041.htm |archive-date=2013-11-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=fyeh4>{{cite web|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90882/8375839.html|title=Sea Turtles 911 dedicated to sea turtle conservation - People's Daily Online|first=|last=F_100542|date=|website=english.people.com.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=chineseamerican1>{{cite web|url=http://www.asamnews.com/2013/09/03/english-news-cn-chinese-american-dedicates-career-to-saving-endangered-turtles/ |title=English News.CN: Chinese American Dedicates Career to Saving Endangered Turtles |publisher=AsAm News |date=2013-09-03 |accessdate=2019-10-27}}</ref><ref name=paul>{{Cite web |url=http://www.paulhiltonphotography.com/index.php/field-notes/30 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-11-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109104419/http://www.paulhiltonphotography.com/index.php/field-notes/30 |archive-date=2011-11-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.dw.com/generationchange/2011/11/saving-sea-turtles-in-hainan/|title=Saving Sea Turtles in Hainan - Uncategorized - Generation Change - DW.COM|author=|date=|website=dw.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=german>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/saving-endangered-sea-turtles-in-hainan/a-6665063|title=Saving endangered Sea Turtles in Hainan - DW - 22.11.2011|first=Deutsche Welle|last=(www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=bf>{{Cite web |url=http://bestfriends.org/News-And-Features/News/China--Until-the-seas-are-safe-again/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130703202901/http://bestfriends.org/News-And-Features/News/China--Until-the-seas-are-safe-again/ |archive-date=2013-07-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=fyeh5>{{cite web|url=http://english.cri.cn/11354/2013/08/24/2561s783859.htm|title=Sea Turtles 911 Dedicated to Sea Turtle Conservation|author=|date=|website=english.cri.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\n\nYeh attended [[Montgomery County Public Schools (Maryland)|Montgomery County Public Schools]], including [[Thomas Sprigg Wootton High School|Thomas S. Wootton High School]], and graduated from [[Johns Hopkins University]] and [[Duke University]].<ref name=paul /><ref name=german /><ref name=bf /> In 2007, Yeh discovered that [[endangered sea turtles]] on [[Hainan|Hainan island, China]], were being sold illegally for their meat and shell.<ref name=\"fyeh1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/806004.shtml|title=Sea Turtles 911 dedicated to sea turtle conservation - Global Times|last=Times|first=Global|date=|website=www.globaltimes.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=fyeh3 /><ref name=paul /><ref name=german /><ref name=bf /> During an interview with [[CNN]], Yeh described, \"I felt really hopeless at that time ... You would see land turtles and freshwater turtles (in the market) and some of those are legal, but when you see a sea turtle it's clearly not supposed to be there and that's shocking to see.\"<ref name=cnn /> This finding was emotionally disturbing to Yeh and became a turning point in his life, which led to the founding of the first non-profit organization working for the advancement of sea turtle protection and conservation in China.<ref name=bbc />\n\n== Sea Turtles 911 ==\n\n{{Main|Sea Turtles 911}}\n[[File:Coast Guard Police Rescue Sea Turtle for Frederick Yeh.jpg|thumb|left|Frederick Yeh and coast guard police rescue a sick sea turtle.]]\n[[File:Sea turtle rehabilitation with fluid therapy by Frederick Yeh.jpg|thumb|right|Frederick Yeh provides medical treatments to a sick sea turtle.]]\nDespite the desperate state of sea turtles in China, Yeh was inspired in 2008 when he saw wild sea turtles undisturbed by people as the animals were naturally basking on public beaches in Hawaii.<ref name=basking1>{{cite web|url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/time-year-turtle-beach-oahu-106738.html|title=The Best Time of the Year for Turtle Beach, Oahu|author=|date=|website=usatoday.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=basking2>{{cite web|url=http://www.fpir.noaa.gov/PRD/prd_volunteer_opps.html|title=Home page of NOAA Fisheries Service - Pacific Islands Regional Office|first=US Department of Commerce, NOAA, National Marine Fisheries|last=Service|date=|website=www.fpir.noaa.gov|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>  As Yeh said on a CNN interview, \"When you see the sea turtles in Hawaii, how great they are, it's worth it when you can envision that and hope that one day it will happen in Hainan, one day, in China.\"<ref name=cnn />  This experience led Yeh to believe that sea turtles and people could live in harmony and that there was still hope in China because of the successful sea turtle conservation efforts in Hawaii.  According to the global authority on nature conservation, [[International Union for the Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN), the sea turtles of the Hawaiian Islands were also once under the threat of near [[extinction]], but are now thriving<ref name=sbalazs>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-20205-iucn-sea-turtles-911-release-tagged-sea-turtle-in-sanya.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925190414/http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-20205-iucn-sea-turtles-911-release-tagged-sea-turtle-in-sanya.html |archive-date=2012-09-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=mbalazs>{{cite web|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2012/0306-pod-seaturtle911.html#|title=Animal photos of the day: green sea turtle saved in China|author=|date=6 March 2012|website=mongabay.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> and their conservation status reclassified as \"Least Concern\" according to the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=iucnred>{{cite web|url=http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/16285718/0|title=Chelonia mydas (Hawaiian subpopulation) (Green Turtle, Hawaiian Green Turtle, Tortuga Blanca)|author=|date=|website=www.iucnredlist.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>  Thus, Yeh established Sea Turtles 911 under Hawaiian jurisdiction, and changed the course of his life by moving to China to save the sea turtles he had hopelessly witnessed being sold, earning him the nickname \"The unlikely sea turtle savior\" by the [[BBC]].<ref name=bbc /><ref name=cnn /> Building a floating sea turtle hospital in a Chinese fishing village known for its extensive sea turtle [[poaching]], Yeh makes a point to work with people of all types to support sea turtle conservation in the area, including government officials, academia, fishermen and poachers, community members, local and international volunteers.<ref name=cnn /><ref name=hospital1>{{cite web|url=http://www.china.org.cn/environment/2013-09/04/content_29924143.htm|title=Floating hospital saves sea turtles - China.org.cn|first=|last=\u5f13\u8fce\u6625|date=|website=www.china.org.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=hospital2>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Science_News/2013/09/03/Floating-hospital-in-China-dedicated-to-caring-for-sea-turtles/UPI-18231378254043/|title=Floating hospital in China dedicated to caring for sea turtles|author=|date=|website=upi.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=hospital3>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/xinhua/2013-09-03/content_10025472.html|title=Around China: Floating hospital saves sea turtles-chinadaily.com.cn|author=|date=|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=inouye>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaii247.com/2012/09/04/chinese-police-rescue-inouye-the-turtle/|title=Chinese police rescue Inouye the turtle|author=|date=4 September 2012|website=hawaii247.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> At a sea turtle release event held at the [[Ritz-Carlton]], [[Sanya]], Yeh stated, \"For our release events, if we can bring multiple sectors in our community together, it will be very beneficial to sea turtle conservation in China. It is my hope that we can put other issues aside and agree on sea turtle rights, for the advancement of sea turtle conservation.\"<ref name=iost>{{cite web|url=http://www.ioseaturtles.org/headline_detail.php?id=2207|title=Indian Ocean - South-East Asian Marine Turtle Memorandum of Understanding|author=|date=|website=www.ioseaturtles.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=ritzquote>{{Cite web |url=http://sanyaexpat.com/index.php/news-sanya-hainan-china-world-sanyabay-dadonghai-yalongwan-shimeibay-haitangbay-haikou-shanghai/seaturtles911-ritzcarlton-yalongbay-sany?blog=1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826171224/http://sanyaexpat.com/index.php/news-sanya-hainan-china-world-sanyabay-dadonghai-yalongwan-shimeibay-haitangbay-haikou-shanghai/seaturtles911-ritzcarlton-yalongbay-sany?blog=1 |archive-date=2011-08-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Local community members, including fishermen and coast guard police, describe Yeh as a true \"[[Haigui]]\" or a \"returning sea turtle,\"<ref name=bbc/> and defer to his expertise when endangered sea turtles are rescued and in need of medical attention.<ref name=inouye /><ref name=hawaii>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaii247.com/2012/03/27/satellite-tagged-sea-turtle-released-in-hainan/|title=Satellite-tagged sea turtle released in Hainan|author=|date=28 March 2012|website=hawaii247.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=sfishermen>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-20775-sea-turtles-911-release-satellite-tagged-sea-turtle-in-hainan.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620034355/http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-20775-sea-turtles-911-release-satellite-tagged-sea-turtle-in-hainan.html |archive-date=2012-06-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\n[[File:Frederick Yeh featured in magazine as public figure.jpg|thumb|right|Local media featuring Frederick Yeh as a public figure who gives a voice to endangered sea turtles.]]\n\nYeh promotes environmental conservation through publicized sea turtle release events in China, and is vocal about ending sea turtle [[Exploitation of natural resources|exploitation]] in Chinese media.<ref name=cm1>{{Cite web |url=http://hi.people.com.cn/n/2012/0327/c231190-16881075.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-04 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130101220538/http://hi.people.com.cn/n/2012/0327/c231190-16881075.html |archive-date=2013-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=cm2>{{Cite web |url=http://ep.chinaluxus.com/Act/20120828/215894.html#picview |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909064731/http://ep.chinaluxus.com/Act/20120828/215894.html#picview |archive-date=2012-09-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=cm3>{{Cite web |url=http://roll.sohu.com/20120328/n339138562.shtml |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017012441/http://roll.sohu.com/20120328/n339138562.shtml |archive-date=2013-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=cm4>{{cite web|url=http://news.hainan.net/newshtml08/2012w3r27/855570f0.htm|title=\u6d77\u5357\u65b0\u95fb-\u6d77\u5357\u65b0\u95fb\u4e2d\u5fc3-\u6d77\u5357\u5728\u7ebf \u6d77\u5357\u4e00\u5bb6|author=|date=|website=news.hainan.net|accessdate=21 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429165555/http://news.hainan.net/newshtml08/2012w3r27/855570f0.htm|archive-date=29 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=cm5>{{cite web|url=http://news.hexun.com/2012-03-27/139763126.html|title=\u4e24\u767e\u591a\u65a4\u6d77\u9f9f\u9675\u6c34\u6401\u6d45 \u56fd\u9645\u6d77\u9f9f\u4fdd\u62a4\u7ec4\u7ec7\u653e\u751f-\u65b0\u95fb\u9891\u9053-\u548c\u8baf\u7f51|author=|date=|website=news.hexun.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=cm6>{{cite web|url=http://v.hinews.cn/page-51659.html|title=3000\u65a4\u9cb8\u9ca8\u8bef\u649e\u6e14\u7f51 \u6c34\u751f\u91ce\u751f\u52a8\u7269\u4fdd\u62a4\u5206\u4f1a\u7ec4\u7ec7\u653e\u751f- \u6d77\u7f51\u5bbd\u9891|author=|date=|website=v.hinews.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=cm7>{{cite web|url=http://www.hi.chinanews.com/hnnew/2012-07-05/244719.html|title=3000\u65a4\u9cb8\u9ca8\u8bef\u649e\u6e14\u7f51 \u6d77\u5357\u52a8\u7269\u4fdd\u62a4\u4f1a\u7ec4\u7ec7\u653e\u751f|author=|date=|website=www.hi.chinanews.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=cm8>{{cite web|url=http://ngdsb.hinews.cn/html/2012-07/05/content_495225.htm|title=\u5357\u56fd\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5\u00b7\u6570\u5b57\u62a5\u520a|author=|date=|website=ngdsb.hinews.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=releasemedia1>{{cite web|url=http://hnrb.hinews.cn/html/2013-08/11/content_2_5.htm|title=\u6d77\u5357\u65e5\u62a5\u6570\u5b57\u62a5-\"\u5927\u6d77\u624d\u662f\u4f60\u4eec\u7684\u5bb6\"|author=|date=|website=hnrb.hinews.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=releasemedia2>{{cite web|author=\u4e2d\u9f99\u7f8e\u56fd\u9645 |url=http://bbs.tianya.cn/post-838-34922-1.shtml |title=911\u56fd\u9645\u6d77\u9f9f\u6551\u52a9\u7ec4\u7ec7\u521b\u59cb\u4eba\u53f6\u653f\u5ef7\u4e13\u8bbf_\u516c\u76ca\u540c\u884c_\u8bba\u575b_\u5929\u6daf\u793e\u533a |publisher=Bbs.tianya.cn |date=2012-10-19 |accessdate=2019-10-27}}</ref> As he has said, \"Their survival is our responsibility; we must create hope.\"<ref name=createhope>{{Cite web |url=http://ep.chinaluxus.com/Glv/20120828/215879.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901210931/http://ep.chinaluxus.com/Glv/20120828/215879.html |archive-date=2012-09-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During interviews with journalists, he is known to use metaphors to facilitate the understanding of environmental conservation to the public.  Yeh cautioned the Chinese public not to delay the increased protection efforts of sea turtles until they decline to the same population level as China's cherished [[Giant panda]].<ref name=interview1>{{cite web|url=http://hnrb.hinews.cn/html/2013-08/14/content_4_1.htm|title=\u6d77\u5357\u65e5\u62a5\u6570\u5b57\u62a5-\u6d77\u9f9f\u6fd2\u5371\u8fde\u95ee4\u4e2a\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48|author=|date=|website=hnrb.hinews.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> In addressing [[marine pollution]] problems in China, he reminds the public not to treat the ocean as an enormous toilet and garbage dump.<ref name=interview1 />\n\nIn China, poached sea turtles include endangered [[Green sea turtles]] raised primarily for consumption of their meat, and the [[critically endangered]] [[Hawksbill sea turtle]] raised for the trade in shell products such as jewelry, combs, eyeglass frames, and preserved trophies.<ref name=paul /><ref name=world>{{cite web|url=http://www.theworld.org/2012/02/china-turtle-poaching/|title=Sea Turtle Poaching and High Demand in China|author=|date=|website=theworld.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=pri>{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/science/environment/high-demand-for-sea-turtles-in-china-sends-poachers-toward-philippines-8358.html|title=High demand for sea turtles in China sends poachers toward Philippines|author=|date=|website=pri.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> During a speech condemning the use of sea turtle products, Yeh echoed [[Yao Ming]]'s famous quotation, \"When the buying stops, the killing can too.\"<ref name=sbalazs /><ref name=mbalazs />\n\nDeclaring July 4, 2012, as a day of freedom for all marine animals, Yeh led the release of an endangered [[Whale shark]] that had been caught accidentally by a Chinese fishing boat as [[bycatch]], as well as two Green sea turtles.<ref name=freedom>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaii247.com/2012/07/05/freedom-release-whale-shark-and-sea-turtles-in-china/|title=Freedom release: Whale shark and sea turtles in China|author=|date=5 July 2012|website=hawaii247.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=shark>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-22425-sea-turtles-911-releases-whale-shark-and-sea-turtles-in-hainan.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023042802/http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-22425-sea-turtles-911-releases-whale-shark-and-sea-turtles-in-hainan.html |archive-date=2013-10-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=hotel>{{Cite web |url=http://hotelhainan.com/sea-turtles-whale-shark-released-in-hainan/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017022027/http://hotelhainan.com/sea-turtles-whale-shark-released-in-hainan/ |archive-date=2013-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At this event, he proclaimed, \"Sea turtle conservation does not only involve sea turtles. When we protect [[charismatic species]] such as whale sharks, those efforts spill over and protect sea turtles as well. These two animals share the ocean, and we must learn to share the ocean with them.\u201d<ref name=freedom /><ref name=shark /><ref name=hotel /> Holding humans accountable for sea turtle and Whale shark endangerment, he added that, \"protecting them is humankind's responsibility.\"<ref name=freedom /><ref name=shark /><ref name=hotel />\n\n[[File:Yao Ming and Frederick Yeh release endangered sea turtle back into the wild.jpg|thumb|left|Frederick Yeh and [[Yao Ming]], [[NBA]] basketball star and China's top celebrity, release an endangered sea turtle back into the wild during an event to raise public awareness for environmental conservation.]]\n\nOn March 23, 2013, Yeh spoke out on [[climate change]] and [[global warming]] during [[Earth Hour]], the one hour when the [[World Wildlife Fund]] (WWF) encourages businesses and households worldwide to switch off their lights to raise awareness on climate change.  Sea turtle eggs are influenced by a biological process known as [[Temperature-dependent sex determination]], meaning that their gender is determined by the environmental temperature.<ref name=tsd>{{cite journal |pmid=7079758 | volume=216 | issue=4551 | title=Temperature-dependent sex determination: current practices threaten conservation of sea turtles | year=1982 | journal=Science | pages=1245\u20137 | last1 = Morreale | first1 = SJ | last2 = Ruiz | first2 = GJ | last3 = Spotila | first3 = JR | last4 = Standora | first4 = EA | doi=10.1126/science.7079758}}</ref>  Yeh reminded the public, \u201cAs the global climate\u2019s average temperature increases, more females will be hatched, jeopardizing sea turtle populations with an unbalanced sex ratio.\u201d<ref name=earthhourmonga>{{cite web|url=http://blog.mongabay.com/2013/04/05/sea-turtles-released-during-earth-hour/|title=Sea Turtles Released During Earth Hour|author=|date=|website=blog.mongabay.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=earthhourroar>{{Cite web |url=http://roarhawaii.org/sea-turtles-released-during-earth-hour/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016232300/http://roarhawaii.org/sea-turtles-released-during-earth-hour/ |archive-date=2013-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with China's official state-run news agency, [[Xinhua News Agency]], Yeh called for a celebrity to help save endangered sea turtles by raising public awareness.<ref name=\"fyeh3\" />  In 2014, Yeh was answered by former [[NBA]] basketball superstar [[Yao Ming]], who consistently ranked #1 on the [[Forbes China Celebrity 100]].<ref name=\"yaoming6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/03/18/chinese-celebrities-beijing-olympics-yao-ming-business-media-chinas-top-celebrities.html|title=Forbes China Celebrity List|first=Russell|last=Flannery|date=|website=forbes.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-03/19/content_7594549.htm|title=Yao tops Forbes China Celebrity list for the 6th time|author=|date=|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.china.org.cn/english/NM-e/86932.htm|title=Yao Ming Tops Forbes' China Celebrity List|author=|date=|website=www.china.org.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>  Yao Ming joined Yeh in his public sea turtle release events and the duo set free rescued turtles back into the wild, raising awareness together that leads people to \"an epiphany that turtles belong in the wild, and not in the market.\u201d<ref name=\"yaoming1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china-insider/article/1534600/former-basketball-star-yao-ming-calls-protection-sea-turtles|title=Former basketball star Yao Ming calls for protection of sea turtles|author=|date=|website=scmp.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/12172-nba-star-yao-ming-saves-endangered-sea-turtles|title=NBA Star Yao Ming Saves Endangered Sea Turtles|author=|date=17 June 2014|website=looktothestars.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=cnn /><ref name=\"yaoming3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sci-news.com/biology/science-yao-ming-green-turtles-02025.html|title=Basketball Star Saves Endangered Green Turtles - Biology - Sci-News.com|author=|date=|website=sci-news.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ecorazzi.com/2014/06/18/former-nba-star-yao-ming-saves-sea-turtles/|title=Former NBA Star Yao Ming Saves Sea Turtles : Ecorazzi|author=|date=|website=www.ecorazzi.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ortablu.org/news/world-news/former-nba-star-yao-ming-saves-sea-turtles|title=Former NBA Star Yao Ming Saves Sea Turtles \u00ab  Orta Blu|author=|date=|website=Orta Blu|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2015, Yeh led a large-scale event in which five (5) rescued sea turtles were released from different beaches around the island of Hainan to maximize conservation awareness for [[World Oceans Day]] as recognized by the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|title = World Oceans Day - 8 June|url = https://www.un.org/en/events/oceansday/|website = www.un.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = EN}}</ref>  Yeh said, \"The emotional experience of watching a sea turtle swim for freedom back to nature reminds us that we are all connected to the vast ocean expanse, and thus have the responsibility to protect them for our future generations.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|title = Sea Turtle 911 - World Ocean Day 2015 - World Ocean Network|url = http://www.worldoceannetwork.org/portfolio-posts/sea-turtle-911-world-ocean-day-2015/|website = World Ocean Network|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:US Ambassador Max Baucus and Sea Turtles 911 Frederick Yeh release rescued turtle.jpg|thumb|right|Frederick Yeh and [[United States Ambassador to China|United States Ambassador]] and [[List of United States Senators from Montana|former U.S. Senator]] [[Max Baucus]] release a satellite tracked sea turtle.]]\n\nOn January 15, 2016, [[United States Ambassador to China]] and [[List of United States Senators from Montana|former U.S. Senator]] [[Max Baucus]] joined Yeh in the release of two rescued turtles named [[Harvard]] and [[Yale]] into the South China Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yalealumnimagazine.com/articles/4282-shell-game|title=Shell game|author=|date=|website=yalealumnimagazine.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2016-02/03/content_23373150.htm|title=US ambassador sends New Year greetings in video-Americas-chinadaily.com.cn|author=|date=|website=usa.chinadaily.com.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>  According to Yeh, the U.S. Ambassador\u2019s charitable act was recognized as symbolic because \"Sea turtles are charismatic, migratory animals that serve as natural ambassadors of the ocean; as communities and countries work together to preserve this flagship species for future generations, our shared mission to save sea turtles nurtures a peaceful platform of common grounds to improve community and international relations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ecopartnerships.lbl.gov/news/sea-turtles-911-and|title=Sea Turtles 911 and U.S. Ambassador Release Endangered Sea Turtles in the South China Sea - EcoPartnerships|author=|date=|website=ecopartnerships.lbl.gov|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\n[[File:Gary Locke and Frederick Yeh showing support for sea turtle conservation at 2018 conference in Silicon Valley.jpg|thumb|left|Frederick Yeh and Ambassador Gary Locke, former [[United States Secretary of Commerce|U.S. Secretary of Commerce]] and [[List of Governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]], show support for sea turtle conservation at their committee meeting.]]\n\nOn March 30, 2013, the [[Ministry of Agriculture of the People's Republic of China]] honored Yeh the 2012 [[Popular Science]] Award, in recognition for his significant contributions to public awareness of marine conservation.<ref name=haichang1>{{Cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/local/2013-03/30/m_115219425.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114185110/http://news.xinhuanet.com/local/2013-03/30/m_115219425.htm |archive-date=2013-11-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=haichang2>{{cite web|url=http://www.nawca.org.cn/haichang-2013/list.asp?unid=1642|title=\u5168\u56fd\u6c34\u751f\u91ce\u751f\u52a8\u7269\u4fdd\u62a4\u5206\u4f1a |author=|date=|website=www.nawca.org.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 9, 2015, the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] officially recognized Yeh as a marine turtle expert in the China region.<ref>{{cite web|title = Member List by Country|url = http://iucn-mtsg.org/members/member-list-by-country/|website = IUCN SSC Marine Turtle Specialist Group|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2015, [[Duke University]] awarded Yeh with the prestigious Global Fellowship in Marine Conservation.<ref>{{cite web|title = 2015 Participants {{!}} Marine Conservation Summer Institute|url = http://superpod.ml.duke.edu/mcsi/2015-participants/|website = superpod.ml.duke.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2015, the [[United States Department of State]] and the [[National Development and Reform Commission]] supported Yeh to lead the [[China\u2013United States relations|U.S.-China]] bilateral partnership to save endangered sea turtles.<ref>{{cite web|title = US, China Broaden Collaboration on Climate Issues|url = http://www.voanews.com/content/us-china-broaden-collaboration-on-climate-issues/2834952.html|website = VOA|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = U.S.-China EcoPartnerships Program|url = https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2015/06/244111.htm|website = U.S. Department of State|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref><ref name=cnn /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://revitalizationnews.com/article/us-china-partnership-funds-program-rescue-restore-sea-turtles-hainan-island|title=US-China partnership funds the rescue and restoration of sea turtles on Hainan Island|author=|date=|website=revitalizationnews.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 28, 2015, [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] interviewed Yeh as their Featured Explorer to inspire children to save sea turtles.<ref>{{cite web|title = National Geographic Features Frederick Yeh to Inspire Children to Save Sea Turtles|url = http://www.seaturtles911.org/news/national-geographic-frederick-yeh-inspires-kids-save-sea-turtles.htm|website = NatGeo|accessdate = 2015-07-28}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2018, the [[Committee of 100 (United States)|Committee of 100]] officially recognized Yeh as their Next Generation Leader to advance the betterment of U.S.-China relations.<ref>{{cite web|title = Announcing Committee of 100 Next Generation Leaders 2018|url = http://www.committee100.org/announcements/announcing-committee-of-100-next-generation-leaders-2018/|website = C100|accessdate = 2018-06-07}}</ref>  Committee delegations have been invited to give briefings to top officials at the [[White House]] and [[Zhongnanhai]].<ref name = chinadailyc100>{{cite journal | author = Qidong Zhang | date = April 25, 2014 | title = C-100 strengthens US-China relations | journal = [[China Daily]] | url = http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/2014-04/25/content_17467034.htm | access-date = April 26, 2017 }}</ref>  Prominent members of the committee include Ambassador [[Gary Locke]], former [[United States Secretary of Commerce]] and [[List of Governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]]; [[I. M. Pei]], renowned architect; [[Yo-Yo Ma]], master cellist; [[Jerry Yang]], Founder of [[Yahoo!]]; [[David Ho (scientist)|David Ho]], [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]]'s 1996 [[Time Magazine Person of the Year|Man of the Year]] for pioneering [[HIV/AIDS research]]; [[Michelle Kwan]], Olympic medalist in figure skating; and [[Steve Chen]], Founder of [[YouTube]].<ref name = Comm100roster>{{cite web | title = Committee of 100 Members | publisher = Committee of 100 | url=https://committee100.org/member-roster/ | access-date = April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.seaturtles911.org/ Sea Turtles 911]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeh, Frederick}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American conservationists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American social entrepreneurs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Frederick C. Yeh\n|image = Frederick_C._Yeh_releases_rescued_sea_turtle_back_in_the_ocean_with_children,_Apr_2013.jpg\n|caption = Yeh releases a rescued sea turtle back in the ocean with disadvantaged children\n|alma_mater = {{plain list|\n*[[Johns Hopkins University]] \n*[[Duke University]] }}\n|occupation = [[social entrepreneur]] <br> [[conservation biologist]]\n|known_for = The unlikely sea turtle savior<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/travel/story/20150521-in-china-saving-sea-turtles-from-soup|title=The unlikely sea turtle saviour|first=Amanda|last=Ruggeri|date=|website=bbc.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> \n}}\n\n'''Frederick C. Yeh''' is an [[United States|American]] [[social entrepreneur]] and [[conservation biologist]] who founded [[Sea Turtles 911]], a [[non-profit]] [[sea turtle]] rescue and [[conservation organization]] that operates in the United States and China.<ref name=bbc /><ref name=cnn>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/travel/article/china-hainan-sea-turtles|title=Could rare sea turtles return to the Hawaii of China?|author=|date=28 August 2017|website=cnn.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=fyeh2>{{Cite web |url=http://en.visithainan.gov.cn/en/mt_newsview-1776.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131016152546/http://en.visithainan.gov.cn/en/mt_newsview-1776.htm |archive-date=2013-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=fyeh3>{{Cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/sci/2013-09/03/c_132688041.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114185041/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/sci/2013-09/03/c_132688041.htm |archive-date=2013-11-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=fyeh4>{{cite web|url=http://english.people.com.cn/90882/8375839.html|title=Sea Turtles 911 dedicated to sea turtle conservation - People's Daily Online|first=|last=F_100542|date=|website=english.people.com.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=chineseamerican1>{{cite web|url=http://www.asamnews.com/2013/09/03/english-news-cn-chinese-american-dedicates-career-to-saving-endangered-turtles/ |title=English News.CN: Chinese American Dedicates Career to Saving Endangered Turtles |publisher=AsAm News |date=2013-09-03 |accessdate=2019-10-27}}</ref><ref name=paul>{{Cite web |url=http://www.paulhiltonphotography.com/index.php/field-notes/30 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-11-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111109104419/http://www.paulhiltonphotography.com/index.php/field-notes/30 |archive-date=2011-11-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.dw.com/generationchange/2011/11/saving-sea-turtles-in-hainan/|title=Saving Sea Turtles in Hainan - Uncategorized - Generation Change - DW.COM|author=|date=|website=dw.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=german>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/saving-endangered-sea-turtles-in-hainan/a-6665063|title=Saving endangered Sea Turtles in Hainan - DW - 22.11.2011|first=Deutsche Welle|last=(www.dw.com)|date=|website=DW.COM|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=bf>{{Cite web |url=http://bestfriends.org/News-And-Features/News/China--Until-the-seas-are-safe-again/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130703202901/http://bestfriends.org/News-And-Features/News/China--Until-the-seas-are-safe-again/ |archive-date=2013-07-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=fyeh5>{{cite web|url=http://english.cri.cn/11354/2013/08/24/2561s783859.htm|title=Sea Turtles 911 Dedicated to Sea Turtle Conservation|author=|date=|website=english.cri.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\n\nYeh attended [[Montgomery County Public Schools (Maryland)|Montgomery County Public Schools]], including [[Thomas Sprigg Wootton High School|Thomas S. Wootton High School]], and graduated from [[Johns Hopkins University]] and [[Duke University]].<ref name=paul /><ref name=german /><ref name=bf /> In 2007, Yeh discovered that [[endangered sea turtles]] on [[Hainan|Hainan island, China]], were being sold illegally for their meat and shell.<ref name=\"fyeh1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/806004.shtml|title=Sea Turtles 911 dedicated to sea turtle conservation - Global Times|last=Times|first=Global|date=|website=www.globaltimes.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=fyeh3 /><ref name=paul /><ref name=german /><ref name=bf /> During an interview with [[CNN]], Yeh described, \"I felt really hopeless at that time ... You would see land turtles and freshwater turtles (in the market) and some of those are legal, but when you see a sea turtle it's clearly not supposed to be there and that's shocking to see.\"<ref name=cnn /> This finding was emotionally disturbing to Yeh and became a turning point in his life, which led to the founding of the first non-profit organization working for the advancement of sea turtle protection and conservation in China.<ref name=bbc />\n\n== Sea Turtles 911 ==\n\n{{Main|Sea Turtles 911}}\n[[File:Coast Guard Police Rescue Sea Turtle for Frederick Yeh.jpg|thumb|left|Frederick Yeh and coast guard police rescue a sick sea turtle.]]\n[[File:Sea turtle rehabilitation with fluid therapy by Frederick Yeh.jpg|thumb|right|Frederick Yeh provides medical treatments to a sick sea turtle.]]\nDespite the desperate state of sea turtles in China, Yeh was inspired in 2008 when he saw wild sea turtles undisturbed by people as the animals were naturally basking on public beaches in Hawaii.<ref name=basking1>{{cite web|url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/time-year-turtle-beach-oahu-106738.html|title=The Best Time of the Year for Turtle Beach, Oahu|author=|date=|website=usatoday.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=basking2>{{cite web|url=http://www.fpir.noaa.gov/PRD/prd_volunteer_opps.html|title=Home page of NOAA Fisheries Service - Pacific Islands Regional Office|first=US Department of Commerce, NOAA, National Marine Fisheries|last=Service|date=|website=www.fpir.noaa.gov|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>  As Yeh said on a CNN interview, \"When you see the sea turtles in Hawaii, how great they are, it's worth it when you can envision that and hope that one day it will happen in Hainan, one day, in China.\"<ref name=cnn />  This experience led Yeh to believe that sea turtles and people could live in harmony and that there was still hope in China because of the successful sea turtle conservation efforts in Hawaii.  According to the global authority on nature conservation, [[International Union for the Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN), the sea turtles of the Hawaiian Islands were also once under the threat of near [[extinction]], but are now thriving<ref name=sbalazs>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-20205-iucn-sea-turtles-911-release-tagged-sea-turtle-in-sanya.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925190414/http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-20205-iucn-sea-turtles-911-release-tagged-sea-turtle-in-sanya.html |archive-date=2012-09-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=mbalazs>{{cite web|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2012/0306-pod-seaturtle911.html#|title=Animal photos of the day: green sea turtle saved in China|author=|date=6 March 2012|website=mongabay.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> and their conservation status reclassified as \"Least Concern\" according to the [[IUCN Red List]].<ref name=iucnred>{{cite web|url=http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/16285718/0|title=Chelonia mydas (Hawaiian subpopulation) (Green Turtle, Hawaiian Green Turtle, Tortuga Blanca)|author=|date=|website=www.iucnredlist.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>  Thus, Yeh established Sea Turtles 911 under Hawaiian jurisdiction, and changed the course of his life by moving to China to save the sea turtles he had hopelessly witnessed being sold, earning him the nickname \"The unlikely sea turtle savior\" by the [[BBC]].<ref name=bbc /><ref name=cnn /> Building a floating sea turtle hospital in a Chinese fishing village known for its extensive sea turtle [[poaching]], Yeh makes a point to work with people of all types to support sea turtle conservation in the area, including government officials, academia, fishermen and poachers, community members, local and international volunteers.<ref name=cnn /><ref name=hospital1>{{cite web|url=http://www.china.org.cn/environment/2013-09/04/content_29924143.htm|title=Floating hospital saves sea turtles - China.org.cn|first=|last=\u5f13\u8fce\u6625|date=|website=www.china.org.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=hospital2>{{cite web|url=http://www.upi.com/Science_News/2013/09/03/Floating-hospital-in-China-dedicated-to-caring-for-sea-turtles/UPI-18231378254043/|title=Floating hospital in China dedicated to caring for sea turtles|author=|date=|website=upi.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=hospital3>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/xinhua/2013-09-03/content_10025472.html|title=Around China: Floating hospital saves sea turtles-chinadaily.com.cn|author=|date=|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=inouye>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaii247.com/2012/09/04/chinese-police-rescue-inouye-the-turtle/|title=Chinese police rescue Inouye the turtle|author=|date=4 September 2012|website=hawaii247.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> At a sea turtle release event held at the [[Ritz-Carlton]], [[Sanya]], Yeh stated, \"For our release events, if we can bring multiple sectors in our community together, it will be very beneficial to sea turtle conservation in China. It is my hope that we can put other issues aside and agree on sea turtle rights, for the advancement of sea turtle conservation.\"<ref name=iost>{{cite web|url=http://www.ioseaturtles.org/headline_detail.php?id=2207|title=Indian Ocean - South-East Asian Marine Turtle Memorandum of Understanding|author=|date=|website=www.ioseaturtles.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=ritzquote>{{Cite web |url=http://sanyaexpat.com/index.php/news-sanya-hainan-china-world-sanyabay-dadonghai-yalongwan-shimeibay-haitangbay-haikou-shanghai/seaturtles911-ritzcarlton-yalongbay-sany?blog=1 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110826171224/http://sanyaexpat.com/index.php/news-sanya-hainan-china-world-sanyabay-dadonghai-yalongwan-shimeibay-haitangbay-haikou-shanghai/seaturtles911-ritzcarlton-yalongbay-sany?blog=1 |archive-date=2011-08-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Local community members, including fishermen and coast guard police, describe Yeh as a true \"[[Haigui]]\" or a \"returning sea turtle,\"<ref name=bbc/> and defer to his expertise when endangered sea turtles are rescued and in need of medical attention.<ref name=inouye /><ref name=hawaii>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaii247.com/2012/03/27/satellite-tagged-sea-turtle-released-in-hainan/|title=Satellite-tagged sea turtle released in Hainan|author=|date=28 March 2012|website=hawaii247.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=sfishermen>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-20775-sea-turtles-911-release-satellite-tagged-sea-turtle-in-hainan.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620034355/http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-20775-sea-turtles-911-release-satellite-tagged-sea-turtle-in-hainan.html |archive-date=2012-06-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\n[[File:Frederick Yeh featured in magazine as public figure.jpg|thumb|right|Local media featuring Frederick Yeh as a public figure who gives a voice to endangered sea turtles.]]\n\nYeh promotes environmental conservation through publicized sea turtle release events in China, and is vocal about ending sea turtle [[Exploitation of natural resources|exploitation]] in Chinese media.<ref name=cm1>{{Cite web |url=http://hi.people.com.cn/n/2012/0327/c231190-16881075.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-04 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130101220538/http://hi.people.com.cn/n/2012/0327/c231190-16881075.html |archive-date=2013-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=cm2>{{Cite web |url=http://ep.chinaluxus.com/Act/20120828/215894.html#picview |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120909064731/http://ep.chinaluxus.com/Act/20120828/215894.html#picview |archive-date=2012-09-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=cm3>{{Cite web |url=http://roll.sohu.com/20120328/n339138562.shtml |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017012441/http://roll.sohu.com/20120328/n339138562.shtml |archive-date=2013-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=cm4>{{cite web|url=http://news.hainan.net/newshtml08/2012w3r27/855570f0.htm|title=\u6d77\u5357\u65b0\u95fb-\u6d77\u5357\u65b0\u95fb\u4e2d\u5fc3-\u6d77\u5357\u5728\u7ebf \u6d77\u5357\u4e00\u5bb6|author=|date=|website=news.hainan.net|accessdate=21 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429165555/http://news.hainan.net/newshtml08/2012w3r27/855570f0.htm|archive-date=29 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=cm5>{{cite web|url=http://news.hexun.com/2012-03-27/139763126.html|title=\u4e24\u767e\u591a\u65a4\u6d77\u9f9f\u9675\u6c34\u6401\u6d45 \u56fd\u9645\u6d77\u9f9f\u4fdd\u62a4\u7ec4\u7ec7\u653e\u751f-\u65b0\u95fb\u9891\u9053-\u548c\u8baf\u7f51|author=|date=|website=news.hexun.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=cm6>{{cite web|url=http://v.hinews.cn/page-51659.html|title=3000\u65a4\u9cb8\u9ca8\u8bef\u649e\u6e14\u7f51 \u6c34\u751f\u91ce\u751f\u52a8\u7269\u4fdd\u62a4\u5206\u4f1a\u7ec4\u7ec7\u653e\u751f- \u6d77\u7f51\u5bbd\u9891|author=|date=|website=v.hinews.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=cm7>{{cite web|url=http://www.hi.chinanews.com/hnnew/2012-07-05/244719.html|title=3000\u65a4\u9cb8\u9ca8\u8bef\u649e\u6e14\u7f51 \u6d77\u5357\u52a8\u7269\u4fdd\u62a4\u4f1a\u7ec4\u7ec7\u653e\u751f|author=|date=|website=www.hi.chinanews.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=cm8>{{cite web|url=http://ngdsb.hinews.cn/html/2012-07/05/content_495225.htm|title=\u5357\u56fd\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5\u00b7\u6570\u5b57\u62a5\u520a|author=|date=|website=ngdsb.hinews.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=releasemedia1>{{cite web|url=http://hnrb.hinews.cn/html/2013-08/11/content_2_5.htm|title=\u6d77\u5357\u65e5\u62a5\u6570\u5b57\u62a5-\"\u5927\u6d77\u624d\u662f\u4f60\u4eec\u7684\u5bb6\"|author=|date=|website=hnrb.hinews.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=releasemedia2>{{cite web|author=\u4e2d\u9f99\u7f8e\u56fd\u9645 |url=http://bbs.tianya.cn/post-838-34922-1.shtml |title=911\u56fd\u9645\u6d77\u9f9f\u6551\u52a9\u7ec4\u7ec7\u521b\u59cb\u4eba\u53f6\u653f\u5ef7\u4e13\u8bbf_\u516c\u76ca\u540c\u884c_\u8bba\u575b_\u5929\u6daf\u793e\u533a |publisher=Bbs.tianya.cn |date=2012-10-19 |accessdate=2019-10-27}}</ref> As he has said, \"Their survival is our responsibility; we must create hope.\"<ref name=createhope>{{Cite web |url=http://ep.chinaluxus.com/Glv/20120828/215879.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-09-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901210931/http://ep.chinaluxus.com/Glv/20120828/215879.html |archive-date=2012-09-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> During interviews with journalists, he is known to use metaphors to facilitate the understanding of environmental conservation to the public.  Yeh cautioned the Chinese public not to delay the increased protection efforts of sea turtles until they decline to the same population level as China's cherished [[Giant panda]].<ref name=interview1>{{cite web|url=http://hnrb.hinews.cn/html/2013-08/14/content_4_1.htm|title=\u6d77\u5357\u65e5\u62a5\u6570\u5b57\u62a5-\u6d77\u9f9f\u6fd2\u5371\u8fde\u95ee4\u4e2a\u4e3a\u4ec0\u4e48|author=|date=|website=hnrb.hinews.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> In addressing [[marine pollution]] problems in China, he reminds the public not to treat the ocean as an enormous toilet and garbage dump.<ref name=interview1 />\n\nIn China, poached sea turtles include endangered [[Green sea turtles]] raised primarily for consumption of their meat, and the [[critically endangered]] [[Hawksbill sea turtle]] raised for the trade in shell products such as jewelry, combs, eyeglass frames, and preserved trophies.<ref name=paul /><ref name=world>{{cite web|url=http://www.theworld.org/2012/02/china-turtle-poaching/|title=Sea Turtle Poaching and High Demand in China|author=|date=|website=theworld.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=pri>{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/science/environment/high-demand-for-sea-turtles-in-china-sends-poachers-toward-philippines-8358.html|title=High demand for sea turtles in China sends poachers toward Philippines|author=|date=|website=pri.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref> During a speech condemning the use of sea turtle products, Yeh echoed [[Yao Ming]]'s famous quotation, \"When the buying stops, the killing can too.\"<ref name=sbalazs /><ref name=mbalazs />\n\nDeclaring July 4, 2012, as a day of freedom for all marine animals, Yeh led the release of an endangered [[Whale shark]] that had been caught accidentally by a Chinese fishing boat as [[bycatch]], as well as two Green sea turtles.<ref name=freedom>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaii247.com/2012/07/05/freedom-release-whale-shark-and-sea-turtles-in-china/|title=Freedom release: Whale shark and sea turtles in China|author=|date=5 July 2012|website=hawaii247.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=shark>{{Cite web |url=http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-22425-sea-turtles-911-releases-whale-shark-and-sea-turtles-in-hainan.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023042802/http://www.whatsonsanya.com/news-22425-sea-turtles-911-releases-whale-shark-and-sea-turtles-in-hainan.html |archive-date=2013-10-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=hotel>{{Cite web |url=http://hotelhainan.com/sea-turtles-whale-shark-released-in-hainan/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017022027/http://hotelhainan.com/sea-turtles-whale-shark-released-in-hainan/ |archive-date=2013-10-17 |url-status=dead }}</ref> At this event, he proclaimed, \"Sea turtle conservation does not only involve sea turtles. When we protect [[charismatic species]] such as whale sharks, those efforts spill over and protect sea turtles as well. These two animals share the ocean, and we must learn to share the ocean with them.\u201d<ref name=freedom /><ref name=shark /><ref name=hotel /> Holding humans accountable for sea turtle and Whale shark endangerment, he added that, \"protecting them is humankind's responsibility.\"<ref name=freedom /><ref name=shark /><ref name=hotel />\n\n[[File:Yao Ming and Frederick Yeh release endangered sea turtle back into the wild.jpg|thumb|left|Frederick Yeh and [[Yao Ming]], [[NBA]] basketball star and China's top celebrity, release an endangered sea turtle back into the wild during an event to raise public awareness for environmental conservation.]]\n\nOn March 23, 2013, Yeh spoke out on [[climate change]] and [[global warming]] during [[Earth Hour]], the one hour when the [[World Wildlife Fund]] (WWF) encourages businesses and households worldwide to switch off their lights to raise awareness on climate change.  Sea turtle eggs are influenced by a biological process known as [[Temperature-dependent sex determination]], meaning that their gender is determined by the environmental temperature.<ref name=tsd>{{cite journal |pmid=7079758 | volume=216 | issue=4551 | title=Temperature-dependent sex determination: current practices threaten conservation of sea turtles | year=1982 | journal=Science | pages=1245\u20137 | last1 = Morreale | first1 = SJ | last2 = Ruiz | first2 = GJ | last3 = Spotila | first3 = JR | last4 = Standora | first4 = EA | doi=10.1126/science.7079758}}</ref>  Yeh reminded the public, \u201cAs the global climate\u2019s average temperature increases, more females will be hatched, jeopardizing sea turtle populations with an unbalanced sex ratio.\u201d<ref name=earthhourmonga>{{cite web|url=http://blog.mongabay.com/2013/04/05/sea-turtles-released-during-earth-hour/|title=Sea Turtles Released During Earth Hour|author=|date=|website=blog.mongabay.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=earthhourroar>{{Cite web |url=http://roarhawaii.org/sea-turtles-released-during-earth-hour/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016232300/http://roarhawaii.org/sea-turtles-released-during-earth-hour/ |archive-date=2013-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with China's official state-run news agency, [[Xinhua News Agency]], Yeh called for a celebrity to help save endangered sea turtles by raising public awareness.<ref name=\"fyeh3\" />  In 2014, Yeh was answered by former [[NBA]] basketball superstar [[Yao Ming]], who consistently ranked #1 on the [[Forbes China Celebrity 100]].<ref name=\"yaoming6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/03/18/chinese-celebrities-beijing-olympics-yao-ming-business-media-chinas-top-celebrities.html|title=Forbes China Celebrity List|first=Russell|last=Flannery|date=|website=forbes.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2009-03/19/content_7594549.htm|title=Yao tops Forbes China Celebrity list for the 6th time|author=|date=|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming8\">{{cite web|url=http://www.china.org.cn/english/NM-e/86932.htm|title=Yao Ming Tops Forbes' China Celebrity List|author=|date=|website=www.china.org.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>  Yao Ming joined Yeh in his public sea turtle release events and the duo set free rescued turtles back into the wild, raising awareness together that leads people to \"an epiphany that turtles belong in the wild, and not in the market.\u201d<ref name=\"yaoming1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/china-insider/article/1534600/former-basketball-star-yao-ming-calls-protection-sea-turtles|title=Former basketball star Yao Ming calls for protection of sea turtles|author=|date=|website=scmp.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/12172-nba-star-yao-ming-saves-endangered-sea-turtles|title=NBA Star Yao Ming Saves Endangered Sea Turtles|author=|date=17 June 2014|website=looktothestars.org|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=cnn /><ref name=\"yaoming3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sci-news.com/biology/science-yao-ming-green-turtles-02025.html|title=Basketball Star Saves Endangered Green Turtles - Biology - Sci-News.com|author=|date=|website=sci-news.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ecorazzi.com/2014/06/18/former-nba-star-yao-ming-saves-sea-turtles/|title=Former NBA Star Yao Ming Saves Sea Turtles : Ecorazzi|author=|date=|website=www.ecorazzi.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yaoming5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ortablu.org/news/world-news/former-nba-star-yao-ming-saves-sea-turtles|title=Former NBA Star Yao Ming Saves Sea Turtles \u00ab  Orta Blu|author=|date=|website=Orta Blu|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 8, 2015, Yeh led a large-scale event in which five (5) rescued sea turtles were released from different beaches around the island of Hainan to maximize conservation awareness for [[World Oceans Day]] as recognized by the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|title = World Oceans Day - 8 June|url = https://www.un.org/en/events/oceansday/|website = www.un.org|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = EN}}</ref>  Yeh said, \"The emotional experience of watching a sea turtle swim for freedom back to nature reminds us that we are all connected to the vast ocean expanse, and thus have the responsibility to protect them for our future generations.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|title = Sea Turtle 911 - World Ocean Day 2015 - World Ocean Network|url = http://www.worldoceannetwork.org/portfolio-posts/sea-turtle-911-world-ocean-day-2015/|website = World Ocean Network|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:US Ambassador Max Baucus and Sea Turtles 911 Frederick Yeh release rescued turtle.jpg|thumb|right|Frederick Yeh and [[United States Ambassador to China|United States Ambassador]] and [[List of United States Senators from Montana|former U.S. Senator]] [[Max Baucus]] release a satellite tracked sea turtle.]]\n\nOn January 15, 2016, [[United States Ambassador to China]] and [[List of United States Senators from Montana|former U.S. Senator]] [[Max Baucus]] joined Yeh in the release of two rescued turtles named [[Harvard]] and [[Yale]] into the South China Sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://yalealumnimagazine.com/articles/4282-shell-game|title=Shell game|author=|date=|website=yalealumnimagazine.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/world/2016-02/03/content_23373150.htm|title=US ambassador sends New Year greetings in video-Americas-chinadaily.com.cn|author=|date=|website=usa.chinadaily.com.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>  According to Yeh, the U.S. Ambassador\u2019s charitable act was recognized as symbolic because \"Sea turtles are charismatic, migratory animals that serve as natural ambassadors of the ocean; as communities and countries work together to preserve this flagship species for future generations, our shared mission to save sea turtles nurtures a peaceful platform of common grounds to improve community and international relations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ecopartnerships.lbl.gov/news/sea-turtles-911-and|title=Sea Turtles 911 and U.S. Ambassador Release Endangered Sea Turtles in the South China Sea - EcoPartnerships|author=|date=|website=ecopartnerships.lbl.gov|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\n[[File:Gary Locke and Frederick Yeh showing support for sea turtle conservation at 2018 conference in Silicon Valley.jpg|thumb|left|Frederick Yeh and Ambassador Gary Locke, former [[United States Secretary of Commerce|U.S. Secretary of Commerce]] and [[List of Governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]], show support for sea turtle conservation at their committee meeting.]]\n\nOn March 30, 2013, the [[Ministry of Agriculture of the People's Republic of China]] honored Yeh the 2012 [[Popular Science]] Award, in recognition for his significant contributions to public awareness of marine conservation.<ref name=haichang1>{{Cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/local/2013-03/30/m_115219425.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131114185110/http://news.xinhuanet.com/local/2013-03/30/m_115219425.htm |archive-date=2013-11-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=haichang2>{{cite web|url=http://www.nawca.org.cn/haichang-2013/list.asp?unid=1642|title=\u5168\u56fd\u6c34\u751f\u91ce\u751f\u52a8\u7269\u4fdd\u62a4\u5206\u4f1a |author=|date=|website=www.nawca.org.cn|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 9, 2015, the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] officially recognized Yeh as a marine turtle expert in the China region.<ref>{{cite web|title = Member List by Country|url = http://iucn-mtsg.org/members/member-list-by-country/|website = IUCN SSC Marine Turtle Specialist Group|accessdate = 2015-10-16|language = en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 2015, [[Duke University]] awarded Yeh with the prestigious Global Fellowship in Marine Conservation.<ref>{{cite web|title = 2015 Participants {{!}} Marine Conservation Summer Institute|url = http://superpod.ml.duke.edu/mcsi/2015-participants/|website = superpod.ml.duke.edu|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2015, the [[United States Department of State]] and the [[National Development and Reform Commission]] supported Yeh to lead the [[China\u2013United States relations|U.S.-China]] bilateral partnership to save endangered sea turtles.<ref>{{cite web|title = US, China Broaden Collaboration on Climate Issues|url = http://www.voanews.com/content/us-china-broaden-collaboration-on-climate-issues/2834952.html|website = VOA|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = U.S.-China EcoPartnerships Program|url = https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2015/06/244111.htm|website = U.S. Department of State|accessdate = 2015-10-16}}</ref><ref name=cnn /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://revitalizationnews.com/article/us-china-partnership-funds-program-rescue-restore-sea-turtles-hainan-island|title=US-China partnership funds the rescue and restoration of sea turtles on Hainan Island|author=|date=|website=revitalizationnews.com|accessdate=21 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn July 28, 2015, [[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] interviewed Yeh as their Featured Explorer to inspire children to save sea turtles.<ref>{{cite web|title = National Geographic Features Frederick Yeh to Inspire Children to Save Sea Turtles|url = http://www.seaturtles911.org/news/national-geographic-frederick-yeh-inspires-kids-save-sea-turtles.htm|website = NatGeo|accessdate = 2015-07-28}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2018, the [[Committee of 100 (United States)|Committee of 100]] officially recognized Yeh as their Next Generation Leader to advance the betterment of U.S.-China relations.<ref>{{cite web|title = Announcing Committee of 100 Next Generation Leaders 2018|url = http://www.committee100.org/announcements/announcing-committee-of-100-next-generation-leaders-2018/|website = C100|accessdate = 2018-06-07}}</ref>  Committee delegations have been invited to give briefings to top officials at the [[White House]] and [[Zhongnanhai]].<ref name = chinadailyc100>{{cite journal | author = Qidong Zhang | date = April 25, 2014 | title = C-100 strengthens US-China relations | journal = [[China Daily]] | url = http://usa.chinadaily.com.cn/2014-04/25/content_17467034.htm | access-date = April 26, 2017 }}</ref>  Prominent members of the committee include Ambassador [[Gary Locke]], former [[United States Secretary of Commerce]] and [[List of Governors of Washington|Governor of Washington]]; [[I. M. Pei]], renowned architect; [[Yo-Yo Ma]], master cellist; [[Jerry Yang]], Founder of [[Yahoo!]]; [[David Ho (scientist)|David Ho]], [[Time (magazine)|''Time'' magazine]]'s 1996 [[Time Magazine Person of the Year|Man of the Year]] for pioneering [[HIV/AIDS research]]; [[Michelle Kwan]], Olympic medalist in figure skating; and [[Steve Chen]], Founder of [[YouTube]].<ref name = Comm100roster>{{cite web | title = Committee of 100 Members | publisher = Committee of 100 | url=https://committee100.org/member-roster/ | access-date = April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.seaturtles911.org/ Sea Turtles 911]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yeh, Frederick}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Social entrepreneurs]]\n[[Category:American conservationists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "RayScript", "label": "safe", "comment": "American social entrepreneurs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frederick_Yeh"}
{"title_page": "Legend (1994 video game)", "text_new": "{{about|the 1994 Super NES video game|the 1992 video game|Legend (1992 video game)|other uses|Legend (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title         = Legend\n|image         = SNES Legend cover art.jpg\n|caption       = North American SNES cover art\n|developer     = Arcade Zone\n|publisher     = '''Super NES'''{{vgrelease|NA|Seika Corporation|EU|[[Sony Imagesoft|Sony Electronic Publishing]]|WW|[[Piko Interactive]]<br /><small>(Re-release)</small>}} '''Windows'''{{vgrelease|WW|Piko Interactive}}\n|designer      = Carlo Perconti<br />Lyes Belaidouni\n|artist        = Lyes Belaidouni\n|composer      = Carlo Perconti\n|platforms     = [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]], [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]\n|released      = '''Super NES'''<br />''Original release''{{vgrelease|NA|April [[1994 in video gaming|1994]]|EU|21 December 1994}} ''Re-release''{{vgrelease|WW|30 January [[2017 in video gaming|2017]]}} '''Windows'''{{vgrelease|WW|11 November [[2015 in video gaming|2015]]}}\n|genre         = [[Beat 'em up]], [[hack and slash]]\n|modes         = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]], [[Cooperative gameplay|co-op]]\n}}\n\n'''''Legend''''' is a [[side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[hack and slash]] [[beat 'em up]] [[video game]] developed by Arcade Zone and originally published in North America by Seika Corporation on April [[1994 in video gaming|1994]] and later in Europe by [[Sony Imagesoft|Sony Electronic Publishing]] on December 21 of the same year for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]]. It is the first game to be solely developed by the duo of Carlo Perconti and Lyes Belaidouni at Arcade Zone, who both would later go on to found [[Toka (company)|Toka]] and [[HyperDevbox Japan]] respectively.<ref name=\"C+33\">{{cite magazine|last=Souibgui|first=Sami|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=7659&album=oui|title=Work In Progress - Arcade Zone - A Few Good Games|magazine=[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]|issue=33|publisher=[[:fr:M.E.R.7|M.E.R.7]]|date=June 1994|pages=52\u201355|lang=fr|access-date=April 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170908175651/http://abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=7659&album=oui|archive-date=September 8, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DHDIE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamatomic.com/reports/280/hyper-devbox-interview-exclusive|title=Dossier - Hyper-Devbox : Interview Exclusive|website=gamatomic.com|date=July 20, 2003|accessdate=2019-04-17|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312141718/https://www.gamatomic.com/reports/280/hyper-devbox-interview-exclusive|archive-date=March 12, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"IwtMoL\">{{cite web|author=Sanjuro|url=http://www.1up-games.com/snes/legend/interview-english.html|title=Interview with the Makers of Legend|website=1up-games.com|date=March 13, 2008|accessdate=2019-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412061159/http://www.1up-games.com/snes/legend/interview-english.html|archive-date=April 12, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nTaking place in the fictional kingdom of Sellech during the [[middle ages]], players take control of the [[knight]] [[warrior]]s Kaor and Igor in an attempt to defeat the corrupt son of the [[king]] of Sellech, Clovis, before he manages to harness power from the imprisoned [[soul]] of maleficent [[Despotism|despot]] Beldor and conquers the land as a result. Inspired by several [[high fantasy]] [[Historical fantasy#Medieval fantasy|medieval]]-themed beat 'em up [[arcade game]]s from [[Capcom]] and [[Sega]], ''Legend'' was conceived as an idea by Perconti and Belaidouni to create their own action-oriented project.<ref name=\"C+33\"/><ref name=\"DHDIE\"/><ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/>\n\n''Legend'' garnered mixed reception from critics since its initial release on the Super Nintendo. While the graphics received unanimous praise, many of the reviewers felt divided in regards to the sound department and gameplay, which was deemed by some as repetitive. Although it never received a direct sequel, Toka later created a [[Video game remake|remake]] of the game for the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] which was also called ''[[Legend (1998 video game)|Legend]]''. In [[2015 in video gaming|2015]], the original game was ported to [[Microsoft Windows]] by independent developer and publisher [[Piko Interactive]]. A [[spiritual successor]], ''Konan'', was also in development and planned for the [[Atari Jaguar]] by both Perconti and Belaidouni but was never finished and released.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:SNES Legend.png|thumb|left|Gameplay screenshot.]]\n''Legend'' is an arcade-style side-scrolling hack and slash beat 'em up game similar to ''[[Golden Axe (video game)|Golden Axe]]'' and ''[[The King of Dragons]]'' where players take control of Kaor and Igor through seven stages in total of varying thematic set in the kingdom of Sellech and battling against an assortment of enemies along the journey, with the main objective being defeating the corrupt son of the land's king, Clovis, before he manages to break free the sealed remnant of Beldor's powers and conquers Sellech.<ref name=\"EGM51\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/Electronic_Gaming_Monthly_51/page/n125|title=Fact-Files - Super NES - Legend|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=51|publisher=Sendai Publishing|date=October 1993|pages=124-125}}</ref><ref name=\"GP35\">{{cite magazine|last=Lundrigan|first=Jeff|url=https://archive.org/details/Game_Players_Issue_35_December_1993/page/n75|title=Features - Legend|magazine=[[Game Players]]|issue=35|publisher=Signal Research|date=December 1993|pages=72-74}}</ref> The characters have several fighting abilities in their disposal to counterattack such as their swords, kicks and [[Incantation|magic spell]]s.<ref name=\"GP35\"/> Players can also block incoming enemy attacks by using their shields.<ref name=\"GP35\"/> There are also special techniques that can be performed by pressing a combination of buttons such as a jump slash, among others at the cost of health. Defeating certain enemies also drops items that can be picked up such as food, magic bags and extra lives.<ref name=\"GP35\"/> After completing a level, players would be sent to a bonus round where items can be collected for points or picked up for later use in the game.<ref name=\"GP35\"/> Although there are seven stages, one of them can only be accessed if the players are captured by the enemies and imprisoned in a dungeon during a boss fight. In the options menu, players can customize the color of their clothing as well as the ability to change the default difficulty setting or share lives between each other during co-op play.\n\n== Synopsis ==\nThe story of the game is that the maleficent despot Beldor reigned over the kingdom of Sellech for 1000 years, bringing chaos and destruction to the land. Many knights went on a crusade to overthrow Beldor but none of them ever returned. United, people built energized heroes, managing to seal the soul of Beldor and peace was brought to the land afterwards. Clovis, the corrupt son of the king of Sellech, now seeks to harness the power of Beldor and conquer the kingdom by doing so.<ref name=\"GP35\"/> As such, players assume the role of knight warriors Kaor and Igor in order to defeat Clovis. After travelling across the land, meeting townsfolks who aid them in their quest, while battling against enemies and creatures, both Kaor and Igor reach the [[sanctuary]] where Clovis resides and after finally defeating him, Beldor's soul is vanished from the land and their glorious victory is widespread all over the world.\n\n== Development ==\n[[File:SNES-Mod1-Console-Set.jpg|thumb|right|''Legend'' for the SNES was created under tight conditions in a short development time.]]\nCarlo Perconti worked for several companies such as [[Loriciels]] and [[Titus Interactive]] as a [[freelance]] graphic designer, while Lyes Belaidouni worked under the same area in the latter, who were mainly developing [[racing game]]s for [[Amstrad]] [[home computer]]s and the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]].<ref name=\"C+33\"/><ref name=\"DHDIE\"/><ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> Belaidouni preferred action-oriented titles but due to the then-current direction of productions under Titus, who also were not interested in developing for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System outside of publishing with the exception of ''[[Prehistorik Man]]'', he resigned along with Perconti and marketing manager Gabriel Guary to establish their own [[game development company]] called Arcade Zone to create titles for home consoles.<ref name=\"C+33\"/><ref name=\"DHDIE\"/><ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> Their first idea was to create a game under the beat 'em up genre, which was not widely developed in North American and Europe in the 1990s, and were inspired by several arcade games from Capcom and Sega such as ''[[Knights of the Round (video game)|Knights of the Round]]'', ''Golden Axe'' and ''The King of Dragons'', with Perconti later stating that \"we made the game we wanted to play.\"<ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/>\n\nThe two co-founders were the sole authors of ''Legend'' which was developed as a passion project under turbulent conditions on a quick pace between two and three months, becoming the company's first project, with Perconti serving as its programmer.<ref name=\"C+33\"/><ref name=\"DHDIE\"/><ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> The game was created from scratch as the team had no financial backing, no access to a software library, nor an official [[Nintendo]] development kit for the Super Nintendo, while Guary was in charge of the business side of the company.<ref name=\"C+33\"/><ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> Belaidouni made all the artwork for backgrounds and characters in ''[[Deluxe Paint]]'' on [[Amiga]] before being transferred to [[Personal computer|PC]] for Perconti, who handled hardware coordination and other tasks.<ref name=\"DHDIE\"/><ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> After finishing development, the game was first showcased at [[Consumer Electronics Show]], where Capcom was also exhibiting the Super NES conversion of ''The King of Dragons''.<ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/Gamefan_Vol_1_Issue_09/page/n105|title=Summer CES '93|magazine=[[GameFan]]|volume=1|issue=9|publisher=DieHard Gamers Club|date=August 1993|pages=95-108}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/Electronic_Gaming_Monthly_50/page/n101|title=Next Wave - Seika - Legend|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=50|publisher=Sendai Publishing|date=September 1993|page=102}}</ref>\n\n== Release ==\n''Legend'' was first released in North America on April 1994 by Seika Corporation and later in Europe by Sony Electronic Publishing on December 24 of the same year. Perconti has said that the lack of a Japanese release of the game was due to the company not having contact and competition of the market in the region.<ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> He also stated that the game sold well, though it is unknown how many were sold in total during its original lifetime.<ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> In 2015, Piko Interactive ported the title to Microsoft Windows and it was published through [[Steam (software)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Estrada|first=Marcus|url=https://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/11/piko-interactive-releases-snes-game-legend-onto-steam/176672/|title=Piko Interactive Releases SNES Game \u2018Legend\u2019 onto Steam|publisher=Hardcore Gamer|date=November 11, 2015|accessdate=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418235213/https://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/11/piko-interactive-releases-snes-game-legend-onto-steam/176672/|archive-date=April 18, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Two years later, the original Super Nintendo version was re-released worldwide by Piko Interactive.<ref name=\"NLSNESl1\">{{cite web|last=McFerran|first=Damien|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/10/piko_interactive_is_launching_new_nes_snes_and_genesis_games|title=Piko Interactive Is Launching New NES, SNES And Genesis Games - Oh, and one for the Atari Jaguar as well|publisher=[[Nintendo Life]]|date=October 12, 2016|accessdate=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228121414/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2016/10/piko_interactive_is_launching_new_nes_snes_and_genesis_games|archive-date=February 28, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"NLSNESl2\">{{cite web|last=Lopes|first=Gon\u00e7alo|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/news/2017/04/super_nintendo_games_legend_and_iron_commando_seek_re-release|title=Super Nintendo Games, \"Legend\" And \"Iron Commando\", Seek Re-release - Piko Interactive seeks to republish Arcade Zone's finest|publisher=[[Nintendo Life]]|date=April 19, 2017|accessdate=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180818064952/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2017/04/super_nintendo_games_legend_and_iron_commando_seek_re-release|archive-date=August 18, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n|GR         = (SNES) 67.75%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerankings.com/snes/588434-legend/index.html|title=Legend for Super Nintendo|work=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=2019|access-date=2019-11-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104180551/https://www.gamerankings.com/snes/588434-legend/index.html|archive-date=2019-11-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev1       = ''[[AllGame]]''\n|rev1Score  = (SNES) {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"AGSNESl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16520|title=Legend (Super Nintendo Entertainment System) - Overview|website=[[AllGame]]|accessdate=2019-04-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141115102624/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=16520|archivedate=2014-11-15|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|rev2       = ''[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]''\n|rev2Score  = (SNES) 90%<ref name=\"C+SNESl\">{{cite magazine|last1=Souibgui|first1=Sami|author2=Switch|url=https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=2884&album=oui|title=Super Nintendo Review - Legend|magazine=[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]|issue=35|publisher=[[:fr:M.E.R.7|M.E.R.7]]|date=September 1994|pages=106\u2013107|lang=fr|access-date=April 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404224529/https://www.abandonware-magazines.org/affiche_mag.php?mag=51&num=2884&album=oui|archive-date=April 4, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|rev3       = ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''\n|rev3Score  = (SNES) 34 / 50<ref name=\"EGMSNESl\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/Electronic_Gaming_Monthly_56/page/n35|title=Review Crew - Major Mike's Game Roundup - Legend - Seika / Super NES|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=56|publisher=Sendai Publishing|date=March 1994|page=36}}</ref>\n|rev4       = ''[[GameFan]]''\n|rev4Score  = (SNES) 271 / 400<ref name=\"DHGFSNESl\">{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/details/Gamefan_Vol_1_Issue_12/page/n21|title=Viewpoint - Nintendo - Legend|magazine=[[GameFan]]|volume=1|issue=12|publisher=DieHard Gamers Club|date=November 1993|page=23}}</ref>\n|rev5       = ''[[GamePro]]''\n|rev5Score  = (SNES) 16 / 20<ref name=\"GProSNESl\">{{cite magazine|last=Squideo|first=Captain|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:GamePro_US_051.pdf&page=100|title=Super NES ProReview: Legend|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=51|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=October 1993|page=96}}</ref>\n|rev6       = ''[[:fr:Joypad (magazine)|Joypad]]''\n|rev6Score  = (SNES) 79%<ref name=\"JpadSNESl\">{{cite magazine|last1=Hellot|first1=Gr\u00e9goire|last2=Nini|first2=Nourdine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AJoypad_FR_034.pdf&page=102|title=Super Nintendo - Quelle L\u00e9gende? - Legend|magazine=[[:fr:Joypad 