[[:de:Play Time|Play Time]]|issue=39|publisher=[[:de:Computec Media Group|CT Computec Verlag GmbH & Co. KG]]|date=September 1994|page=134|lang=de}}</ref>\n|rev11      = ''[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]''\n|rev11Score = (SNES) 80%<ref name=\"POSNESl\">{{cite magazine|last=Pottier|first=Christophe|url=|title=Tests - Super NES - Legend|magazine=[[:fr:Player One (magazine)|Player One]]|issue=45|publisher=[[:fr:M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition|M\u00e9dia Syst\u00e8me \u00c9dition]]|date=September 1994|pages=70\u201371|lang=fr}}</ref>\n|rev12      = ''[[Super Play]]''\n|rev12Score = (SNES) 55%<ref name=\"SPSNESl\">{{cite magazine|last=Mott|first=Tony|url=https://archive.org/details/Superplay_Issue_22_1994-08_Future_Publishing_GB/page/n43|title=Import Review - Legend|magazine=[[Super Play]]|issue=22|publisher=[[Future plc|Future Publishing]]|date=August 1994|pages=44-45}}</ref>\n|rev13      = ''[[:de:Total (Zeitschrift)|Total!]]''\n|rev13Score = (SNES) 4-<ref name=\"T!SNESl\">{{cite magazine|last=Koczy|first=Michael|url=http://total.bee-ware.ch/tests/snes/snes_Legend.jpg|title=Test - SNES - Legend|magazine=[[:de:Total (Zeitschrift)|Total!]]|issue=19|publisher=X-Plain-Verlag|date=December 1994|page=36|lang=de|access-date=April 17, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429105501/http://total.bee-ware.ch/tests/snes/snes_Legend.jpg|archive-date=April 29, 2016|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|rev14      = ''[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]''\n|rev14Score = (SNES) 79%<ref name=\"VGSNESl\">{{cite magazine|last=Karels|first=Ralph|url=https://www.kultboy.com/index.php?site=t&id=8879|title=Rom Check - Super Nintendo - Legend|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=23|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=October 1993|page=43|lang=de}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' gave the game a 6.8 out of 10. They praised the boss design and long levels, but remarked that the game, while good overall, is lacking in variety, which they felt to be a crucial factor in beat 'em ups.<ref name=\"EGMSNESl\"/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nAfter the initial release of ''Legend'' in North America, Arcade Zone would go on to develop two more titles for the Super Nintendo: ''[[Iron Commando]]'' and ''[[Nightmare Busters]]'',<ref name=\"C+33\"/><ref name=\"DHDIE\"/> with the former being originally only published in Japan by Poppo on February [[1995 in video gaming|1995]] before being picked up for a worldwide re-release as well as being ported to Windows by Piko Interactive,<ref name=\"NLSNESl1\"/><ref name=\"NLSNESl2\"/> and the later being cancelled due to financial issues before its development was resumed by the original authors and eventually published worldwide by [[Super Fighter Team]] on December [[2013 in video gaming|2013]].<ref>{{cite magazine|author=|title=Homebrew - Preview: Nightmare Busters|magazine=ReVival|issue=46|publisher=ABCD Dire|date=Spring 2011|page=21|lang=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Crawley|first=Dan|url=https://venturebeat.com/2013/05/03/consoles-that-wont-die-snes/|title=Consoles that won\u2019t die: The SNES in 2013|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=May 3, 2013|accessdate=2019-04-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119164445/https://venturebeat.com/2013/05/03/consoles-that-wont-die-snes/|archivedate=January 19, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameblog.fr/blogs/PGR/p_100644_un-nouveau-jeu-super-nintendo-nightmare-busters-aux-editions|title=Un nouveau jeu Super Nintendo: Nightmare Busters aux \u00e9ditions Super Fighter Team|website=gameblog.fr|date=December 28, 2013|accessdate=2019-04-18|language=fr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825190453/http://www.gameblog.fr/blogs/PGR/p_100644_un-nouveau-jeu-super-nintendo-nightmare-busters-aux-editions|archive-date=August 25, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kohler|first=Chris|url=https://www.wired.com/2014/01/nightmare-busters/|title=Nightmare Busters Is an Awesome New Game for ... Super Nintendo?|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|date=January 16, 2014|accessdate=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170930131953/https://www.wired.com/2014/01/nightmare-busters/|archive-date=September 30, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A spiritual successor, Konan, was also in development and planned for the Atari Jaguar by both Perconti and Belaidouni but was never finished and released.<ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> Due to no longer being able to find interested publishers as a result of Sony discontinuing distribution of Nintendo-related products and incapable of publishing their own titles, Arcade Zone was shut down and stopped any current project under development,<ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> however both Perconti and Belaidouni founded Toka shortly afterwards and would later develop a remake of the game for the PlayStation bearing the same title.<ref name=\"DHDIE\"/>\n\n=== Konan ===\n[[File:JAG Konan (Single-player).jpg|thumb|right|Gameplay screenshot from the unreleased ''Konan'' for the Atari Jaguar.]]\nDuring an exhibition at the CES, both Carlo Perconti and Lyes Belaidouni met key people representing [[Atari Corporation]] and intrigued by the architecture of the Atari Jaguar, the duo became involved with developing for the platform.<ref name=\"CJC\">{{cite web|author=monokoma|url=https://www.unseen64.net/2010/03/12/conan-jaguar-cancelled/|title=Conan [Jaguar \u2013 Cancelled]|website=unseen64.net|date=March 12, 2010|accessdate=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414152018/https://www.unseen64.net/2010/03/12/conan-jaguar-cancelled/|archive-date=April 14, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"UAJGFF\">{{cite web|last=Williams|first=Carl|url=http://retrogamingmagazine.com/2017/09/17/unreleased-atari-jaguar-game-footage-found/|title=Unreleased Atari Jaguar Game Footage Found|website=retrogamingmagazine.com|date=September 17, 2017|accessdate=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306103156/http://retrogamingmagazine.com/2017/09/17/unreleased-atari-jaguar-game-footage-found/|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The two began creating a new engine on PC before receiving a Jaguar development kit and afterwards, they started porting a level of what the team wanted to showcase their engine based upon the [[fictional character]] [[Conan the Barbarian]], although a license had yet to be signed and were inspired by several arcade games.<ref name=\"CJC\"/><ref name=\"UAJGFF\"/> Regarded by Belaidouni as \"the most beautiful beat 'em up with huge sprites and monumental backgrounds\",<ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/> the project was first announced and previewed in December 1994 by French magazine ''CD Consoles'' under the tentative title ''Conan'', featuring an early graphical art style while its overall style and gameplay were very similar to that of ''Legend''.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/CD%20Consoles/cdconsoles_numero02/Page%20018.jpg|title=Actualit\u00e9s France - Conan \u2022 Arcade Zone|magazine=CD Consoles|issue=2|publisher=Pressimage|date=December 1994|page=18|lang=fr}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/CD%20Consoles/cdconsoles_numero05/Page%20077.jpg|title=Dossier - Ils Arrivent Sur Jaguar - Conan / Jaguar|magazine=CD Consoles|issue=5|publisher=Pressimage|date=March 1995|page=77|lang=fr|access-date=2019-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926090315/http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/CD%20Consoles/cdconsoles_numero05/Page%20077.jpg|archive-date=2018-09-26|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe game was only displayed for co-op play once at Atari Corp.'s booth during the [[Consumer Electronics Show|Winter Consumer Electronics Show]] in 1995, featuring two playable characters that were named after both developers and used the same sound effects from the aforementioned Super Nintendo title,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=http://download.abandonware.org/magazines/Consoles%20Plus/consoleplus_numero040/Consoles%20%2B%20040%20-%20Page%20051%20%28f%e9vrier%201995%29.jpg|title=La Gazette De las Vegas - Fait Divers|magazine=[[:fr:Consoles +|Consoles +]]|issue=40|publisher=[[:fr: M.E.R.7|M.E.R.7]]|date=February 1995|page=51|lang=fr|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/Gamefan_Vol_3_Issue_03#page/n108/mode/1up|title=WCES Special - Winter CES '95 - Atari|magazine=[[GameFan]]|volume=3|issue=3|publisher=DieHard Gamers Club|date=March 1995|page=109|access-date=April 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113200349/https://archive.org/stream/Gamefan_Vol_3_Issue_03#page/n108/mode/1up|archive-date=January 13, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AMegaFun_DE_1995-03.pdf&page=8|title=Special CES-Show - Winter CES Las Vegas - Atari|magazine=[[:de:Mega Fun|Mega Fun]]|issue=30|publisher=[[:de:Computec Media Group|CT Computec Verlag GmbH & Co. KG]]|date=March 1995|page=8|lang=de|access-date=2019-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728191315/https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AMegaFun_DE_1995-03.pdf&page=8|archive-date=2018-07-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:VideoGames_DE_1995-03.pdf&page=12|title=Winter-CES - Atari|magazine=[[:de:Video Games|Video Games]]|issue=40|publisher=Future-Verlag|date=March 1995|page=12|access-date=2019-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301074438/https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:VideoGames_DE_1995-03.pdf&page=12|archive-date=March 1, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"SFfWCESJ95P1o2\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=03guo596Xfo&t|work=[[YouTube]]|date=February 27, 2016|author=PS Nation|title=Shakycam Footage from Winter CES January 1995 - Part 1 of 2 (11min 19sec)|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\"AJCDCES95\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EbPVeQ4acuc|work=[[YouTube]]|date=January 31, 2018|author=[[National Videogame Museum]]|title=Atari Jaguar Conan Demo CES 1995|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref> with ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' referring to the title as ''Conan the Barbarian''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://imgur.com/gallery/oL5fV|title=Jaguar - Atari \u2022 Conan the Barbarian|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|publisher=Sendai Publishing|date=1995|access-date=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190418091930/https://imgur.com/gallery/oL5fV|archive-date=2019-04-18|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also showcased in a [[promotional recording]] sent by Atari to [[Video game industry#Retail|video game retail stores]] on the same year, now under the title ''Konan'' and scheduled for an August/Q4 1995 release date.<ref name=\"PvoAJg\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JEGbuOAoZVk|work=[[YouTube]]|date=April 11, 2019|author=Rill|title=Promotional video of Atari Jaguar games (9min 29sec)|access-date=2019-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413070412/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JEGbuOAoZVk|archive-date=April 13, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"IEM\">{{cite video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7SFi1ei3NY0|work=[[YouTube]]|date=November 7, 2016|author=TGApuleius|title=Interactive Entertainment (IE) Magazine - Issue 10, Feb. 1995: Atari Winter CES (News) (2min 10sec)|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Reutter|first=Hans|url=http://www.cyberroach.com/jaguarcd/html/conan.htm|title=Unreleased Or Unfinished Jaguar Games - Conan|website=cyberroach.com|date=July 23, 2000|accessdate=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171001050242/http://www.cyberroach.com/jaguarcd/html/conan.htm|archive-date=October 1, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/HiTechMagazine/HiTech%2003#page/n26/mode/1up|title=Reportaje - Jaguar ya ruge en Espa\u00f1a -- As\u00f3mate al futuro|magazine=[[Hobby Consolas|Hobby Hi-Tech]]|issue=3|publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]]|date=May 1995|page=27|lang=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://archive.org/stream/MANIAC.N020.1995.06/MANIAC.N020.1995.06-DURiAN_Searchable#page/n39/mode/1up|title=Feature - XT Generation Report - Atari Jaguar|magazine=[[:de:M! Games|MAN!AC]]|issue=20|publisher=Cybermedia|date=June 1995|page=40|lang=de|access-date=April 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181129120834/https://archive.org/stream/MANIAC.N020.1995.06/MANIAC.N020.1995.06-DURiAN_Searchable#page/n39/mode/1up|archive-date=November 29, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=CRV|url=http://gdri.smspower.org/wiki/index.php/Blog:Legal_Brief:_Atari_vs._Sega|title=Blog:Legal Brief: Atari vs. Sega|website=gdri.smspower.org|date=August 6, 2017|accessdate=2019-04-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116043230/http://gdri.smspower.org/wiki/index.php/Blog:Legal_Brief:_Atari_vs._Sega|archive-date=2018-11-16|url-status=live}}</ref> However, due to financial constrains as a result of Sony's decision to not keep supporting Nintendo products in Europe and lack of funds, the project never moved forward from being a [[tech demo]] to a full-fledged title.<ref name=\"IwtMoL\"/><ref name=\"UAJGFF\"/>\n\nPerconti has since stated in recent years that the [[source code]] of ''Konan'' has become lost and the only remaining proofs of its existence are various screenshots taken by several [[video game magazine]]s and gameplay footage,<ref name=\"UAJGFF\"/><ref name=\"SFfWCESJ95P1o2\"/><ref name=\"AJCDCES95\"/><ref name=\"PvoAJg\"/><ref name=\"IEM\"/> while no prototypes containing a [[ROM image]] of the demo have been found to date.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wallet|first=Adrian|url=http://www.arcadeattack.co.uk/dan-mcnamee/|title=Dan McNamee (Atari) - Interview|website=arcadeattack.co.uk|date=February 2, 2018|accessdate=2019-04-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316152638/http://www.arcadeattack.co.uk/dan-mcnamee/|archive-date=2018-03-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://gamefaqs.gamespot.com/snes/588434-legend ''Legend''] at [[GameFAQs]]\n* [https://www.giantbomb.com/legend/3030-14402/ ''Legend''] at [[Giant Bomb]]\n* [https://www.mobygames.com/game/legend- ''Legend''] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{Portal bar|1990s|France|Video games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legend (1994 video game)}}\n[[Category:1994 video games]]\n[[Category:Arcade Zone games]]\n[[Category:Beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:Hack and slash games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:Piko Interactive games]]\n[[Category:Seika Corporation games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Super Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1994]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in France]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Witchcraft in video games]]\n", "name_user": "KGRAMR", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legend_(1994_video_game)"}
{"title_page": "Sasha Velour", "text_new": "{{short description|American drag queen}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sasha Velour\n| image              = Sasha Velour (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Velour at [[RuPaul's DragCon NYC]] 2017.\n| birth_name         = Alexander Hedges Steinberg<ref name=\"middlename\">{{cite web |title=Mother: Sasha Velour |url=https://nightout.com/events/mother-sasha-velour/tickets |website=Night Out |accessdate=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1987|6|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Berkeley, California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[Vassar College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Center for Cartoon Studies]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation         = [[Drag queen]], artist\n| years_active       = 2009\u2013present\n| known_for          = ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'' ([[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)|season 9]]) winner\n| predecessor        = [[Bob the Drag Queen]]\n| successor          = [[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]]\n| partner             = [[Johnny Velour]]\n| website            = {{URL|sashavelour.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexander \"Sasha\" Hedges Steinberg''' (born June 25, 1987), known by the [[stage name]] '''Sasha Velour''', is an American [[drag queen]] and artist, based in [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://sashavelour.com/about-1/|title=about|website=Sasha Velour|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Velour is known for winning the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)|ninth season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'' in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/g22553306/sasha-velour-drag-race-queen-facts/|title=11 Things You Didn't Know About \"RuPaul's Drag Race\" Winner Sasha Velour|last=Lasher|first=Megan|date=2018-07-27|website=Seventeen|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-15}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSteinberg was born in [[Berkeley, California]], the only child of [[Mark D. Steinberg|Mark Steinberg]] and Jane Hedges. She is of Russian Jewish descent on her father's side. She was raised in Connecticut until the age of 9 when the family moved to Urbana, Illinois, where her father is a Russian historian at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.illinois.edu/directory/profile/steinb|title=Mark D Steinberg {{!}} Illinois Department of History|website=history.illinois.edu|language=en|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref> Her mother served as the Managing Editor of the&nbsp;''[[Slavic Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.renner-wikoffchapel.com/fh/obituaries/obituary.cfm?o_id=3200453&fh_id=10562|title=Obituary for Jane Hedges at Renner-Wikoff Chapel and Crematory|publisher=renner-wikoffchapel.com|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg graduated from&nbsp;[[University Laboratory High School (Urbana, Illinois)|University Laboratory High School]]&nbsp;in&nbsp;[[Champaign\u2013Urbana metropolitan area|Champaign-Urbana]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Merli|first=Melissa|date=June 8, 2015|title=Studio Visit: Sasha Steinberg and John Jacob Lee|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/arts-entertainment/local/2015-06-08/studio-visit-sasha-steinberg-and-john-jacob-lee.html|work=News-Gazette|location=Champaign, IL|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en}}</ref> After high school, she spent time as a part-time security guard at the&nbsp;[[Hermitage Museum|Russian State Hermitage Museum]]&nbsp;in&nbsp;[[Saint Petersburg|St. Petersburg]], Russia,&nbsp;and interned at the&nbsp;[[Staatsoper Berlin|Staatsoper]]&nbsp;(State Opera) in&nbsp;[[Berlin]], Germany.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.grizzlykiki.com/podcast/podcast/sasha-velour|title=Sasha Velour|work=Grizzly Kiki|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://forward.com/culture/art/318495/sasha-velours-talmud-of-drag/|title=Inside Sasha Velour's Talmud of Drag|work=The Forward|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg obtained a BA in Modern Literature from&nbsp;[[Vassar College]]&nbsp;in 2009. In 2010, she was a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholar]] in Moscow and completed a project that aimed to understand the role of different art forms in contemporary Russian society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fulbright.ru/en/steinbergAMC|title=The Fulbright Program in Russia {{!}} \"Lost in Translation: The Theory and Practice of Experimental Translation\"|website=fulbright.ru|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> She received an MFA in cartooning in 2013 from the&nbsp;[[Center for Cartoon Studies]]&nbsp;in&nbsp;[[White River Junction, Vermont|White River Junction]], Vermont.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cartoonstudies.org/tag/sasha-velour/|title=Congratulations to RuPaul's Drag Race Winner Sasha Velour '13!|work=The Center for Cartoon Studies|access-date=July 17, 2017}}</ref> Prior to pursuing drag as a full-time career, Steinberg worked as a freelance graphic designer and illustrator.<ref>{{Citation|last=Logo|title='The Reigning Queen' Out Of The Closet w/ Sasha Velour Ep. 1 {{!}} Logo|date=April 24, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HWSCJ38r2H4|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nSteinberg's drag career as Sasha Velour started in Vermont while at school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thotyssey.tumblr.com/post/151478750581/on-point-with-sasha-velour|title=On Point With: Sasha Velour|website=Thotyssey!|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Known for being an out of the box artist, Steinberg incorporates that eccentricity into Velour's drag persona. Steinberg starred in the music video C.L.A.T. along with fellow New York City drag queens [[Peppermint (drag queen)|Peppermint]], [[Aja (entertainer)|Aja]] and Alexis Michelle, who also appeared on the ninth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7767972/rupauls-drag-race-new-york-city-queens-clat|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Season 9 Queens From NYC Team Up for 'C.L.A.T.' Video: Exclusive|work=Billboard|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Velour's makeup and look transformations have been featured in publications such as ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/sasha-velour-rupaul-drag-race-karl-lagerfeld-celebrity-style/amp|title=Sasha Velour From RuPaul's Drag Race Season 9 on Her Style Icons and Winning the Title|website=Vogue|access-date=June 29, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/style-beauty/beauty/a10017266/sasha-velour-makeup-transformation/|title=You Have to See Sasha Velour's Stunning Makeup Transformation|date=June 13, 2017|work=Cosmopolitan|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en}}</ref> ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/06/sasha-velour-rupauls-drag-race-winner|title=RuPaul's Drag Race Winner Sasha Velour on That Shocking Finale and the Britney Spears Stunt You Didn't See|last=Desta|first=Yohana|work=HWD|access-date=July 3, 2017|language=en}}</ref> and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lifestyle/7834060/rock-the-look-rupauls-drag-race-sasha-velour|title=Rock the Look: 'RuPaul's Drag Race' Finalist Sasha Velour is a Master at Recreating This Iconic Look|work=Billboard|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Steinberg has further created, produced, and organized different photoshoots, collages, and drawings that discuss art and drag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sashavelour.com/work|title=Home|website=Sasha Velour|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Comics and design ===\nSteinberg's comics and illustrations have appeared in The Nib, InkBRICK,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://inkbrick.com/post/141516785392/from-what-now-by-sasha-steinberg-in-ink-brick|title=INK BRICK \u2013 From \"What Now\" by Sasha Steinberg&nbsp;in INK BRICK...|last=BRICK|first=INK|work=INK BRICK|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Comics Workbook Magazine,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.copaceticcomics.com/comics/comics-workbook-magazine-2|title=Comics Workbook Magazine #2 by Frank Santoro, Andrew White, Zach Mason, Warren Craghead III, Lala Albert, Whit Taylor, Jen Rickert, Derek Badman, Evie Cahir|publisher=copaceticcomics.com|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> QU33R,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://begallerynyc.tumblr.com/pastexhibitions|title=Past Exhibitions|website=begallerynyc.tumblr.com|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Cicada Magazine<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cicadamag.com/thisissue/artist-allies-sasha-velour|title=Artist Allies: Sasha Velour|publisher=cicadamag.com|access-date=June 24, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601142947/http://www.cicadamag.com/thisissue/artist-allies-sasha-velour|archivedate=June 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and others, under the names Sasha Velour and Sasha Steinberg.&nbsp;Steinberg also created a series of comics entitled \"Stonewall\", which told the story of the [[Stonewall riots]] from multiple viewpoints. The series was called \"a smart, beautiful and artful take on a significant and difficult historical event\" by Highlow Comics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://highlowcomics.blogspot.nl/2013/11/thirty-days-of-ccs-3-sasha-steinberg.html|title=Thirty Days of CCS #3: Sasha Steinberg|website=highlowcomics.blogspot.nl|date=November 3, 2013|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA solo gallery show of Steinberg's illustration work, \"Nightrooms\", was held at the Black Box Gallery in&nbsp;[[Brooklyn]]&nbsp;in March 2016&nbsp;and Steinberg's cut paper work was part of the group show \"Coney Island Babies, Visual Artists from the Brooklyn Drag Scene\" at the Bureau of General Services Queer Division that opened in&nbsp;[[Manhattan]] in November 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bgsqd.com/strange-loop-gallery-hosts-the-bureau-of-general-services-queer-division-pop-up-shop/|title=Strange Loop Gallery Hosts The Bureau of General Services\u2014Queer Division Pop-Up Shop : BGSQD {{!}} The Bureau of General Services \u2013 Queer Division|website=bgsqd.com|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> In March 2017, Steinberg designed a long sleeve T-shirt for \"Contemporary Drag\", a limited-edition fashion line for the&nbsp;[[New Art Dealers Alliance]]'s (NADA) in collaboration with Print All Over Me.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ma.de/nada-x-poam-contemporary-drag-collection/|title=NADA x PAOM: Contemporary Drag collection {{!}} MADE|date=February 23, 2017|work=MADE|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Velour, The Drag Magazine'' ===\nSteinberg founded ''Velour, The Drag Magazine'' (originally named ''Vym''), a bi-yearly publication about drag, alongside partner Johnny in the summer of 2014.<ref name=\"Merli\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/arts-entertainment/local/2017-06-27/urbana-native-uni-alum-wins-season-9-rupauls-drag-race.html|title=Urbana native, Uni alum wins Season 9 of 'RuPaul's Drag Race'|last=Merli|first=Melissa|date=June 27, 2017|work=News-Gazette|access-date=October 7, 2017|location=Champaign, IL}}</ref> Steinberg serves as the magazine's artistic director. The first issue (\"What is Drag?\") was released June 2015&nbsp;and the second issue (\"Realness\") was released in October 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/velour-issue-two-realness_us_580a70cce4b02444efa366a8|title=This Beautiful Drag Magazine Is Providing A Comprehensive Guide To 'Realness'|last=Nichols|first=James Michael|date=October 22, 2016|work=HuffPost|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The magazine includes interviews as well as varied art forms such as photography, poetry, and illustration that address the power, beauty, and purpose of drag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thedragmagazine.com/about-2/|title=About|website=VELOUR {{!}} The Drag Magazine|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===''Nightgowns''===\nSince August 2015, Velour has produced ''Nightgowns'', a monthly drag show in Brooklyn.&nbsp;The events have been regularly hosted at Bizarre Bushwick and National Sawdust. The shows have been celebrated as \"beautiful and funny and politically charged\" by ''The New York Times''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/24/arts/gay-pride-new-york-all-drag-weekend.html|title=It's Gay Pride Weekend: Dress the Part|last=Piepenburg|first=Erik|date=June 23, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 24, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>[[File:Sasha Velour at Dragcon by dvsross.jpg|thumb|Velour at [[RuPaul's DragCon NYC]], in 2018.|alt=|291x291px]]\n\nIn 2020, Velour will star in her own [[Quibi]] show, ''NightGowns'', which will follow Velour across eight episodes as she transforms Nightgowns into a full-blown stage act.<ref name=\"quibi\">{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/02/06/sasha-velour-nightgowns-teaser-trailer-quibi/|title=Watch Sasha Velour lead drag revolution in NightGowns Quibi series teaser|last=Nolfi|first=Joey|work=Ew.com|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===''RuPaul's Drag Race''===\nVelour tried out for [[RuPaul's Drag Race|''RuPaul's Drag Race'']]'s eighth season, but was not selected for the lineup.<ref name=\"Rudolph2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newnownext.com/sasha-velour-drag-race-season-9-audition/06/2017/?xrs=synd_facebook_logo|title=Sasha Velour on Being Picked For 'Drag Race': \"I Was Shocked I Got On\"|last1=Rudolph|first1=Christopher|date=June 29, 2017|accessdate=June 30, 2017|publisher=NewNowNext}}</ref> In March 2017, she was announced as one of 14 contestants on the ninth season of&nbsp;the show.&nbsp;In June 2017, Sasha Velour was crowned the winner of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/06/25/534313492/rupauls-drag-race-winner-sasha-velour-cut-from-a-different-fabric|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Winner Sasha Velour Cut From A Different Fabric|publisher=NPR|access-date=June 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/sasha-velour-rupaul-drag-race-karl-lagerfeld-celebrity-style|title=Sasha Velour From RuPaul's Drag Race on Her Style Icons and How to Be a Queen|work=Vogue|access-date=June 29, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Allison Shoemaker of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' named Velour's lipsync to [[Whitney Houston]]'s \"[[So Emotional]]\" in the season finale as the best TV performance of 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/looking-for-the-performance-of-the-year-watch-2-minute-1821318303/amp|title=Looking for the performance of the year? Watch 2 minutes of RuPaul's Drag Race|author=Shoemaker, Allison|date=December 26, 2017|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=December 26, 2017|publisher=Onion, Inc.}}</ref> Her lip sync was later referenced on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', during [[Kate McKinnon]]'s impression of [[Elizabeth Warren]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/10/saturday-night-live-elizabeth-warren-town-hall|title=Saturday Night Live: Bow Down to Kate McKinnon's Elizabeth Warren|last=Valby|first=Karen|date=October 13, 2019|website=Vanity Fair|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/10/14/saturday-night-live-snl-elizabeth-warren-kate-mckinnon/|title=Kate McKinnon served Sasha Velour and Elizabeth Warren realness on SNL and it's everything|last=Smith|first=Reiss|date=October 14, 2019|website=PinkNews|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==== After ''Drag Race'' ====\nFollowing ''Drag Race'', Steinberg continued to work as a drag queen and expanded into the fashion industry. They selected 40 LGBT+ models to walk for [[Opening Ceremony (brand)|Opening Ceremony]] in the 2018 [[New York Fashion Week]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cms.intomore.com/was-this-new-york-fashion-week-the-queerest-season-ever/|title=INTO: A Digital Magazine For The Modern Queer World|website=cms.intomore.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/comprehensive-guide-most-show-stopping-220144705.html|title=A Comprehensive Guide to the Most Show-Stopping Moments of New York Fashion Week|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ulmhawkeyeonline.com/23701/freestyle/top-3-nyfw-collections/|title=Top 3 NYFW collections|last=Dennis|first=Ethan|work=The Hawkeye|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Velour attended [[Rihanna]]'s fourth annual Diamond Ball in September 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/gallery/rihanna-fourth-annual-diamond-ball|title=Rihanna Hosted a Wild Black-Tie Ball for a Good Cause|last=McCarthy|first=Lauren|work=W Magazine|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/diamond-ball-2018-issa-rae-normani-more-rihannas-influence-1143443|title=Issa Rae, Normani and More Stars Talk Rihanna's Influence at Diamond Ball|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2017, Steinberg's artwork of German singer-actress [[Marlene Dietrich]] was used as a [[Google Doodle]] on the performer's 116th birthday on December 27, 2017. Steinberg had previously impersonated Dietrich on ''Drag Race'' in the \"[[Snatch Game]]\" challenge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/sasha-velour-drew-marlene-dietrichs-google-doodle-because-this-rupauls-drag-race-winner-is-incredibly-talented-7702991|title=You've Been Seeing 'Drag Race' Winner Sasha Velour's Artwork All Day & Didn't Even Realize|last=Roberts|first=Amy|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\nOn December 7, 2018 Steinberg participated in The Long Conversation at the Smithsonian in Washington D.C.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2018/12/09/smithsonian-brings-big-thinkers-alfre-woodard-sasha-velour-together-long-conversation/?noredirect=on|title=Smithsonian brings together big thinkers \u2014 from Alfre Woodard to Sasha Velour \u2014 for a 'long conversation'|work=Washington Post|access-date=2019-03-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n{{As of|2013}}, Steinberg resides in Brooklyn, New York, with partner John Jacob Lee (also known as Johnny Velour) and their pet [[Italian Greyhound|Italian greyhound]], Vanya.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bedfordandbowery.com/2015/12/sasha-velour-talks-vym-a-magazine-spotlighting-the-revolutionary-art-of-drag/|title=Sasha Velour Talks Vym, a Magazine Spotlighting the 'Revolutionary' Art of Drag|work=Bedford + Bowery|access-date=July 3, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Steinberg is [[genderqueer]] and does not have any preferred pronouns when not in drag. Their drag persona, Sasha Velour, is referred to as 'she'.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sasha_velour/status/830305619886366720|title=Thank so much for asking @glassarmy! For my Velour self\u2014always she/her (out of drag its even less binary lol...any will do) #genderqueer|last=Velour|first=Sasha|date=February 10, 2017|website=@sasha_velour|access-date=March 19, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg has a shaved head. As Sasha, she often performs in drag bald as a tribute to her mother, Jane Hedges, who died of cancer in 2015 and had lost her hair during treatment for the disease.<ref name=\"Merli\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''\n| Herself (Contestant)\n| [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)|Season 9]] (Winner)\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Broad City]]''\n| Herself\n|Guest Appearance\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[The Bold Type]]''\n| Herself \n| Guest Appearance\n|}\n\n===Web Series===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race#Untucked|Untucked]]''\n| Herself\n| Season 9\n|-\n|2020\n|''The Pit Stop''<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rGqCzcSZzs4|title=Bob The Drag Queen & Sasha Velour Recap the Premiere {{!}} The Pit Stop S12 E1 {{!}} RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race|publisher=[[VH1]]|date=February 29, 2020|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n| Herself\n| Season 12, Episode 1\n|-\n|2020\n|''NightGowns''<ref name=\"quibi\"></ref>\n|Herself\n|[[Quibi]] original\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" <!-- Do not center -->\n|- <!-- Never add unnecessary background colors -->\n! Year\n! Award Giving Body\n! Category\n! Work\n! Results\n! Ref.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|2020\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Queerty|The Queerties]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|Drag Royalty\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|Herself\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/Queerties2020/|title='The 2020 Queerties|work=Cheat Sheet|date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[LGBT culture in New York City]]\n* [[List of self-identified LGBTQ New Yorkers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Sasha Velour}}\n* {{Official website|http://sashavelour.com/}}\n\n{{RuPaul's Drag Race}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Velour, Sasha}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:American drag queens]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:New York City nightlife]]\n[[Category:RuPaul's Drag Race winners|Sasha Velour]]\n[[Category:Vassar College alumni]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Genderqueer people]]\n[[Category:People with non-binary gender identities]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:LGBT comics creators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American drag queen}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sasha Velour\n| image              = Sasha Velour (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Velour at [[RuPaul's DragCon NYC]] 2017.\n| birth_name         = Alexander Hedges Steinberg<ref name=\"middlename\">{{cite web |title=Mother: Sasha Velour |url=https://nightout.com/events/mother-sasha-velour/tickets |website=Night Out |accessdate=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1987|6|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Berkeley, California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[Vassar College]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}<br>[[Center for Cartoon Studies]] {{small|([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])}}\n| occupation         = [[Drag queen]], artist\n| years_active       = 2009\u2013present\n| known_for          = ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'' ([[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)|season 9]]) winner\n| predecessor        = [[Bob the Drag Queen]]\n| successor          = [[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]]\n| partner             = [[Johnny Velour]]\n| website            = {{URL|sashavelour.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexander \"Sasha\" Hedges Steinberg''' (born June 25, 1987), known by the [[stage name]] '''Sasha Velour''', is an American [[drag queen]] and artist, based in [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://sashavelour.com/about-1/|title=about|website=Sasha Velour|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Velour is known for winning the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)|ninth season]] of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'' in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seventeen.com/celebrity/g22553306/sasha-velour-drag-race-queen-facts/|title=11 Things You Didn't Know About \"RuPaul's Drag Race\" Winner Sasha Velour|last=Lasher|first=Megan|date=2018-07-27|website=Seventeen|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-15}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSteinberg was born in [[Berkeley, California]], the only child of [[Mark D. Steinberg|Mark Steinberg]] and Jane Hedges. He is of Russian Jewish descent on his father's side. He was raised in Connecticut until the age of 9 when the family moved to Urbana, Illinois, where his father is a Russian historian at the [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign|University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://history.illinois.edu/directory/profile/steinb|title=Mark D Steinberg {{!}} Illinois Department of History|website=history.illinois.edu|language=en|access-date=December 9, 2018}}</ref> His mother served as the Managing Editor of the&nbsp;''[[Slavic Review]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.renner-wikoffchapel.com/fh/obituaries/obituary.cfm?o_id=3200453&fh_id=10562|title=Obituary for Jane Hedges at Renner-Wikoff Chapel and Crematory|publisher=renner-wikoffchapel.com|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg graduated from&nbsp;[[University Laboratory High School (Urbana, Illinois)|University Laboratory High School]]&nbsp;in&nbsp;[[Champaign\u2013Urbana metropolitan area|Champaign-Urbana]] in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Merli|first=Melissa|date=June 8, 2015|title=Studio Visit: Sasha Steinberg and John Jacob Lee|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/arts-entertainment/local/2015-06-08/studio-visit-sasha-steinberg-and-john-jacob-lee.html|work=News-Gazette|location=Champaign, IL|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en}}</ref> After high school, he spent time as a part-time security guard at the&nbsp;[[Hermitage Museum|Russian State Hermitage Museum]]&nbsp;in&nbsp;[[Saint Petersburg|St. Petersburg]], Russia,&nbsp;and interned at the&nbsp;[[Staatsoper Berlin|Staatsoper]]&nbsp;(State Opera) in&nbsp;[[Berlin]], Germany.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.grizzlykiki.com/podcast/podcast/sasha-velour|title=Sasha Velour|work=Grizzly Kiki|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://forward.com/culture/art/318495/sasha-velours-talmud-of-drag/|title=Inside Sasha Velour's Talmud of Drag|work=The Forward|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg obtained a BA in Modern Literature from&nbsp;[[Vassar College]]&nbsp;in 2009. In 2010, he was a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Scholar]] in Moscow and completed a project that aimed to understand the role of different art forms in contemporary Russian society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fulbright.ru/en/steinbergAMC|title=The Fulbright Program in Russia {{!}} \"Lost in Translation: The Theory and Practice of Experimental Translation\"|website=fulbright.ru|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> He received an MFA in cartooning in 2013 from the&nbsp;[[Center for Cartoon Studies]]&nbsp;in&nbsp;[[White River Junction, Vermont|White River Junction]], Vermont.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cartoonstudies.org/tag/sasha-velour/|title=Congratulations to RuPaul's Drag Race Winner Sasha Velour '13!|work=The Center for Cartoon Studies|access-date=July 17, 2017}}</ref> Prior to pursuing drag as a full-time career, Steinberg worked as a freelance graphic designer and illustrator.<ref>{{Citation|last=Logo|title='The Reigning Queen' Out Of The Closet w/ Sasha Velour Ep. 1 {{!}} Logo|date=April 24, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HWSCJ38r2H4|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nSteinberg's drag career as Sasha Velour started in Vermont while at school.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thotyssey.tumblr.com/post/151478750581/on-point-with-sasha-velour|title=On Point With: Sasha Velour|website=Thotyssey!|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Known for being an out of the box artist, Steinberg incorporates that eccentricity into Velour's drag persona. Steinberg starred in the music video C.L.A.T. along with fellow New York City drag queens [[Peppermint (drag queen)|Peppermint]], [[Aja (entertainer)|Aja]] and Alexis Michelle, who also appeared on the ninth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7767972/rupauls-drag-race-new-york-city-queens-clat|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Season 9 Queens From NYC Team Up for 'C.L.A.T.' Video: Exclusive|work=Billboard|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Velour's makeup and look transformations have been featured in publications such as ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/sasha-velour-rupaul-drag-race-karl-lagerfeld-celebrity-style/amp|title=Sasha Velour From RuPaul's Drag Race Season 9 on Her Style Icons and Winning the Title|website=Vogue|access-date=June 29, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com/style-beauty/beauty/a10017266/sasha-velour-makeup-transformation/|title=You Have to See Sasha Velour's Stunning Makeup Transformation|date=June 13, 2017|work=Cosmopolitan|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en}}</ref> ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2017/06/sasha-velour-rupauls-drag-race-winner|title=RuPaul's Drag Race Winner Sasha Velour on That Shocking Finale and the Britney Spears Stunt You Didn't See|last=Desta|first=Yohana|work=HWD|access-date=July 3, 2017|language=en}}</ref> and ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lifestyle/7834060/rock-the-look-rupauls-drag-race-sasha-velour|title=Rock the Look: 'RuPaul's Drag Race' Finalist Sasha Velour is a Master at Recreating This Iconic Look|work=Billboard|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Steinberg has further created, produced, and organized different photoshoots, collages, and drawings that discuss art and drag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sashavelour.com/work|title=Home|website=Sasha Velour|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Comics and design ===\nSteinberg's comics and illustrations have appeared in The Nib, InkBRICK,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://inkbrick.com/post/141516785392/from-what-now-by-sasha-steinberg-in-ink-brick|title=INK BRICK \u2013 From \"What Now\" by Sasha Steinberg&nbsp;in INK BRICK...|last=BRICK|first=INK|work=INK BRICK|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Comics Workbook Magazine,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.copaceticcomics.com/comics/comics-workbook-magazine-2|title=Comics Workbook Magazine #2 by Frank Santoro, Andrew White, Zach Mason, Warren Craghead III, Lala Albert, Whit Taylor, Jen Rickert, Derek Badman, Evie Cahir|publisher=copaceticcomics.com|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> QU33R,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://begallerynyc.tumblr.com/pastexhibitions|title=Past Exhibitions|website=begallerynyc.tumblr.com|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref> Cicada Magazine<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cicadamag.com/thisissue/artist-allies-sasha-velour|title=Artist Allies: Sasha Velour|publisher=cicadamag.com|access-date=June 24, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601142947/http://www.cicadamag.com/thisissue/artist-allies-sasha-velour|archivedate=June 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and others, under the names Sasha Velour and Sasha Steinberg.&nbsp;Steinberg also created a series of comics entitled \"Stonewall\", which told the story of the [[Stonewall riots]] from multiple viewpoints. The series was called \"a smart, beautiful and artful take on a significant and difficult historical event\" by Highlow Comics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://highlowcomics.blogspot.nl/2013/11/thirty-days-of-ccs-3-sasha-steinberg.html|title=Thirty Days of CCS #3: Sasha Steinberg|website=highlowcomics.blogspot.nl|date=November 3, 2013|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nA solo gallery show of Steinberg's illustration work, \"Nightrooms\", was held at the Black Box Gallery in&nbsp;[[Brooklyn]]&nbsp;in March 2016&nbsp;and Steinberg's cut paper work was part of the group show \"Coney Island Babies, Visual Artists from the Brooklyn Drag Scene\" at the Bureau of General Services Queer Division that opened in&nbsp;[[Manhattan]] in November 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bgsqd.com/strange-loop-gallery-hosts-the-bureau-of-general-services-queer-division-pop-up-shop/|title=Strange Loop Gallery Hosts The Bureau of General Services\u2014Queer Division Pop-Up Shop : BGSQD {{!}} The Bureau of General Services \u2013 Queer Division|website=bgsqd.com|access-date=May 7, 2018}}</ref> In March 2017, Steinberg designed a long sleeve T-shirt for \"Contemporary Drag\", a limited-edition fashion line for the&nbsp;[[New Art Dealers Alliance]]'s (NADA) in collaboration with Print All Over Me.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ma.de/nada-x-poam-contemporary-drag-collection/|title=NADA x PAOM: Contemporary Drag collection {{!}} MADE|date=February 23, 2017|work=MADE|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Velour, The Drag Magazine'' ===\nSteinberg founded ''Velour, The Drag Magazine'' (originally named ''Vym''), a bi-yearly publication about drag, alongside partner Johnny in the summer of 2014.<ref name=\"Merli\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/arts-entertainment/local/2017-06-27/urbana-native-uni-alum-wins-season-9-rupauls-drag-race.html|title=Urbana native, Uni alum wins Season 9 of 'RuPaul's Drag Race'|last=Merli|first=Melissa|date=June 27, 2017|work=News-Gazette|access-date=October 7, 2017|location=Champaign, IL}}</ref> Steinberg serves as the magazine's artistic director. The first issue (\"What is Drag?\") was released June 2015&nbsp;and the second issue (\"Realness\") was released in October 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/velour-issue-two-realness_us_580a70cce4b02444efa366a8|title=This Beautiful Drag Magazine Is Providing A Comprehensive Guide To 'Realness'|last=Nichols|first=James Michael|date=October 22, 2016|work=HuffPost|access-date=June 24, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> The magazine includes interviews as well as varied art forms such as photography, poetry, and illustration that address the power, beauty, and purpose of drag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thedragmagazine.com/about-2/|title=About|website=VELOUR {{!}} The Drag Magazine|access-date=June 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===''Nightgowns''===\nSince August 2015, Velour has produced ''Nightgowns'', a monthly drag show in Brooklyn.&nbsp;The events have been regularly hosted at Bizarre Bushwick and National Sawdust. The shows have been celebrated as \"beautiful and funny and politically charged\" by ''The New York Times''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/06/24/arts/gay-pride-new-york-all-drag-weekend.html|title=It's Gay Pride Weekend: Dress the Part|last=Piepenburg|first=Erik|date=June 23, 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 24, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>[[File:Sasha Velour at Dragcon by dvsross.jpg|thumb|Velour at [[RuPaul's DragCon NYC]], in 2018.|alt=|291x291px]]\n\nIn 2020, Velour will star in her own [[Quibi]] show, ''NightGowns'', which will follow Velour across eight episodes as she transforms Nightgowns into a full-blown stage act.<ref name=\"quibi\">{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/02/06/sasha-velour-nightgowns-teaser-trailer-quibi/|title=Watch Sasha Velour lead drag revolution in NightGowns Quibi series teaser|last=Nolfi|first=Joey|work=Ew.com|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===''RuPaul's Drag Race''===\nVelour tried out for [[RuPaul's Drag Race|''RuPaul's Drag Race'']]'s eighth season, but was not selected for the lineup.<ref name=\"Rudolph2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newnownext.com/sasha-velour-drag-race-season-9-audition/06/2017/?xrs=synd_facebook_logo|title=Sasha Velour on Being Picked For 'Drag Race': \"I Was Shocked I Got On\"|last1=Rudolph|first1=Christopher|date=June 29, 2017|accessdate=June 30, 2017|publisher=NewNowNext}}</ref> In March 2017, she was announced as one of 14 contestants on the ninth season of&nbsp;the show.&nbsp;In June 2017, Sasha Velour was crowned the winner of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/06/25/534313492/rupauls-drag-race-winner-sasha-velour-cut-from-a-different-fabric|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Winner Sasha Velour Cut From A Different Fabric|publisher=NPR|access-date=June 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vogue.com/article/sasha-velour-rupaul-drag-race-karl-lagerfeld-celebrity-style|title=Sasha Velour From RuPaul's Drag Race on Her Style Icons and How to Be a Queen|work=Vogue|access-date=June 29, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Allison Shoemaker of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' named Velour's lipsync to [[Whitney Houston]]'s \"[[So Emotional]]\" in the season finale as the best TV performance of 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/looking-for-the-performance-of-the-year-watch-2-minute-1821318303/amp|title=Looking for the performance of the year? Watch 2 minutes of RuPaul's Drag Race|author=Shoemaker, Allison|date=December 26, 2017|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=December 26, 2017|publisher=Onion, Inc.}}</ref> Her lip sync was later referenced on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', during [[Kate McKinnon]]'s impression of [[Elizabeth Warren]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2019/10/saturday-night-live-elizabeth-warren-town-hall|title=Saturday Night Live: Bow Down to Kate McKinnon's Elizabeth Warren|last=Valby|first=Karen|date=October 13, 2019|website=Vanity Fair|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/10/14/saturday-night-live-snl-elizabeth-warren-kate-mckinnon/|title=Kate McKinnon served Sasha Velour and Elizabeth Warren realness on SNL and it's everything|last=Smith|first=Reiss|date=October 14, 2019|website=PinkNews|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==== After ''Drag Race'' ====\nFollowing ''Drag Race'', Steinberg continued to work as a drag queen and expanded into the fashion industry. They selected 40 LGBT+ models to walk for [[Opening Ceremony (brand)|Opening Ceremony]] in the 2018 [[New York Fashion Week]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cms.intomore.com/was-this-new-york-fashion-week-the-queerest-season-ever/|title=INTO: A Digital Magazine For The Modern Queer World|website=cms.intomore.com|language=en|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/comprehensive-guide-most-show-stopping-220144705.html|title=A Comprehensive Guide to the Most Show-Stopping Moments of New York Fashion Week|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ulmhawkeyeonline.com/23701/freestyle/top-3-nyfw-collections/|title=Top 3 NYFW collections|last=Dennis|first=Ethan|work=The Hawkeye|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-US}}</ref> Steinberg attended [[Rihanna]]'s fourth annual Diamond Ball in September 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/gallery/rihanna-fourth-annual-diamond-ball|title=Rihanna Hosted a Wild Black-Tie Ball for a Good Cause|last=McCarthy|first=Lauren|work=W Magazine|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/diamond-ball-2018-issa-rae-normani-more-rihannas-influence-1143443|title=Issa Rae, Normani and More Stars Talk Rihanna's Influence at Diamond Ball|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 2017, Steinberg's artwork of German singer-actress [[Marlene Dietrich]] was used as a [[Google Doodle]] on the performer's 116th birthday on December 27, 2017. Steinberg had previously impersonated Dietrich on ''Drag Race'' in the \"[[Snatch Game]]\" challenge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bustle.com/p/sasha-velour-drew-marlene-dietrichs-google-doodle-because-this-rupauls-drag-race-winner-is-incredibly-talented-7702991|title=You've Been Seeing 'Drag Race' Winner Sasha Velour's Artwork All Day & Didn't Even Realize|last=Roberts|first=Amy|website=Bustle|language=en|access-date=2019-02-15}}</ref>\n\nOn December 7, 2018 Steinberg participated in The Long Conversation at the Smithsonian in Washington D.C.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2018/12/09/smithsonian-brings-big-thinkers-alfre-woodard-sasha-velour-together-long-conversation/?noredirect=on|title=Smithsonian brings together big thinkers \u2014 from Alfre Woodard to Sasha Velour \u2014 for a 'long conversation'|work=Washington Post|access-date=2019-03-23|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n{{As of|2013}}, Steinberg resides in Brooklyn, New York, with partner John Jacob Lee (also known as Johnny Velour) and their pet [[Italian Greyhound|Italian greyhound]], Vanya.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bedfordandbowery.com/2015/12/sasha-velour-talks-vym-a-magazine-spotlighting-the-revolutionary-art-of-drag/|title=Sasha Velour Talks Vym, a Magazine Spotlighting the 'Revolutionary' Art of Drag|work=Bedford + Bowery|access-date=July 3, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> Steinberg is [[genderqueer]] and does not have any preferred pronouns when not in drag. Their drag persona, Sasha Velour, is referred to as 'she'.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/sasha_velour/status/830305619886366720|title=Thank so much for asking @glassarmy! For my Velour self\u2014always she/her (out of drag its even less binary lol...any will do) #genderqueer|last=Velour|first=Sasha|date=February 10, 2017|website=@sasha_velour|access-date=March 19, 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=April 2018}}{{Primary source inline|date=May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSteinberg has a shaved head. As Sasha, she often performs in drag bald as a tribute to her mother, Jane Hedges, who died of cancer in 2015 and had lost her hair during treatment for the disease.<ref name=\"Merli\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''\n| Herself (Contestant)\n| [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)|Season 9]] (Winner)\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Broad City]]''\n| Herself\n|Guest Appearance\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[The Bold Type]]''\n| Herself \n| Guest Appearance\n|}\n\n===Web Series===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race#Untucked|Untucked]]''\n| Herself\n| Season 9\n|-\n|2020\n|''The Pit Stop''<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rGqCzcSZzs4|title=Bob The Drag Queen & Sasha Velour Recap the Premiere {{!}} The Pit Stop S12 E1 {{!}} RuPaul\u2019s Drag Race|publisher=[[VH1]]|date=February 29, 2020|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n| Herself\n| Season 12, Episode 1\n|-\n|2020\n|''NightGowns''<ref name=\"quibi\"></ref>\n|Herself\n|[[Quibi]] original\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" <!-- Do not center -->\n|- <!-- Never add unnecessary background colors -->\n! Year\n! Award Giving Body\n! Category\n! Work\n! Results\n! Ref.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|2020\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|[[Queerty|The Queerties]]\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|Drag Royalty\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|Herself\n| {{Nominated}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\"|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/Queerties2020/|title='The 2020 Queerties|work=Cheat Sheet|date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[LGBT culture in New York City]]\n* [[List of self-identified LGBTQ New Yorkers]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Sasha Velour}}\n* {{Official website|http://sashavelour.com/}}\n\n{{RuPaul's Drag Race}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Velour, Sasha}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian descent]]\n[[Category:American drag queens]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:New York City nightlife]]\n[[Category:RuPaul's Drag Race winners|Sasha Velour]]\n[[Category:Vassar College alumni]]\n[[Category:Fulbright Scholars]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Genderqueer people]]\n[[Category:People with non-binary gender identities]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:LGBT comics creators]]\n", "name_user": "64.180.246.84", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Edited some pronouns)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sasha_Velour"}
{"title_page": "Subway Series", "text_new": "{{for|the ice hockey tournament|Subway Super Series}}\n{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| name = Subway Series\n| image = [[File:161st Street Yankee Stadium IRT Jerome southbound platform 2009 Yankee Stadium.JPG|300px]]\n| caption = The view of [[Yankee Stadium]] from the adjacent [[New York City Subway]] station; both the Yankees' and Mets' home grounds are accessible via the subway.\n| team1 = New York Yankees\n| team2 = New York Mets\n| team3 = New York Giants\n| team4 = Brooklyn Dodgers\n| team1logo = NewYorkYankees caplogo.svg\n| team2logo = New York Mets Insignia.svg\n| team3logo = New York Giants Cap (1948 - 1957).png\n| team4logo = BrooklynDodgersCapInsignia.jpg\n| firstmeeting = October 5, 1921 ([[1921 World Series|World Series]], between the Giants and Yankees)<br />October 1, 1941 ([[1941 World Series|World Series]], between the Dodgers and Yankees)<br />June 16, 1997 (regular season, between the Mets and Yankees)\n| mostrecent = July 3, 2019 (between the Mets and Yankees)\n| nextmeeting = July 7, 2020 (between the Mets and Yankees)\n| total = 188 (84 World Series, 104 regular season)<br />36 (all World Series, between the Giants and Yankees)<br />43 (all World Series, between the Dodgers and Yankees)<br />109 (5 World Series, 104 regular season between the Mets and Yankees)\n| most wins =\n| regularseason = 60\u201344, Yankees (over Mets)\n| longeststreak = {{Plainlist|\n* Mets: 6 (May 27, 2013\u2013May 13, 2014)\n* Yankees: 7 (June 30, 2002\u2013June 29, 2003)\n}}\n| largestvictory = {{Plainlist|\n* Giants: 13\u20135 (October 7, 1921\u2013World Series)\n* Dodgers: 13\u20138 (October 5, 1956\u2013World Series)\n* Mets: 12\u20132 (June 9, 2000\u2013regular season)\n* Yankees: 18\u20134 (over Giants, October 2, 1936\u2013World Series)<br />9\u20130 (over Dodgers, October 10, 1956\u2013World Series)<br />15\u20130 (over Mets, June 14, 2009\u2013regular season)\n}}\n| currentstreak = 1, Mets (over Yankees)\n| section_header = Post-season history\n| section_info = {{Plainlist|class=nowrap|\n* [[1921 World Series]]: Giants defeat Yankees, 5\u20133\n* [[1922 World Series]]: Giants defeat Yankees, 4\u20130\n* [[1923 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Giants, 4\u20132\n* [[1936 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Giants, 4\u20132\n* [[1937 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Giants, 4\u20131\n* [[1941 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20131\n* [[1947 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20133\n* [[1949 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20131\n* [[1951 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Giants, 4\u20132\n* [[1952 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20133\n* [[1953 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20132\n* [[1955 World Series]]: Dodgers defeat Yankees, 4\u20133\n* [[1956 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20133\n* [[2000 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Mets, 4\u20131\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Subway Series''' is a series of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) [[Major League Baseball rivalries|rivalry]] games played between the two teams based in [[New York City]], the [[New York Yankees|Yankees]] and the [[New York Mets|Mets]]. Previously, this applied to the Giants and Dodgers as well, before they moved out of New York City. Every historic and current venue for such games has been accessible via the [[New York City Subway]], hence the name of the series.\n\nThe term's historic usage has been in reference to [[World Series]] games played between the city's teams. The [[New York Yankees]] have appeared in all Subway Series games as they have been the only [[American League]] (AL) team based in the city, and have compiled an 11\u20133 all-time series record in the 14 championship Subway Series.\n\nSince 1997, the term '''Subway Series''' has been applied to [[interleague play]] during the regular season between the Yankees and New York City's [[National League]] (NL) team: the [[New York Mets]]. The Mets and Yankees also played each other in the [[2000 World Series]], in which the Yankees won.\n\n==19th century Trolley Series==\n{{main article|1889 World Series}}\n{{see also|Dodgers\u2013Giants rivalry}}\nAlthough organized games between all-stars from New York teams against all-stars from Brooklyn teams date back to the 1850s, the first actual New York-Brooklyn \"[[World Series|World Championship Series]]\" occurred in 1889, a full nine years before Brooklyn was incorporated into the City of New York by the Greater New York Act of 1898, when the [[New York Giants (NL)|New York Giants]] squared off against (and defeated) the [[Brooklyn Bridegrooms]], also called the \"[[Trolley dodger|Trolley Dodgers]]\", of the [[American Association (19th century)|American Association]]. The following season, Brooklyn withdrew from the Association and joined the League, setting the stage for many future intra-city competitions.\n\nSome{{who|date=July 2015}} might argue that the 1889 Series would qualify as a \"Trolley Series\", but would not qualify as a Subway Series since [[Early history of the IRT subway|New York's subway did not open until 1904]].\n\nThe [[1906 World Series]] between the Chicago Cubs and the Chicago White Sox is also loosely referred to as a Subway Series, though the term Crosstown Series is more commonly used. The term is also inaccurate, since Chicago had surface systems from 1892 till the building of the State Street Subway in 1943.\n\n==Early and mid-20th century Subway Series==\nBy the 1920s, the [[New York City Subway|subway]] had become an important form of public transport in the city and provided a convenient form of travel between the three city ballparks: the [[Polo Grounds]], in upper [[Manhattan]]; [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]], in [[the Bronx]]; and [[Ebbets Field]] in [[Brooklyn]]. The 155th Street [[155th Street (IRT Ninth Avenue Line)|elevated]] and [[155th Street (IND Concourse Line)|subway]] stations, the [[161st Street \u2013 Yankee Stadium (New York City Subway)|161st Street]] station, and the [[Prospect Park (BMT Brighton Line)|Prospect Park]]<nowiki/> respectively, served the ballparks. (New York's subway and elevated systems\u2014the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|IRT]], [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company|BRT]]/[[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation|BMT]], and [[Independent Subway System|IND]]\u2014were in competition with each other until 1940.)\n\nIn the case of the World Series contests listed, the entire Series could be attended by using the subway. The date of the first usage of the term \"Subway Series\" is uncertain. The term \"Nickel Series\" (a nickel was the [[New York City transit fares#Fare history|old subway fare]]) appeared in newspapers by 1927, and \"Subway Series\" appeared by 1928.<ref>[http://www.barrypopik.com/index.php/new_york_city/entry/subway_series/]</ref> \"Subway Series\" was clearly already a familiar concept by 1934, as discussed in this article about that year's All-Star Game to be held in New York, discussing the \"subway series\" possibility for the Giants and Yankees. (Ultimately, no New York team made it to the 1934 post-season.).<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=New York Times|title=Terry and Cronin Select Squads For All-Star Game Here Tuesday|date=July 4, 1934|agency=Associated Press|page=21}}</ref>\n\n===Yankees\u2013Giants===\n{{main article|1921 World Series|1922 World Series|1923 World Series|1936 World Series|1937 World Series|1951 World Series|Giants\u2013Yankees rivalry}}\nThe 1921 and 1922 match-ups were played in a single ballpark, as both the [[History of the New York Giants (NL)|Giants]] and Yankees then played at the Polo Grounds. The Giants won both of these World Series against the Yankees, the first two Subway Series played. Despite cordial relations just a few years before when the Yankees allowed the Giants to share their home at [[Hilltop Park]] for a year in 1911 and the Giants more than returning the favor in kind by sharing Polo Grounds with the Yankees since 1913, the Yankees were issued an eviction notice in mid-1920 ending their lease after the 1922 season. The Yankees opened their new ballpark in 1923. Fortunes changed immediately for the Yankees as they defeated the Giants this time in the third straight year of World Series competition between the two teams. Their new home would host the Yankees' first of 11 Subway World Series victories that year and first of an unprecedented 26 World Series until the stadium closed in 2008.\n\nThe venues for the 1923, 1936, 1937, and 1951 World Series&mdash;the Polo Grounds and [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|the old Yankee Stadium]]&mdash;were a short walk apart across the [[Macombs Dam Bridge]] over the [[Harlem River]]. <!--Of course, anyone in the city not living in that vicinity could have opted for the subway system.-->\n\n===Yankees\u2013Dodgers===\n{{main article|1941 World Series|1947 World Series|1949 World Series|1952 World Series|1953 World Series|1955 World Series|1956 World Series|Dodgers\u2013Yankees rivalry}}\nThe term was used again in 1941 when the [[History of the Brooklyn Dodgers|Dodgers]] made their first [[World Series]] appearance since 1920. Multiple Hall of Famers took part in these contests between the \"Bronx Bombers\" and \"Dem Bums from Brooklyn\" and the games involved numerous achievements including [[Jackie Robinson]] breaking the color barrier as the first African-American baseball player in the World Series and [[Don Larsen]]'s performance in pitching the only [[Perfect game (baseball)|perfect game]] in post-season history. The seven matchups between the Yankees and the Dodgers between 1941 and 1956 cemented the term as being mostly associated with the New York vs. Brooklyn contests, during the time when New York City was retroactively dubbed by historians as \"The Capital of Baseball\".<ref>{{cite video\n | people =\n | title = Baseball: A Film by Ken Burns; ''Inning 7: The Capital of Baseball''\n | medium = Television Documentary\n | publisher = PBS\n | location =\n | date =\n | url =https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/baseball/capital/ }}</ref> Despite Brooklyn's repeated success at winning the National League pennant, it was only able to win one World Series (1955) against the Yankees.\n\n===World Series matchups===\nThe all-New York match-ups in [[World Series]] play during this period been the following:\n\n{{legend|#d0e7ff|National League team}}\n\n{{legend|#fcc|American League team}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Year\n!scope=\"col\"|Winning team\n!scope=\"col\"|Manager\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"|Games\n!scope=\"col\"|Losing team\n!scope=\"col\"|Manager\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Ref.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1921}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1921 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|John|McGraw}} ||5\u20133{{ref label|BestOf9|V|V}}||align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1921 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Miller|Huggins}} || |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1921_WS.shtml|title=1921 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1922}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1922 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|John|McGraw}} ||4\u20130&ndash;(1){{ref label|TieGame|T|T}}||align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1922 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Miller|Huggins}} || |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1922_WS.shtml|title=1922 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1923}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1923 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Miller|Huggins}} || |4\u20132||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1923 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]||align=left