ason|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Burt|Shotton}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1947_WS.shtml|title=1947 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1949}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1949 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20131||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1949 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Burt|Shotton}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1949_WS.shtml|title=1949 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1951}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1951 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20132||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1951 New York Giants (MLB) season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|Leo|Durocher}} || <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1951_WS.shtml|title=1951 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1952}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1952 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20133||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1952 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Charlie|Dressen}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1952_WS.shtml|title=1952 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1953}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1953 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20132||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1953 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Charlie|Dressen}} || <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1953_WS.shtml|title=1953 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1955}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1955 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Walter|Alston}} ||4\u20133||align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1955 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1955_WS.shtml|title=1955 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1956}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1956 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20133||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1956 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Walter|Alston}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1956_WS.shtml|title=1956 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|2000}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[2000 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Joe|Torre}} || |4\u20131||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[2000 New York Mets season|New York Mets]]{{ref label|WildCard|W|W}}||align=left |{{sortname|Bobby|Valentine}} || <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2000_WS.shtml|title=2000 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Exhibition series==\nIn addition to the five World Series played between the Yankees and Giants before 1940, the two teams also played exhibition series against each other from time to time. The match-ups were known as the \"City Series\" and were sometimes played in October while other teams played in the World Series.  However, after 1940, this became difficult because the Yankees would routinely appear in the World Series. In the 17 years from 1941 to 1957 (after which the Giants and Dodgers left New York City for California), the Yankees appeared in the World Series 12 times, failing to reach the Series only in 1944, 1945, 1946, 1948, and 1954.\n\nBefore New York's two National League teams left the city, the Yankees and Dodgers played an annual midseason exhibition game called the Mayor's Trophy Game to benefit sandlot baseball in New York City. The proceeds raised by the Yankees were given to leagues in Manhattan and the Bronx, while proceeds raised by the Dodgers went to leagues on Long Island and Staten Island.  The annual charity event was discontinued following the 1957 season, when the Dodgers moved to Los Angeles and the Giants moved to San Francisco. leaving the Yankees as the only major league team in the city. The game was revived in 1963, after the National League returned to New York with the expansion New York Mets in 1962.  After dwindling interest and public bickering between the owners of both teams, the Mayor's Trophy Game was discontinued following the 1983 season. It was revived again as a pre-[[Opening Day]] series titled the \"Mayor's Challenge\" and held in 1989.\n\n==Modern usage==\n[[File:Subway Series 2008.jpg|thumb|250px|Subway Series 2008, [[Johnny Damon]] with the Yankees (left) and [[Brian Schneider]] with the Mets]]\n[[File:Subway Series 2009.jpg|thumb|250px|A full house at the new [[Yankee Stadium]] for a Subway Series game against the Mets on June 13, 2009. The Mets won the game 6-2.]]\n{{see also|Mets\u2013Yankees rivalry}}\n\nIn modern usage, the term \"Subway Series\" generally refers to a series played between the two current New York baseball teams, the [[New York Yankees]] and the [[New York Mets]]. Their stadiums remain directly accessible by subway: [[Yankee Stadium]] via the [[161st Street\u2013Yankee Stadium (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|161st Street\u2013Yankee Stadium]] station, and [[Citi Field]] via the [[Mets\u2013Willets Point (IRT Flushing Line)|Mets\u2013Willets Point]] station. It can also refer to any time two New York City-based teams play each other, such as the [[New York Knicks|Knicks]] and [[Brooklyn Nets|Nets]] in the [[NBA]], and the [[New York Rangers|Rangers]] and [[New York Islanders|Islanders]] in the [[NHL]]. All of these teams' venues are easily accessible via the New York City Subway as well.\n\nWith the departure of the Dodgers and Giants in the 1950s New York was left without a crosstown rivalry. Even with the Mets joining MLB they were placed in the National League opposite of the Yankees. When interleague play was introduced in 1997 the teams finally got to play one another in a competitive fashion. The rivalry has included heated moments such as the Roger Clemens and Mike Piazza feud. Currently the Yankees lead the \"Subway Series\" 71-55 all time. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1213554-yankees-mets-and-the-10-best-rivalries-in-baseball-today|title=Yankees-Mets and the 10 Best Rivalries in Baseball Today|last=Rymer|first=Zachary|date=|website=Bleacher Report|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===2000 World Series===\n{{main article|2000 World Series}}\nThe name \"Subway Series\" was commonly applied to the [[2000 World Series]] between the [[New York Yankees]] and the [[New York Mets]]. The Yankees won four games to one and celebrated their 26th championship in front of Mets fans at Shea Stadium. This was the only time that visiting teams had ever won a World Series at Shea Stadium. The other two times the World Series ended at Shea Stadium, in {{wsy|1969}} and {{wsy|1986}}, it ended with the Mets winning.\n\nDuring the 2000 World Series, the City of New York decorated some of the trains that ran on the '''{{NYCS service|7}}''' train (which went to [[Shea Stadium]] in [[Queens]], home of the Mets) and '''{{NYCS service|4}}''' train (which went to [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|the old Yankee Stadium]] in the Bronx, home of the Yankees). The '''7''' trains were blue and orange and featured the Mets version of the \"NY\" logo, and the '''4''' trains were white with blue pinstripes and featured the Yankees version of the \"NY\" logo. Also, after each game in the series the city offered free subway rides home for attendees of the game.  Yankee fans displayed signs that read \"Yankees in 4 and not in 7\", predicting that the Yankees would easily dispatch the Mets in a Series sweep as opposed to a difficult, full-length Series.  The signs had the '''4''' in a dark green circle designating the number '''4''' train, and the '''7''' in a purple circle designating the number '''7''' train.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Giants\u2013Jets rivalry]]\n* [[Islanders\u2013Rangers rivalry]]\n* [[Devils\u2013Rangers rivalry]]\n* [[Knicks\u2013Nets rivalry]]\n* [[Hudson River Derby]]\n\n==Notes==\n* {{note label|TieGame|T|T}} The 1907, 1912, and 1922 World Series each included one [[Tie (draw)|tied game]].\n* {{note label|BestOf9|V|V}} The 1903, 1919, 1920, and 1921 World Series were in a [[Playoff format#Best-of-nine playoff|best-of-nine format]] (carried by the first team to win five games).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mlb.mlb.com/NASApp/mlb/mlb/history/postseason/mlb_ws_recaps.jsp?feature=2000 2000 Subway Series Recap on MLB.com]\n* [http://espn.go.com/classic/s/series_subway_moments.html Great Subway Series moments]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/images/2000/10/21/sports/baseball/sseries_hist_001020_05.html History of the Subway Series from the NY Times]\n* [http://mrudolf.tripod.com/subway/ The Subway Series (and Other Inter-Urban Series)]\n* [http://sports.newsday.com/long-island/baseball/yankees-mets-subway-series/ Subway Series Yankees vs. Mets history and boxscores from Newsday]\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{New York City Subway}}\n{{Subway Series}}\n{{New York Yankees}}\n{{New York Mets}}\n{{San Francisco Giants}}\n{{Los Angeles Dodgers}}\n{{Major League Baseball on NBC}}\n{{Navboxes|title = Championship Navigation Boxes|list1=\n{{1921 New York Giants}}\n{{1922 New York Giants}}\n{{1923 New York Yankees}}\n{{1936 New York Yankees}}\n{{1937 New York Yankees}}\n{{1941 New York Yankees}}\n{{1947 New York Yankees}}\n{{1949 New York Yankees}}\n{{1951 New York Yankees}}\n{{1952 New York Yankees}}\n{{1953 New York Yankees}}\n{{1955 Brooklyn Dodgers}}\n{{1956 New York Yankees}}\n{{2000 New York Yankees}}\n}}\n{{MLB rivalries}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball in New York City]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Dodgers]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees]]\n[[Category:New York Giants (NL)]]\n[[Category:New York Mets]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball rivalries]]\n[[Category:Interleague play]]\n[[Category:Sports in the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the ice hockey tournament|Subway Super Series}}\n{{Infobox sports rivalry\n| name = Subway Series\n| image = [[File:161st Street Yankee Stadium IRT Jerome southbound platform 2009 Yankee Stadium.JPG|300px]]\n| caption = The view of [[Yankee Stadium]] from the adjacent [[New York City Subway]] station; both the Yankees' and Mets' home grounds are accessible via the subway.\n| team1 = New York Yankees\n| team2 = New York Mets\n| team3 = New York Giants\n| team4 = Brooklyn Dodgers\n| team1logo = NewYorkYankees caplogo.svg\n| team2logo = New York Mets Insignia.svg\n| team3logo = New York Giants Cap (1948 - 1957).png\n| team4logo = BrooklynDodgersCapInsignia.jpg\n| firstmeeting = October 5, 1921 ([[1921 World Series|World Series]], between the Giants and Yankees)<br />October 1, 1941 ([[1941 World Series|World Series]], between the Dodgers and Yankees)<br />June 16, 1997 (regular season, between the Mets and Yankees)\n| mostrecent = July 3, 2019 (between the Mets and Yankees)\n| nextmeeting = July 7, 2020 (between the Mets and Yankees)\n| total = 188 (84 World Series, 104 regular season)<br />36 (all World Series, between the Giants and Yankees)<br />43 (all World Series, between the Dodgers and Yankees)<br />109 (5 World Series, 104 regular season between the Mets and Yankees)\n| most wins =\n| regularseason = 60\u201344, Yankees (over Mets)\n| longeststreak = {{Plainlist|\n* Mets: 6 (May 27, 2013\u2013May 13, 2014)\n* Yankees: 7 (June 30, 2002\u2013June 29, 2003)\n}}\n| largestvictory = {{Plainlist|\n* Giants: 13\u20135 (October 7, 1921\u2013World Series)\n* Dodgers: 13\u20138 (October 5, 1956\u2013World Series)\n* Mets: 12\u20132 (June 9, 2000\u2013regular season)\n* Yankees: 18\u20134 (over Giants, October 2, 1936\u2013World Series)<br />9\u20130 (over Dodgers, October 10, 1956\u2013World Series)<br />15\u20130 (over Mets, June 14, 2009\u2013regular season)\n}}\n| currentstreak = 1, Mets (over Yankees)\n| section_header = Post-season history\n| section_info = {{Plainlist|class=nowrap|\n* [[1921 World Series]]: Giants defeat Yankees, 5\u20133\n* [[1922 World Series]]: Giants defeat Yankees, 4\u20130\n* [[1923 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Giants, 4\u20132\n* [[1936 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Giants, 4\u20132\n* [[1937 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Giants, 4\u20131\n* [[1941 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20131\n* [[1947 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20133\n* [[1949 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20131\n* [[1951 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Giants, 4\u20132\n* [[1952 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20133\n* [[1953 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20132\n* [[1955 World Series]]: Dodgers defeat Yankees, 4\u20133\n* [[1956 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Dodgers, 4\u20133\n* [[2000 World Series]]: Yankees defeat Mets, 4\u20131\n}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Subway Series''' is a series of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) [[Major League Baseball rivalries|rivalry]] games played between the two teams based in [[New York City]], the [[New York Yankees|Yankees]] and the [[New York Mets|Mets]]. Previously, this applied to the Giants and Dodgers as well, before they moved out of New York City. Every historic and current venue for such games has been accessible via the [[New York City Subway]], hence the name of the series.\n\nThe term's historic usage has been in reference to [[World Series]] games played between the city's teams. The [[New York Yankees]] have appeared in all Subway Series games as they have been the only [[American League]] (AL) team based in the city, and have compiled an 11\u20133 all-time series record in the 14 championship Subway Series.\n\nSince 1997, the term '''Subway Series''' has been applied to [[interleague play]] during the regular season between the Yankees and New York City's [[National League]] (NL) team: the [[New York Mets]]. The Mets and Yankees also played each other in the [[2000 World Series]], in which the Yankees won.\n\n==19th century Trolley Series==\n{{main article|1889 World Series}}\n{{see also|Dodgers\u2013Giants rivalry}}\nAlthough organized games between all-stars from New York teams against all-stars from Brooklyn teams date back to the 1850s, the first actual New York-Brooklyn \"[[World Series|World Championship Series]]\" occurred in 1889, a full nine years before Brooklyn was incorporated into the City of New York by the Greater New York Act of 1898, when the [[New York Giants (NL)|New York Giants]] squared off against (and defeated) the [[Brooklyn Bridegrooms]], also called the \"[[Trolley dodger|Trolley Dodgers]]\", of the [[American Association (19th century)|American Association]]. The following season, Brooklyn withdrew from the Association and joined the League, setting the stage for many future intra-city competitions.\n\nSome{{who|date=July 2015}} might argue that the 1889 Series would qualify as a \"Trolley Series\", but would not qualify as a Subway Series since [[Early history of the IRT subway|New York's subway did not open until 1904]].\n\nThe [[1906 World Series]] between the Chicago Cubs and the Chicago White Sox is also loosely referred to as a Subway Series, though the term Crosstown Series is more commonly used. The term is also inaccurate, since Chicago had surface systems from 1892 till the building of the State Street Subway in 1943.\n\n==Early and mid-20th century Subway Series==\nBy the 1920s, the [[New York City Subway|subway]] had become an important form of public transport in the city and provided a convenient form of travel between the three city ballparks: the [[Polo Grounds]], in upper [[Manhattan]]; [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]], in [[the Bronx]]; and [[Ebbets Field]] in [[Brooklyn]]. The 155th Street [[155th Street (IRT Ninth Avenue Line)|elevated]] and [[155th Street (IND Concourse Line)|subway]] stations, the [[161st Street \u2013 Yankee Stadium (New York City Subway)|161st Street]] station, and the [[Prospect Park (BMT Brighton Line)|Prospect Park]]<nowiki/> respectively, served the ballparks. (New York's subway and elevated systems\u2014the [[Interborough Rapid Transit Company|IRT]], [[Brooklyn Rapid Transit Company|BRT]]/[[Brooklyn\u2013Manhattan Transit Corporation|BMT]], and [[Independent Subway System|IND]]\u2014were in competition with each other until 1940.)\n\nIn the case of the World Series contests listed, the entire Series could be attended by using the subway. The date of the first usage of the term \"Subway Series\" is uncertain. The term \"Nickel Series\" (a nickel was the [[New York City transit fares#Fare history|old subway fare]]) appeared in newspapers by 1927, and \"Subway Series\" appeared by 1928.<ref>[http://www.barrypopik.com/index.php/new_york_city/entry/subway_series/]</ref> \"Subway Series\" was clearly already a familiar concept by 1934, as discussed in this article about that year's All-Star Game to be held in New York, discussing the \"subway series\" possibility for the Giants and Yankees. (Ultimately, no New York team made it to the 1934 post-season.).<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=New York Times|title=Terry and Cronin Select Squads For All-Star Game Here Tuesday|date=July 4, 1934|agency=Associated Press|page=21}}</ref>\n\n===Yankees\u2013Giants===\n{{main article|1921 World Series|1922 World Series|1923 World Series|1936 World Series|1937 World Series|1951 World Series|Giants\u2013Yankees rivalry}}\nThe 1921 and 1922 match-ups were played in a single ballpark, as both the [[History of the New York Giants (NL)|Giants]] and Yankees then played at the Polo Grounds. The Giants won both of these World Series against the Yankees, the first two Subway Series played. Despite cordial relations just a few years before when the Yankees allowed the Giants to share their home at [[Hilltop Park]] for a year in 1911 and the Giants more than returning the favor in kind by sharing Polo Grounds with the Yankees since 1913, the Yankees were issued an eviction notice in mid-1920 ending their lease after the 1922 season. The Yankees opened their new ballpark in 1923. Fortunes changed immediately for the Yankees as they defeated the Giants this time in the third straight year of World Series competition between the two teams. Their new home would host the Yankees' first of 11 Subway World Series victories that year and first of an unprecedented 26 World Series until the stadium closed in 2008.\n\nThe venues for the 1923, 1936, 1937, and 1951 World Series&mdash;the Polo Grounds and [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|the old Yankee Stadium]]&mdash;were a short walk apart across the [[Macombs Dam Bridge]] over the [[Harlem River]]. <!--Of course, anyone in the city not living in that vicinity could have opted for the subway system.-->\n\n===Yankees\u2013Dodgers===\n{{main article|1941 World Series|1947 World Series|1949 World Series|1952 World Series|1953 World Series|1955 World Series|1956 World Series|Dodgers\u2013Yankees rivalry}}\nThe term was used again in 1941 when the [[History of the Brooklyn Dodgers|Dodgers]] made their first [[World Series]] appearance since 1920. Multiple Hall of Famers took part in these contests between the \"Bronx Bombers\" and \"Dem Bums from Brooklyn\" and the games involved numerous achievements including [[Jackie Robinson]] breaking the color barrier as the first African-American baseball player in the World Series and [[Don Larsen]]'s performance in pitching the only [[Perfect game (baseball)|perfect game]] in post-season history. The seven matchups between the Yankees and the Dodgers between 1941 and 1956 cemented the term as being mostly associated with the New York vs. Brooklyn contests, during the time when New York City was retroactively dubbed by historians as \"The Capital of Baseball\".<ref>{{cite video\n | people =\n | title = Baseball: A Film by Ken Burns; ''Inning 7: The Capital of Baseball''\n | medium = Television Documentary\n | publisher = PBS\n | location =\n | date =\n | url =https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/baseball/capital/ }}</ref> Despite Brooklyn's repeated success at winning the National League pennant, it was only able to win one World Series (1955) against the Yankees.\n\n===World Series matchups===\nThe all-New York match-ups in [[World Series]] play during this period been the following:\n\n{{legend|#d0e7ff|National League team}}\n\n{{legend|#fcc|American League team}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Year\n!scope=\"col\"|Winning team\n!scope=\"col\"|Manager\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"|Games\n!scope=\"col\"|Losing team\n!scope=\"col\"|Manager\n!scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\"| Ref.\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1921}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1921 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|John|McGraw}} ||5\u20133{{ref label|BestOf9|V|V}}||align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1921 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Miller|Huggins}} || |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1921_WS.shtml|title=1921 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1922}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1922 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|John|McGraw}} ||4\u20130&ndash;(1){{ref label|TieGame|T|T}}||align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1922 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Miller|Huggins}} || |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1922_WS.shtml|title=1922 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1923}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1923 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Miller|Huggins}} || |4\u20132||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1923 New York Giants season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|John|McGraw}} || <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1923_WS.shtml|title=1923 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1936}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1936 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Joe|McCarthy|Joe McCarthy (manager)}} || |4\u20132||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1936 New York Giants (MLB) season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|Bill|Terry}} || <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1936_WS.shtml|title=1936 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1937}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1937 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Joe|McCarthy|Joe McCarthy (manager)}} || |4\u20131||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1937 New York Giants (MLB) season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|Bill|Terry}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1937_WS.shtml|title=1937 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1941}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1941 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Joe|McCarthy|Joe McCarthy (manager)}} || |4\u20131||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"| [[1941 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Leo|Durocher}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1941_WS.shtml|title=1941 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1947}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1947 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Bucky|Harris}} || |4\u20133||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1947 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Burt|Shotton}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1947_WS.shtml|title=1947 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1949}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1949 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20131||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1949 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Burt|Shotton}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1949_WS.shtml|title=1949 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1951}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1951 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20132||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1951 New York Giants (MLB) season|New York Giants]]||align=left|{{sortname|Leo|Durocher}} || <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1951_WS.shtml|title=1951 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1952}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1952 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20133||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1952 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Charlie|Dressen}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1952_WS.shtml|title=1952 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1953}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1953 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20132||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1953 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Charlie|Dressen}} || <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1953_WS.shtml|title=1953 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1955}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1955 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Walter|Alston}} ||4\u20133||align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1955 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1955_WS.shtml|title=1955 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|1956}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[1956 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Casey|Stengel}} || |4\u20133||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[1956 Brooklyn Dodgers season|Brooklyn Dodgers]]||align=left|{{sortname|Walter|Alston}} ||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1956_WS.shtml|title=1956 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" align=left |{{wsy|2000}}\n|align=left style=\"background:#fcc;\"|[[2000 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]||align=left |{{sortname|Joe|Torre}} || |4\u20131||align=left style=\"background:#d0e7ff;\"|[[2000 New York Mets season|New York Mets]]{{ref label|WildCard|W|W}}||align=left |{{sortname|Bobby|Valentine}} || <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2000_WS.shtml|title=2000 World Series|work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=January 2, 2010}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Exhibition series==\nIn addition to the five World Series played between the Yankees and Giants before 1940, the two teams also played exhibition series against each other from time to time. The match-ups were known as the \"City Series\" and were sometimes played in October while other teams played in the World Series.  However, after 1940, this became difficult because the Yankees would routinely appear in the World Series. In the 17 years from 1941 to 1957 (after which the Giants and Dodgers left New York City for California), the Yankees appeared in the World Series 12 times, failing to reach the Series only in 1944, 1945, 1946, 1948, and 1954.\n\nBefore New York's two National League teams left the city, the Yankees and Dodgers played an annual midseason exhibition game called the Mayor's Trophy Game to benefit sandlot baseball in New York City. The proceeds raised by the Yankees were given to leagues in Manhattan and the Bronx, while proceeds raised by the Dodgers went to leagues on Long Island and Staten Island.  The annual charity event was discontinued following the 1957 season, when the Dodgers moved to Los Angeles and the Giants moved to San Francisco. leaving the Yankees as the only major league team in the city. The game was revived in 1963, after the National League returned to New York with the expansion New York Mets in 1962.  After dwindling interest and public bickering between the owners of both teams, the Mayor's Trophy Game was discontinued following the 1983 season. It was revived again as a pre-[[Opening Day]] series titled the \"Mayor's Challenge\" and held in 1989.\n\n==Modern usage==\n[[File:Subway Series 2008.jpg|thumb|250px|Subway Series 2008, [[Johnny Damon]] with the Yankees (left) and [[Brian Schneider]] with the Mets]]\n[[File:Subway Series 2009.jpg|thumb|250px|A full house at the new [[Yankee Stadium]] for a Subway Series game against the Mets on June 13, 2009. The Mets won the game 6-2.]]\n{{see also|Mets\u2013Yankees rivalry}}\n\nIn modern usage, the term \"Subway Series\" generally refers to a series played between the two current New York baseball teams, the [[New York Yankees]] and the [[New York Mets]]. Their stadiums remain directly accessible by subway: [[Yankee Stadium]] via the [[161st Street\u2013Yankee Stadium (IRT Jerome Avenue Line)|161st Street\u2013Yankee Stadium]] station, and [[Citi Field]] via the [[Mets\u2013Willets Point (IRT Flushing Line)|Mets\u2013Willets Point]] station. It can also refer to any time two New York City-based teams play each other, such as the [[New York Knicks|Knicks]] and [[Brooklyn Nets|Nets]] in the [[NBA]], and the [[New York Rangers|Rangers]] and [[New York Islanders|Islanders]] in the [[NHL]]. All of these teams' venues are easily accessible via the New York City Subway as well.\n\n===2000 World Series===\n{{main article|2000 World Series}}\nThe name \"Subway Series\" was commonly applied to the [[2000 World Series]] between the [[New York Yankees]] and the [[New York Mets]]. The Yankees won four games to one and celebrated their 26th championship in front of Mets fans at Shea Stadium. This was the only time that visiting teams had ever won a World Series at Shea Stadium. The other two times the World Series ended at Shea Stadium, in {{wsy|1969}} and {{wsy|1986}}, it ended with the Mets winning.\n\nDuring the 2000 World Series, the City of New York decorated some of the trains that ran on the '''{{NYCS service|7}}''' train (which went to [[Shea Stadium]] in [[Queens]], home of the Mets) and '''{{NYCS service|4}}''' train (which went to [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|the old Yankee Stadium]] in the Bronx, home of the Yankees). The '''7''' trains were blue and orange and featured the Mets version of the \"NY\" logo, and the '''4''' trains were white with blue pinstripes and featured the Yankees version of the \"NY\" logo. Also, after each game in the series the city offered free subway rides home for attendees of the game.  Yankee fans displayed signs that read \"Yankees in 4 and not in 7\", predicting that the Yankees would easily dispatch the Mets in a Series sweep as opposed to a difficult, full-length Series.  The signs had the '''4''' in a dark green circle designating the number '''4''' train, and the '''7''' in a purple circle designating the number '''7''' train.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Giants\u2013Jets rivalry]]\n* [[Islanders\u2013Rangers rivalry]]\n* [[Devils\u2013Rangers rivalry]]\n* [[Knicks\u2013Nets rivalry]]\n* [[Hudson River Derby]]\n\n==Notes==\n* {{note label|TieGame|T|T}} The 1907, 1912, and 1922 World Series each included one [[Tie (draw)|tied game]].\n* {{note label|BestOf9|V|V}} The 1903, 1919, 1920, and 1921 World Series were in a [[Playoff format#Best-of-nine playoff|best-of-nine format]] (carried by the first team to win five games).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mlb.mlb.com/NASApp/mlb/mlb/history/postseason/mlb_ws_recaps.jsp?feature=2000 2000 Subway Series Recap on MLB.com]\n* [http://espn.go.com/classic/s/series_subway_moments.html Great Subway Series moments]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/images/2000/10/21/sports/baseball/sseries_hist_001020_05.html History of the Subway Series from the NY Times]\n* [http://mrudolf.tripod.com/subway/ The Subway Series (and Other Inter-Urban Series)]\n* [http://sports.newsday.com/long-island/baseball/yankees-mets-subway-series/ Subway Series Yankees vs. Mets history and boxscores from Newsday]\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{New York City Subway}}\n{{Subway Series}}\n{{New York Yankees}}\n{{New York Mets}}\n{{San Francisco Giants}}\n{{Los Angeles Dodgers}}\n{{Major League Baseball on NBC}}\n{{Navboxes|title = Championship Navigation Boxes|list1=\n{{1921 New York Giants}}\n{{1922 New York Giants}}\n{{1923 New York Yankees}}\n{{1936 New York Yankees}}\n{{1937 New York Yankees}}\n{{1941 New York Yankees}}\n{{1947 New York Yankees}}\n{{1949 New York Yankees}}\n{{1951 New York Yankees}}\n{{1952 New York Yankees}}\n{{1953 New York Yankees}}\n{{1955 Brooklyn Dodgers}}\n{{1956 New York Yankees}}\n{{2000 New York Yankees}}\n}}\n{{MLB rivalries}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Baseball in New York City]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn Dodgers]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees]]\n[[Category:New York Giants (NL)]]\n[[Category:New York Mets]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball rivalries]]\n[[Category:Interleague play]]\n[[Category:Sports in the New York metropolitan area]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Willster777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModern usage:Adding a little more information on the Mets-Yankees rivalry", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subway_Series"}
